<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: 1995 Annual Report -- Overview</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>1995 Annual Report: Overview</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>

<p>
Fiscal Year 1995 was a year of new beginnings for the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs. <p> 

On January 10, 1995, Gov. Jim Edgar signaled his commitment to advancing economic development in Illinois by appointing Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra as his senior advisor on economic development and giving him responsibility to oversee DCCA's future direction.  In making the appointment, Edgar said, "To ensure the future prosperity of Illinois, state government needs a coordinated, effective and well-managed system of economic development programs.  Bob Kustra is uniquely qualified to lead such a coordinated approach."  The executive order specified that the Director of DCCA reports directly to the Lieutenant Governor and remains ultimately responsible to the Governor.  The order also created the Economic Development Coordinating Council, which includes the heads of more than a dozen state agencies, boards and commissions that impact economic development.  Kustra was named Chairman of the Council by the Governor.<p>

In accepting the new responsibilities, Kustra said, "Illinois, obviously, has what it takes to create and retain jobs.  That's one reason we have more Illinoisans in jobs today than at any point in history.  Yet, we face pressures from other regions of the country and global competition.  We must be ready to take advantage of all opportunities, protect our investment and plan for the future."<p>

A week later, on January 17, 1995, Gov. Edgar named Dennis R. Whetstone as DCCA Director, replacing Jan M. Grayson, who resigned to pursue opportunities in the private sector.<p>

Whetstone, who had served for two years as an Assistant to the Governor for Planning, returned to DCCA where he had honed his skills in economic development for more than 18 years.  Before joining the Governor's staff, Whetstone had served as Executive Deputy Director at DCCA, supervising and coordinating the functions of the Department's bureaus of Program Administration, Marketing, Small Business Assistance, Tourism and Operations.  He also had served as Deputy Director for the Bureau of Program Administration and as manager of Job Training Programs for that bureau.<p>

Gov. Edgar cited Whetstone's expertise in workforce preparation, in particular, when announcing his choice.  "As part of our efforts to retool and re-energize the state's economic development efforts, we have recognized it is crucial Illinois continues to offer highly skilled, strongly motivated workers who have helped make us an economic giant in the nation's heartland."  Kustra added, "Dennis knows the needs of the private sector and shares our goal of making Illinois an even better place to do business.  With his help, we'll make certain that DCCA responds swiftly to opportunities to create and retain jobs in Illinois."<p>

In May, the leadership team expanded with the appointment of Levi Moore as DCCA's Assistant Director.  Moore, who had earlier worked in DCCA's Business Development Bureau, returned to DCCA following two years as a senior associate in the Chicago office of Korn/Ferry International.<p>
  
With these new leaders at the helm, DCCA moved aggressively forward to further Illinois' leadership in the field of economic development.  Through its Industry Development Division, in Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA successfully worked with local economic development officials to offer assistance to companies seeking to locate or expand their facilities in Illinois.  Among companies announcing plans to locate, expand, modernize or renovate their facilities were DeMert & Dougherty, Inc.; Motorola; Independence Tube Corp.; MacLean-Fogg Company; Maytag Corporation; Knapheide Manufacturing Co.; National Steel Corporation; C. J. Vitner Company; U.S. Robotics, Inc.; Cotter & Co.; and IBP, Inc.<p>

DCCA's Small Business Development Center staff counseled 9,348 companies and helped to provide management training to more than 10,000 people.  This assistance helped businesses to create 534 new jobs, retain more than 1,700 jobs, start 379 new businesses, expand 219 businesses, and obtain more than $52 million in business financing.  The Procurement Technical Assistance Centers helped Illinois firms secure more than $164 million in government contracts, while more than 1,700 small businesses received exporting assistance through the International Trade Centers and NAFTA Opportunity Centers.<p>

DCCA continued with the development of the First-Stop Business Information Center of Illinois, a statewide program designed to make it easier for entrepreneurs and business people to learn about and comply with state requirements.<p>  

The Office of Women's Business Development, created in Fiscal Year 1994, established a firm foundation during Fiscal Year 1995, working to promote greater understanding of the women's business community by helping women entrepreneurs tackle the wide range of challenges they confront, as well as providing administrative support to the Illinois Women's Business Ownership Council.<p>

The Loan Administration Division continued its important work consolidating DCCA's business loan programs, thus lessening confusion for loan applicants.  In Fiscal Year 1995, the Division analyzed more than 100 applications totaling $36.8 million.  The Division also continued to administer the Participation Loan Program, funding 13 loans totaling $2.9 million, which leveraged approximately $15.3 million in private investment, and enabled businesses to create or retain nearly 1,500 jobs.<p>

DCCA expanded its efforts to make information readily available on the "Information Highway" through Access Illinois, a 24-hour on-line information bulletin board service that links government agencies with trade associations and business organizations.  As one of the charter subscribers to Access Illinois, DCCA provides interested people with access to agency publications, newsletters, program descriptions and other information.  During Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA also began working with Access Illinois toward development of a Department "home page" on the Internet.<p>

DCCA also continued to fine-tune its efforts to help Illinois businesses achieve success in the global marketplace.  Through the International Business Division, DCCA provided assistance to 27 Illinois exhibitors at foreign trade shows; provided international marketing assistance to 600 Illinois companies; represented 534 companies at catalog shows; and co-sponsored more than 55 export development seminars, conferences or workshops. <p> 

Fiscal Year 1995 saw DCCA working closely with the business and labor communities to promote positive labor-management relations in Illinois.  In addition to providing 11 labor-management grants totaling $287,800 to support cooperative labor-management programs in the state, DCCA also worked with the Illinois Labor-Management Cooperation Committee to promote and encourage adoption of cooperative workplace programs.  A special "Labor-Management Partners:  On the Road to High Performance" award was developed to highlight and recognize Illinois employer organizations that demonstrate positive labor-management relations and cooperative work strategies.<p>  

DCCA continued its efforts to assist Illinois businesses in finding and implementing new technologies and modern business practices that help them remain competitive.  After leading the successful effort to secure a $1.4 million grant from the National Institute of Standards and Technology, DCCA's Office of Policy Development, Planning and Research (PDPR) administered the contract until staff could be hired.  PDPR staff also developed and distributed Requests for Proposals for funding under the Technology Challenge Grant Program, resulting in the funding of 10 regional manufacturing extension centers.  These centers, the core of the state's Coalition for Manufacturing Performance through Technology (COMPETE) initiative, will play a crucial role in fostering future research and technology transfer.<p>

Fiscal Year 1995 saw DCCA take concrete steps toward an ambitious effort to change the way Illinois delivers job training services to its workers and businesses.  Working closely with the Illinois Department of Employment Security (IDES), DCCA awarded more than $1.1 million in grants to develop 16 regional "one stop" career centers designed to consolidate employment and training services under one roof, thus easing the path to employment for unemployed and economically-
disadvantaged Illinoisans.  The joint effort, for which planning began in 1991, is the foundation of an even more impressive network of one-stop centers which will eventually blanket the entire state.<p>

Meanwhile, DCCA's staff continued working with a network of local administering agencies to ensure that job training services were available to those needing them.  Under Title III of the Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA), 21,200 dislocated workers received job training assistance.  JTPA's Title IIA programs, which address the needs of economically disadvantaged adults, served 15,010 individuals statewide; an additional 1,237 older adults were served through the JTPA Title IIA Set-Aside Program for older workers.  Title IIC programs served 10,957 economically disadvantaged youths.  DCCA also provided a $408,889 grant to continue planning of a comprehensive Education to Careers system for Illinois.<p>

DCCA staffers continued their work with businesses, colleges and universities, and intermediary organizations to provide training to help Illinois workers keep their skills consistent with changing technologies and business processes.  Through the Industrial Training Program (ITP), DCCA funded 58 projects that benefited 1,321 companies and 38,652 trainees.<p>

Smaller Illinois communities often need assistance to meet the housing, infrastructure and economic development needs of their citizens.  In Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA provided nearly $6 million through the federally-funded Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) to assist with 14 economic development projects.  An additional $41.2 million in supplemental CDAP funds were allocated to assist local governments in their continuing efforts to repair damages inflicted by the Great Flood of 1993.<p>

DCCA staffers also worked closely with their counterparts from the Illinois Department of Public Aid to successfully help local communities compile application proposals for the federally-funded Empowerment Zone and Enterprise Community programs.  During Fiscal Year 1995, the City of Chicago was designated as an Empowerment Zone and the cities of Springfield and East St. Louis received designation as Enterprise Communities.<p>

Local government officials also relied on DCCA to help them learn more about ways to effectively utilize their resources.  Through its Office of Local Government Management Services, DCCA conducted or participated in 51 training sessions, assisting more than 3,100 elected and appointed government officials.  The office also responded to more than 1,100 telephone calls from local officials, distributed more than 10,500 publications and conducted 82 direct technical assistance projects.  The Office of Local Government Initiatives, established in Fiscal Year 1994, worked with 19 communities designated to participate in the Competitive Communities Initiative (CCI), a new effort designed to help communities enhance their competitiveness for business retention, expansion and attraction.  CCI received special recognition when a study team sent to Illinois by the Governor of Pennsylvania recommended CCI as a program that should be established in the Keystone State.<p>

Low-income Illinoisans received DCCA assistance to help them overcome many of the difficulties they face in everyday life.  In Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA helped 201,582 households through the Low-Income Home Energy Assistance Program (LIHEAP), which helps pay a portion of the cost of winter energy bills.  In addition, the Illinois Home Weatherization Assistance Program (IHWAP) assisted 6,992 households.  The Community Services Block Grant Program (CSBG), which includes the CSBG Loan Program, a scholarship program and an emergency community services program to help the homeless, assisted 322,932 Illinoisans.<p>

Tourism, one of the state's fastest-growing industries, continued to thrive in Illinois during Fiscal Year 1995.  Domestic and international tourism revenues reached a record $15.9 billion during Calendar Year 1994 -- a 6.3 percent increase over the previous year.  Tourism contributed $995 million in local and state taxes, and supported 241,500 jobs in the state with a payroll of $4.8 billion.  In Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA's Illinois Bureau of Tourism took the marketing of Illinois tourism to a new level, conducting an integrated marketing program designed to identify and reach the state's most likely tourism customers.  A new advertising campaign promoting the theme "Illinois:  A Million Miles from Monday" was launched to position Illinois as the ideal weekend getaway destination.  Advertising and public relations strategies also promoted the Bureau's new toll-free information number, 1-800-2CONNECT, which connects consumers to Illinois' state-of-the-art Illinois Travel Counseling System, enabling consumers to speak with a trained travel counselor.<p> 

DCCA also was affected by the reorganization of the state's natural resource agencies into one "super-agency."  The breakup of the Illinois Department of Energy and Natural Resources (ENR) sent three major responsibilities -- energy conservation and alternative energy, recycling, and coal development and marketing -- to DCCA.  Although these programs did not become a part of the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs until Fiscal Year 1996, their statistical and programmatic information for Fiscal Year 1995 is included in this report.<p> 

The foundations laid in Fiscal Year 1995 will continue to pay dividends as DCCA and the State of Illinois move confidently forward into Fiscal Year 1996 and beyond.<p>


<P>
<HR>
<STRONG>| <A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com">DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/95annrep.htm">1995 Annual Report</A> |</STRONG>
</BODY>
