<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: 1995 Annual Report -- Bureau of Community Development</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>1995 Annual Report: Bureau of Community Development</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>

<p>

DCCA's Bureau of Community Development works with local governments and networks of local administering agencies to help enhance quality of life and create strong, vital communities that attract and retain businesses and their jobs.  Programs administered by the Bureau include the federal Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA), the Industrial Training Program (ITP), and the Illinois Labor-Management Grant Program, that help to enhance workers' skills and the viability of the Illinois workforce; technology programs to help businesses benefit from advancements and become more competitive; programs to help local officials better serve their constituents; programs such as Enterprise Zones and the federally-funded Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP), which help communities improve their attractiveness to businesses and address infrastructure needs; and programs designed to improve economic opportunities for low-income residents of Illinois. <p>  

<strong>
<a href="#JTPA">Job Training Partnership Act</a><br>
<a href="#Industrial Training">Industrial Training Program</a><br>
<a href="#Labor Management">Labor-Management Cooperation Program</a><br>
<a href="#Technology">Illinois Technology Grant Program</a><br>
<a href="#CDAP">Community Development Assistance Program</a><br>
<a href="#Enterprise Zones">Enterprise Zones</a><br>
<a href="#Public Infrastructure Programs">Business Development Public Infrastructure Program</a><br>
<a href="#Affordable Financing">Affordable Financing of Public Infrastructure Program -- Small Project Loan Component</a><br>
<a href="#Local Initiatives">Office of Local Initiatives</a><br>
<a href="#Local Govt Management">Office of Local Government Management Services</a><br>
<a href="#Housing Office">Housing Office</a><br>
<a href="#Community Service Block Grant">Community Services Block Grant Program</a><br>
<a href="#Energy Asst">Energy Assistance & Weatherization Programs</a><p>
</strong>

<a name="JTPA"><hr></a>
<h3>Job Training Partnership Act</h3>

Through the federally-funded Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA), jobless and disadvantaged Illinois workers are provided with retraining, readjustment and supportive services designed to provide them with opportunities to become productive members of society.  JTPA programs assist workers dislocated from their jobs, and help economically-disadvantaged youths and adults, older workers and others who face barriers to employment.<p>

As the state agency administering the JTPA programs in Illinois, DCCA works closely with a network of local administering agencies to operate a comprehensive system of services to respond to the changing work force development environment.<p>

During Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA continued its partnership with the Illinois Department of Employment Security (IDES) to develop new ways to deliver services more effectively.  In addition, the partnership expanded to include the Illinois Department of Public Aid and the Illinois Community College Board.  A primary component of that strategy is development of a network of One-Stop Career Centers (OSCCs) throughout the state, in which employment and training services will be consolidated under one roof.  These centers will allow clients to file for unemployment compensation benefits, register with the Job Service, and access JTPA-funded training and a variety of other services to help the individual enter or re-enter the labor force.  They also will provide business seeking qualified workers with streamlined services, and prepare specific training plans that tailor training, education and work force preparation programs to meet the needs of area employers.<p>  

In September 1994, Gov. Jim Edgar participated in ceremonies announcing more than $1.1 million in planning grants to develop 16 One-Stop Career Centers in Illinois.  By March 1995, when Director Dennis Whetstone participated in grand opening ceremonies at the Decatur Employment and Training Center, that number had grown to $1.7 million in planning grants, with projections for 40 regional OSCCs throughout the state.  In the later months of Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA submitted its application to the U. S. Department of Labor (USDOL) to fund a three-year project to speed up implementation of the network.  (In early Fiscal Year 1996, DCCA received word that the USDOL had selected Illinois as one of seven states chosen to implement the Network.  Illinois received a grant of nearly $6.7 million to fund activities during the first year of the three-year project, with a total of $16.7 million available over the three year period.  With the federal assistance, Illinois now plans to establish 55 full-service centers and 93 satellite centers around the state.)<p>

DCCA continued to serve as an active member of the state's Education-to-Careers Steering Committee during Fiscal Year 1995.  The Steering Committee membership was expanded to include not only representatives from state government, but also local educators at the secondary and postsecondary levels, business partners, and organized labor.  The Steering Committee is under the leadership of the office of Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, with a private sector facilitator.<p>

The Committee is coordinating the organization of local Education-to-Careers partnerships around community college boundaries.  It developed a marketing notebook that will be distributed to local partnerships, and members of the Steering Committee participated in numerous conferences and workshops on school-to-work initiatives.  The Committee is finalizing learner and system goals for the local partnerships to consider during their planning period.  Minimum planning grants will be issued to each partnership when it is appropriately constituted and an application is received.  The work of the Steering Committee will be summarized in a report and forwarded to the Human Resource Investment Council for subsequent action.<p>  

The Illinois Job Training Coordinating Council (IJTCC), a 50-member advisory body to the Governor and General Assembly on workforce preparation and development issues, continued a project to develop a long-term agenda for workforce preparation activities in Illinois.  The IJTCC has focused its efforts on assessing Illinois' future occupational needs and prospects, defining goals, establishing criteria and identifying and fostering the required information flows for policy coordination.  DCCA managed the project during Fiscal Year 1995.<p>  

For Fiscal Year 1995 Illinois received $46,291,769 to fund JTPA Title III programs.  These funds enabled DCCA to provide job training assistance to 23,339 dislocated workers.  Out of 9,731 dislocated workers terminated from the program, 7,350 re-entered the labor force at an average wage of $10.19 per hour after receiving Title III assistance.<p>

During Fiscal Year 1995, $25,205,560 was made available under JTPA Title IIC, the Year-Round Youth Program, to support programs and services for economically disadvantaged and at-risk young people ages 14 to 21.  Of these program participants, 2,701 became employed.<p>

DCCA continued its efforts to help economically disadvantaged adults.  In Fiscal Year 1995, JTPA Title IIA programs served 15,010 participants statewide.  An additional 1,237 older individuals were served through the JTPA Title IIA Set-Aside Program for this population.  Of the 8,929 adults who finished the Title IIA program, 4,946 entered employment with an average wage at placement of $7.50 per hour.  Underlining the importance of the program, 4,166 of Title IIA participants were public assistance recipients; out of 3,081 terminating from the program, 1,456 entered employment.<p>


<a name="Industrial Training"><hr></a>
<h3>Industrial Training Program</h3>

The state-funded Industrial Training Program (ITP) is recognized as a vital component of DCCA's overall effort to ensure that Illinois companies are competitive in a global economy and that the skills of Illinois' workforce remain among the highest in the world.  A skilled work force enables companies to respond to the productivity, cost and quality requirements demanded by its customers.<p>

In Fiscal Year 1995, ITP training funds were an integral component of many of the Industry Development projects outlined in this report, including DeMert & Dougherty, Motorola, SMF, Simonton Building Products, Knapheide Manufacturing Company, Honeywell's Micro Switch Division and Cotter & Company.  In addition, ITP training funds were used to assist with many previously-announced retention, expansion and location projects, including 3M Company, American Steel Foundries, General Tire, Kraft General Foods, Magnet, Nabisco, tesa tuck and Tootsie Roll.  As a result of these projects and others, ITP grants assisted with the training of 1,854 new employees and the retraining and/or skill upgrading of 9,384 existing workers.<p>

Since Fiscal Year 1992, DCCA has worked to develop partnerships with intermediary organizations to encourage the implementation and expansion of multi-company training projects.  These intermediary organizations include statewide business and industry organizations, original equipment manufacturers sponsoring training for employees of their Illinois-based supplier network companies, labor organizations, community colleges and universities.  These programs have proven to be especially beneficial to small and medium-sized companies which often do not have the internal resources -- financial, personnel, expertise and/or technology -- to cost-effectively provide these training programs individually for their employees.<p>  

In Fiscal Year 1995, ITP grants were awarded to the following intermediary organizations:  the Illinois Manufacturers' Association, Management Association of Illinois, Illinois State Chamber of Commerce, Chemical Industry Council of Illinois, Deere & Company, Elgin Community College, Ford Motor Company, Highland Community College, Illinois Cast Metals Association, Society of Plastics Industry, South Suburban Community College, and Valley Industrial Association.  As a result of these grants, 243 new employees and 21,085 existing employees representing 1,278 Illinois companies benefited from training programs.  The type of training conducted varied considerably among the various organizations, ranging from specific technical training, to computerization, to total quality management systems and process reengineering.  There has been an increasing emphasis on training programs related to international and industry quality standards, especially ISO 9000 and QS 9000.<p>

ITP grants also are awarded to individual companies conducting retraining and/or skill upgrading programs for their employees, often in conjunction with the introduction of new equipment or technologies in the workplace.  In Fiscal Year 1995, 21 companies were awarded ITP grants to assist with their training programs benefiting 551 new employees and 5,535 existing employees.<p>

In summary, the $15 million ITP appropriation was used to fund 58 projects benefiting 1,321 companies and 38,652 trainees at an average cost of $310 per trainee.<p>  


<a name="Labor Management"><hr></a>
<h3>Labor-Management Cooperation Program</h3>

The Illinois Labor-Management Cooperation Program promotes positive relations between labor and management and encourages implementation of cooperative labor-management programs at the workplace, industry, regional and state levels.  Numerous studies have found that cooperative work practices have a positive impact on labor relations, productivity and company performance.  Implementation of innovative workplace strategies can contribute significantly to bottom-line profits and improved working conditions.  Based on that concept, increasing such programming in Illinois workplaces would improve labor-management relations and the overall business climate of the state.<p>

The Illinois Labor-Management Cooperation Committee during Fiscal Year 1995 continued efforts to evaluate and enhance the effectiveness of local labor-management committees supported by the Labor-Management Grant Program and to utilize available resources to increase the level of cooperative management programming in Illinois.  During the process, the State Committee found strong support from labor and management for the state's role in developing programs to improve Illinois' labor-management climate.  Steps were taken to expand and strengthen Illinois' local labor-management committee network, increase the visibility of the State Committee and raise awareness about the many benefits derived from cooperative workplace programs.  In its 1995 Report to the Governor and Members of the General Assembly, the State Committee detailed a number of program accomplishments and made recommendations to further enhance Illinois' labor-management climate. <p> 

In Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA's Labor-Management Grant Program provided grants totaling $287,800 to support 11 local labor-management councils statewide.  Programs provided by the local councils included educational conferences and workshops, special labor-management recognition and awards events, information dissemination services, specialized training to establish and maintain cooperative workplace initiatives, and various activities to improve communication between labor and management in the communities. <p> 

During Fiscal Year 1995, the State Committee initiated a special award program, Labor-Management Partners:  On the Road to High Performance.  The awards, which recognize labor and management for their efforts to work together toward outstanding workplace performance, were presented to Quaker Oats Company's Danville operations and the American Federation of Grain Millers Local 347; Black Hawk College and the American Federation of Teachers/Illinois Federation of Teachers AFL-CIO Local 1836 in Moline; Keystone Steel & Wire Company and the Independent Steel Workers Alliance in Bartonville; and Shapiro Developmental Center and the American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees Local 29 in Kankakee.  Winners, who were evaluated using criteria for a High Performance Workplace developed by the U.S. Department of Labor Office of the American Workplace, were recognized with plaques during the statewide Labor-Management Conference held in March 1995.<p>


<a name="Technology">
</a><hr>
<h3>Illinois Technology Grant Program</h3>

Access to technology and modern business practices is one of the major foundations supporting economic growth and business competitiveness.  DCCA's Technology Program focuses on efforts to help businesses become more competitive through technology. <p> 
In Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA continued to coordinate Illinois' business modernization efforts with the assistance of a number of Illinois partner organizations.  DCCA utilized a $1.4 million Technology Reinvestment Project grant from the National Institute of Standards and Technology, in addition to funds from the Illinois Technology Challenge Grant Program to support the state's Coalition for Manufacturing Performance through Technology (COMPETE) initiative.  The mission of COMPETE, an initiative announced by Gov. Jim Edgar in 1994, is to improve the competitiveness of small and mid-sized Illinois manufacturing firms through a statewide network of Manufacturing Extension Centers (MECs) and other support organizations.<p>

Through local MECs and other partners, the state enables firms to directly receive technology advancement and modernization services that they need to increase their productivity and compete on a national and international level.  The regional MECs are staffed with engineers and professionals with practical experience in the manufacturing workplace.  These specialists work with companies to make confidential recommendations for improvements.  With access to a wide array of industry experts and the resources of universities, community colleges and private consultants, the MEC staffers can help companies implement improvement plans and projects they need to enhance their competitiveness.  During Fiscal Year 1995, the network of MECs provided numerous services to Illinois manufacturers, including:<p>

<ul type=square>
<li> 1,055 initial field visits.<p>
<li> 768 firms enrolled for services.<p>
<li> 192 manufacturing assessments and performance benchmarks.<p>
<li> 93 formal service bids.<p>
<li> 100 engineering and technical consulting projects.<p>
</ul>

In directing the Fiscal Year 1995 Technology Challenge Grant Program, DCCA was assisted by The Illinois Coalition and the Governor's Science Advisory Committee.<p>


<a name="CDAP"><hr></a>
<h3>Community Development Assistance Program</h3>

The federally-funded Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) is designed to help smaller Illinois communities meet their housing, infrastructure and economic development needs.  The program, funded through a block grant from the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD), provides grants to local units of government in communities with populations of 50,000 or less that are not located within one of the seven urban counties that receive funds directly from HUD.<p>  

During Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA awarded $5.9 million in grants to assist with 14 CDAP economic development projects.  Public facilities projects -- engineering and construction projects associated with improvements to water and sewer systems -- were undertaken in 121 communities with the assistance of $25 million in CDAP grants.  Four emergency public facilities projects were funded with $436,825 in CDAP assistance, and 24 communities shared in $500,000 in CDAP planning grants to help them prepare plans for needed public facilities projects.  Thirty-seven communities were awarded $7 million in CDAP public housing grants to help local homeowners bring their dwellings up to code requirements.  DCCA also provided $4 million in CDAP grants to assist local units of government in removing barriers that limit accessibility to community buildings and services by those with disabilities.<p>

In Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA also received $41.2 million in CDAP Supplemental Flood Program assistance to continue to help local governments recover from the devastating effects of the Great Flood of 1993.  These funds, combined with other federal and state funds, have helped communities to develop flood recovery plans, acquire properties located in the floodplain, elevate homes and repair needed infrastructure.<p>  

The Community Development Assistance Program continues to be a chief source of assistance to ensure that the citizens of smaller Illinois communities have safe public water and sewer systems, quality housing stock and the infrastructure necessary to attract and retain businesses and their jobs.<p>   


<a name="Enterprise Zones"><hr></a>
<h3>Enterprise Zones</h3>

Enterprise Zones are designated areas in communities and regions throughout the state that offer a mix of state and local tax incentives, regulatory relief and enhanced government services that make the areas more attractive to businesses and residents.  Illinois currently has certified 91 Enterprise Zones.  In Fiscal Year 1995, companies located within the zones invested more than $1.5 billion.  The investments are projected to create more than 8,000 jobs.<p>


<a name="Public Infrastructure Programs"><hr></a>
<h3>Business Development Public Infrastructure Program</h3>

The Business Development Public Infrastructure Program provides low-interest loans or grants to local governments to make improvements to public infrastructure on behalf of business expansion or retention projects.  The projects must demonstrate job creation and retention potential.  Funds may be used for a variety of public infrastructure improvements, such as access roads, extending water and sewer lines, and water and sewage treatment facilities.  In Fiscal Year 1995, $1.3 million was provided to three communities to fund infrastructure improvements associated with projects expected to create and retain more than 700 jobs.<p>


<a name="Affordable Financing"><hr></a>
<h3>Affordable Financing of Public Infrastructure Program - Small Project Loan Component</h3>

This program brings together DCCA, the Illinois Rural Bond Bank, the Illinois Development Finance Authority, and the Illinois Environmental Protection Agency to provide financial assistance to or on behalf of local governments, public entities, medical facilities and public health clinics for the purpose of making affordable the financing of infrastructure needed to ensure public health and safety and economic development.  The program's Small Project Loan Component can provide up to $100,000 for a maximum of 10 years at an attractive interest rate.  Funds may be used for acquisition, construction and improvements of public facilities and associated equipment.<p>  


<a name="Local Initiatives"><hr></a>
<h3>Office of Local Initiatives</h3>

The Office of Local Initiatives often is the first point of contact for local officials seeking DCCA assistance.  Serving as the outreach arm for DCCA's Bureau of Community Development, the office helps local community leaders find the information, resources and technical assistance they need to find solutions to local problems. <p>

The Office of Local Initiatives administers the Competitive Communities Initiative (CCI), a program designed to serve as a catalyst to teach communities to think and act strategically, ultimately resulting in improved competitiveness.  Based on the belief that communities are themselves in the best position to positively affect their own futures, CCI provides a format and the necessary technical assistance to complete the critical first step toward competitiveness -- a community self-assessment of the foundations of growth.<p>  

During Fiscal Year 1995, the Office of Local Initiatives worked with 19 CCI communities identified as being in the initial stages of development to help them undertake self-assessments and take steps to become more competitive.<p>  

The Office of Local Initiatives also oversees the mandates review process required by the General Assembly.<p>  
 

<a name="Local Govt Management"><hr></a>
<h3>Office of Local Government Management Services</h3>

The Office of Local Government Management Services provides assistance to local governments by providing training to local officials on financial issues, responding to questions about the duties of local officials, and providing direct one-on-one technical assistance on matters of particular importance to local government officials.<p>

During Fiscal Year 1995, the Office conducted or participated in 51 training sessions, meeting the training needs of more than 3,100 elected and appointed local government officials.  The training sessions are designed to address a broad range of financial management issues facing local governments, such as  revenue sources, property taxes, preparing and maintaining a balanced budget, statutory duties of local officials and ways local governments can plan and finance needed improvements to infrastructure.  Training sessions were conducted by DCCA staffers, as well as by DCCA staffers working with partners from the Illinois Municipal League, the Illinois Municipal Clerks Association, the Illinois Municipal Treasurers Institute, the University of Illinois, Governor's State University, Western Illinois University, Eastern Illinois University, Township Officials of Illinois, the Illinois Farm Bureau, and a number of county-based local government organizations.<p>

The Office also responded to more than 1,100 telephone calls from local officials on a variety of issues, and distributed nearly 10,500 publications on topics of interest to local officials, such as revenue sources, budgeting procedures, capital improvement planning and budgeting, computer information, local purchasing, and personnel procedures.  In addition, the Office conducted 82 direct technical assistance projects for local governments to help them enhance their financial stability.  Technical assistance was provided through one-on-one direction to improve accounting systems, budget procedures, revenue projections, preparation of revenue and expenditure reports, and water user rate studies.<p>  


<a name="Housing Office"><hr></a>
<h3>Housing Office</h3>

DCCA's Housing Office administers two programs designed to help low- and moderate-income families live in decent, affordable housing.  The Rental Rehab Program provides funds to eligible units of local government to help rehabilitate privately-owned units for occupation by income-eligible families.  The federally-funded Section 8 Moderate Rehabilitation Program provides incentives to private property owners to upgrade their properties for use by eligible renters.  In Fiscal Year 1995, $282,383 in Rental Rehab funds leveraged with $401,268 in private funds resulted in the rehabilitation of 72 units serving 200 low-income people.  Section 8 Moderate Rehabilitation funds provided $1,154,600 in rental assistance to 813 people living in units supported by the funds.<p>

DCCA's Housing Office also administers the federally-funded Emergency Shelter Grant Program (ESGP), which assists homeless people to make the transition from poverty to productivity.  In Fiscal Year 1995, the ESGP served more than 50,075 homeless people.<p>  

The Housing Office also works closely with the Governor's Office and the Office of the Lieutenant Governor to administer the annual Governor's Home Town Awards Program.  The program, which promotes volunteerism in Illinois, awards road signs and plaques to communities and organizations that demonstrate outstanding volunteer efforts.  The 14th Annual Governor's Home Town Awards competition drew applications from more than 100 communities.  Awards were given to 65 communities, with Tamms receiving the Governor's Cup as the project most representative of the spirit of volunteerism.  The 1995 awards program also saw special plaques awarded to seven communities for volunteer efforts associated with re-enactments of the Lincoln-Douglas debates, which were televised on C-SPAN.<p>


<a name="Community Service Block Grant"><hr></a>
<h3>Community Services Block Grant Program</h3>

Funded by the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services (HHS), the Community Services Block Grant Program (CSBG) is administered in Illinois by DCCA.  Funds are awarded to the state's network of 36 Community Action Agencies (CAAs) to help low-income people achieve self-sufficiency and to provide services designed to address the causes and conditions of poverty.  These services take many forms, from scholarships, to loans to businesses that employ low-income people, to providing emergency assistance to pay for food, shelter and clothing.<p>

The CSBG Loan Program provides long-term, fixed rate financing to new and expanding Illinois businesses.  The loans link federal, state and private financing by combining low-interest CSBG loans with bank funds.  Businesses receiving CSBG loans agree to create jobs for low-income individuals.  In Fiscal Year 1995, CSBG loans made to 57 small businesses resulted in the creation of 252 jobs and generated an additional $12.38 million in leveraged private investment.<p> 

The CSBG Scholarship Program assists low-income high school, vocational school or college students who show academic promise and potential in high technology or growth fields of study.  Preference is also given to low-income and disadvantaged racial or ethnic minorities who plan to enter either a two-year or four-year college, university or vocational school in Illinois.  Created in response to CSBG's mandate that funds be used to help low-income people receive adequate education, the scholarships can support tuition costs; textbooks, supplies and fees; room and board expenses; and transportation and child care.  The CSBG scholarship program is administered by the network of Community Action Agencies, the Illinois Migrant Council and the Illinois Community Action Association.  In Fiscal Year 1995, 417 scholarships totaling $464,355 were awarded.<p>

The CSBG Emergency Community Services Homeless Program is also administered by the Community Action Agencies.  The program funds such services as emergency shelter, counseling, food, clothing, medicine, rent and educational assistance needed by the homeless.  During Fiscal Year 1995, $960,931 in CSBG Emergency Community Services Homeless Program funds were allocated to serve 5,892 clients.<p>  


<a name="Energy Asst"><hr></a>
<h3>Energy Assistance and Weatherization Programs</h3>

Economic development is more than business development.  It also means ensuring that all Illinois citizens share in the benefits of a strong economy.  Through the Low-Income Home Energy Assistance Program (LIHEAP) and the Illinois Home Weatherization Assistance Program (IHWAP), DCCA works to make sure that  low-income Illinoisans can live in safe, comfortable, energy-efficient homes.<p>

The Low-Income Home Energy Assistance Program (LIHEAP) is funded through the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services and provides funds to help low-income people pay a portion of their winter energy costs.  Administered throughout the state by a network of Community Action Agencies or community-based organizations, the funds are provided to energy vendors on behalf of households that pay for their energy directly, as well as to households whose energy costs are included in their rent.  Emergency assistance is also available to qualified households to help restore energy services that have been cut off.  In Fiscal Year 1995, LIHEAP served 201,582 Illinois households.<p>  

The Illinois Home Weatherization Assistance Program (IHWAP) helps low-income Illinoisans reduce the costs of energy by helping to fund improvements such as insulation, caulking and weather-stripping, heating system repairs and retrofits.  Administered by DCCA and operated by Community Action Agencies or community-based organizations, IHWAP funds are targeted particularly toward senior citizens and people with disabilities who are often on fixed incomes and cannot afford high fuel costs nor the repairs needed to keep energy bills down.  In Fiscal Year 1995, 6,992 Illinois households were served by IHWAP assistance.<p>  


<P>
<HR>
<STRONG>| <A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com">DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/95annrep.htm">1995 Annual Report</A> |</STRONG>
