<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: 1995 Annual Report -- Policy Development, Planning & Research</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>1995 Annual Report: Policy Development, Planning & Research</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>
<p>

DCCA's Division of Policy Development, Planning and Research (PDPR) operates within the Director's Office to identify issues, barriers and opportunities facing the state's economic development efforts; analyze the various alternatives available to address these issues; and assess the results of DCCA's programs and activities.  These services help agency staffers to make informed decisions and assess the future implications of agency decisions, policies and strategies.<p>

Among PDPR's functions:<p>

<ul type=square>
<li> Research, which helps develop and maintain DCCA's information base and conducts various analyses to apply this information to issues faced by DCCA and the state.<p>
<li> Policy Analysis, analyzing programs and policies that impact Illinois economic development.<p>
<li> Planning and Assessment, providing an integrated system of agency management, including implementation of goals, program objectives, operational strategies and evaluation of progress.<p>
<li> Program Development, identifying possible strategies and courses of action to best pursue an opportunity or overcome a barrier.<p>
</ul>

During Fiscal Year 1995, PDPR staff continued many of the efforts begun in Fiscal Year 1994, including flood relief, community development and technology development.  PDPR maintained DCCA's presence in the state's ongoing efforts to help communities and citizens recover from the devastation of the Great Flood of 1993.  PDPR prepared a publication, Proposal Writing:  The Basic Steps in Planning and Writing a Successful Grant Application, and distributed more than 3,000 copies to DCCA constituents.  Staffers also helped prepare an application to the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service for a grant to augment the state's Labor-Management program, and developed and distributed the Request for Proposals for Fiscal Year 1995 and Fiscal Year 1996 funding for the Technology Challenge Grant Program.  PDPR conducted best-of-practice analyses on department budget initiative topics, including multi-company networks, local government training, place marketing, brownfields, and tax credit incentives.  PDPR also promulgated rulemakings in nine program areas which were formally adopted through the Joint Committee on Administrative Rules process.<p>

PDPR completed development of the Illinois Industry Analysis System and began preliminary testing of the system.  This system is designed to allow economic development officials to answer commonly asked questions about their most important industries, their largest employers, the types of businesses moving into their regions, the name of the CEO of a local company, etc.  The system also is organized to improve targeting of specific firms for business retention or attraction.  It is based upon Dun & Bradstreet's profile of establishments with a minimum of 10 employees that ever operated within Illinois between 1987 and the present.  Target release of the system is planned for calendar year 1996.<p>

PDPR also provided support to many boards and task forces, serving as DCCA's primary representatives to The Illinois Coalition, a public/private partnership pursuing a coherent, coordinated strategy of economic development through technology; the Illinois Coalition Technology and Jobs Agenda, a blue-ribbon committee charged with laying out a strategic plan to position the state's economy to grow through use of technology; and an interagency task force that wrote administrative rules to implement the Interagency Wetland Policy Act and administers the development of an Illinois Wetlands Comprehensive Strategy.<p>
 
PDPR in Fiscal Year 1995 began work to develop benchmarks to compare Illinois' economic development with other states' efforts.  This was a recommendation of the Illinois Economic Development Board, chaired by Samuel K. Skinner.  In January 1995, Skinner and his 21-member board completed their year-long study of the state's climate for job creation and retention, presenting their report to Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra.  The report made 17 recommendations to help the state refine policies and programs to help businesses grow and prosper, thus providing jobs and improving overall quality of life.<p>

PDPR continued to provide valuable economic information and statistics through the quarterly Illinois Economic Summary and the monthly Illinois Economic Bulletin.  The publications were also made available on-line through the Access Illinois bulletin board system.<p>


<P>
<HR>
<STRONG>| <A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com">DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/95annrep.htm">1995 Annual Report</A> |</STRONG>
</BODY>
