<HEAD><TITLE>Illinois Facts: Workforce Development</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>Workforce Development Programs</FONT>
<HR>


<H3>Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA)</H3>

The federally-funded Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA) program is a 
statewide local delivery system designed to provide job training for 
economically-disadvantaged  adults, older adults and youths, workers 
dislocated from their jobs due to plant closings or mass layoffs, and 
others who face serious barriers to employment.  The program is 
administered in Illinois by the Department of Commerce and Community 
Affairs (DCCA) through a network of 26 Service Delivery Areas (SDAs) around 
the state.  Each SDA is overseen by a Private Industry Council of local 
business leaders and public officials, who work together to develop plans 
and programs to meet the needs of local businesses and the local labor 
market.<P>


<h3>Program Descriptions</h3>

<strong>Title 2A - Year Round Adult Program</strong> - This program prepares adults for participation in the labor force by increasing their occupational and educational skills, resulting in improved long-term employability, increased employment and earnings, and reduced welfare dependency.  <p>

<strong>Title 2B - Summer Youth Program</strong> - This program enhances the basic educational skills of youth, encourages school completion or enrollment in supplementary or alternative school programs, provides eligible youth with exposure to the world of work, and enhances their citizenship skills.<p>

<strong>Title 2C - Year Round Youth Program </strong>- This program improves the long-term employability of youth, enhances their educational, occupational, and citizenship skills, encourages school completion or enrollment in alternative school programs, increases their employment and earnings, reduces welfare dependency, and assists youth in addressing problems that impair their ability to make successful transitions from school to work, apprenticeship, the military, or postsecondary education and training.<p>

<strong>Title 3 - Dislocated Worker Program</strong> - This program assists eligible workers who are dislocated due to plant or facility closings, layoffs, or technological changes in their occupation or industry.  Available services include counseling, vocational assessment, case management, occupational training, basic and remedial education, on-the-job training, job search assistance, and placement.<p>

<strong>Illinois Employment & Training Centers (IETCs)</strong> -  An IETC (formerly known as a One-Stop Career Center) is a location where the public can easily access a broad array of employment, training and related services.  One or more IETCs will be located in each of Illinois' 26 service delivery areas designated under the Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA).  Some services will be available through satellite offices and through computer technology in areas of the state where location of an IETC is not practical.  Consolidation of program access will be key.  At a minimum, IETCs will consolidate access to unemployment insurance, job service and veterans employment programs administered by the Department of Employment Security and the JTPA programs described above and administered by the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs.  Other programs may also be consolidated including programs offered by:  the Illinois Department of Public Aid, the Department on Aging and the Department of Rehabilitation Services.  Community  Colleges will also be involved.  Some services will be "self-accessed" through computers.  Access to informational services will also be extended to other sites through LANs and use of Internet.<p>

<ul>
<center><strong>Illinois Employment & Training Center Network</strong><p></center>

<strong><em>What is an Illinois Employment & Training Center (IETC)?</em></strong>  An IETC (formerly known as a One-Stop Career Center) is an office where the public can easily access a broad array of employment, training and related services.  One or more IETCs will be located in each of Illinois' 26 service delivery areas designated under the Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA).  Some services will be available through satellite offices and through computer technology in areas of the state where location of an IETC is not practical.<p>

<strong><em>Who will be served by IETCs?</em></strong>  Centers will provide services to:  (1) dislocated workers, (2) the economically disadvantaged, (3) unemployment insurance claimants, (4) unemployed workers, (5) employed workers wishing to find new jobs, (6) new entrants to the labor force, (7) students, (8) schools and (9) employers.<p>

<strong><em>What services will be available to workers?</em></strong>  Centers will provide informational services to everyone.  Services that will be available to the public include:  labor market information, career information, information and referral to community services, eligibility screening for state and federal training programs, qualitative information about alternative training providers, referral to education and training programs, registration with the Illinois Job Service and registration for unemployment insurance.  Additional services will be available to workers determined to be eligible for them under various categorical programs (e.g., JTPA).  More intensive services will include:  vocational testing, career counseling and planning, ongoing case management, intensive job search assistance and training and financial assistance for training.<p>

<strong><em>What services will be available for employers?</em> </strong> Employers can use the local IETC to:  access a "skills bank" of workers looking for jobs, learn about sources of financial assistance to support worker training, access useful business information products and have job applicants prescreened to meet their requirements.<p>

<strong><em>What services will be available to students and schools? </em></strong>  IETCs will be a source of the latest labor market information (LMI) for schools, libraries and students.  LMI products will be available on-site and will be distributed by the IETC in hard copy and via computer (e.g., distribution of software and LANs).  IETCs will also be a source of in-service training for career counseling personnel regarding the use of LMI products.  Students and dropouts may also use the IETC to obtain career counseling and to learn about "second chance" education programs.<p>

<strong>Consolidation of program access will be key.</strong>  At a minimum, IETCs will consolidate access to programs available through the Department of Employment Security (IDES) and programs administered through the  Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA).  Programs to be consolidated include:  unemployment insurance, the Illinois job service, veterans employment programs, JTPA dislocated worker programs, JTPA youth and adult programs and LMI services.   Other programs may also be consolidated including programs offered by:  the Illinois Department of Public Aid, the Department on Aging and the Department of Rehabilitation Services.<p>

<strong>Technology will also be key.</strong>  Some services will be "self-accessed" through computers.  Access to informational services will also be extended to other sites through LANs and use of Internet.<p>
</ul>

<HR>
