<H3>Vocational/Technical Education</H3>

Local schools, vocational centers, community colleges and 
universities offer a wide array of vocational and technical training 
programs to assist Illinois workers in obtaining the skills they need to be 
productive members of society.<P>

The 49 community colleges of Illinois provide more than 4,000 
associate degree and certification programs within 240 occupational 
specialties.  These programs are designed to meet the labor market needs of 
each district, as well as the state as a whole.  Community colleges 
maintain an open admission policy and will accept all individuals 18 years 
of age or older who can benefit.  Admission requirements for specific 
programs vary as appropriate.<P>

Students served by secondary, post-secondary and state agency 
institutions are eligible to receive vocational education services.  The 
majority of financial support is provided through state general revenue and 
local educational agency property tax funds.  Federal funding is also 
provided to secondary, post-secondary and state agencies to improve 
programs and provide services to special population students enrolled in 
targeted vocational education programs. <P>

Universities in Illinois provide help to area employers to meet 
vocational-technical training needs and provide upgrading opportunities for 
executives, management staff, researchers and technicians.<P>  

<HR>
<strong>| <a href="http://www.ilcommerce.com">DCCA Home Page</a> | <a href="/dcca/files/wforce/work.htm">Workforce Development</a> |</strong>

