<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Community Development Programs</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>

<font size=+3>Community Development Programs</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<CENTER><H3>Governor's Home Town Awards Program</H3></CENTER>
<HR>

<img src="../../graph/hometown.jpg" width=212 height=166 align=right>

<h3>MESSAGE FROM GOV. JIM EDGAR...</h3>

Everyday throughout Illinois, citizens are working voluntarily to improve the communities in which they live.  In doing so, they are combining talents and forming effective partnerships with local governments, businesses, labor, voluntary organizations and individual citizens.<p>

Our Home Town Awards Program, in its fifteenth year, honors communities and volunteers which have planned and implemented successful projects to meet community needs.<p>

The following information tells more about the programs and how to apply for a Home Town Award.<p>

I am proud of our Illinois hometowns.  I encourage you to participate in this year's Home Town Award Program.<p>

<hr>
<h3>GOVERNOR'S HOME TOWN AWARDS PROGRAM</h3>

In many Illinois communities, citizens have been organizing to contribute to their town's economic progress and quality of life.  By taking the initiative on a project, mobilizing volunteers and raising funds, they have successfully addressed local needs in a time of reduced public resources.  These volunteer projects often have the collective involvement of many such as local governments, business and industry, private, civic and community based organizations and individuals that donate time, materials, funds and expertise.<p>

<hr>
<h3>WHY HOME TOWN AWARDS?</h3>

The Governor's Home Town Awards Program gives formal recognition to outstanding community volunteer projects.  This program is administered by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs in close cooperation with the Lieutenant Governor's Office.<p>

<hr>
<h3>HOW CAN I SUBMIT A PROJECT?</h3>


It's simple.  Contact the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs for an application. The application can be submitted by a variety of community representatives such as a local government, a community organization, a local chamber of commerce, a community action agency, an area agency on aging, a local job training agency, etc. Applications are submitted between November and February.<p>

Once the department receives the completed application, the projects will be divided into population categories.  Impartial teams of judges will then evaluate the projects.<p>

The Governor's Home Town Awards Banquet held in June will recognize the winners in each program category, along with the grand prize Governor's Cup winner.<p>

<hr>
<h3>WHAT ARE THE PROGRAM CATEGORIES?</h3>

Home Town Awards will be given in four program categories:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li><strong>General Category</strong><p>
    Volunteer projects that made outstanding contributions to the community's overall improvement and quality of life.<p>

<li><strong>Economic Development</strong><p>
    Community economic development projects that have used volunteers.<p>

<li><strong>Youth Involvement Category</strong><p>
    Community projects that have been selected, planned and conducted by the community's      youth, and/or that directly benefit youth.<p>

<li><strong>Senior Citizen Involvement Category</strong><p>
    Community projects that have been selected, planned and conducted by senior citizens,     and/or that directly benefit senior citizens.<p>
</ul>

For more information about the Governor's Home Town Awards Program, contact:<p>
<dl><dd>
Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs<br>
620 East Adams<br>
Springfield, Illinois 62701<br>
217/785-6154; TDD:800/785-6055<br>
</dd></dl>

<hr>
<h3>GOVERNOR'S HOME TOWN AWARDS PROJECTS</h3>

Listed below are examples of projects entered in the program.  By capturing the resources available within the community, local volunteers were able to maintain or increase economic progress and the quality of life.<p>

Community Economic Development; Fire House Construction; Park Construction; Ambulance Service; Senior Citizen Center; Public Pool; Rehabilitation; Christmas Food and Toy Drive; Development of a Recreation Complex; Downtown Revitalization; Civic Center Construction; Senior Citizen Transportation Center; Youth Programs; Bicycle Safety Programs; Industrial Retention Programs; Economic Development Commission; Housing Rehabilitation; Literacy Council; Unemployment Services; Energy Conservation Project; Crimestoppers; "Urban Playground" for area youths.<p>





