<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>Energy, Coal & Recycling Programs</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>

<CENTER><H3>Ethanol Demonstration Program</H3></CENTER>
<HR>
<H4>
DCCA manages numerous ethanol demonstration projects to foster the
usage of ethanol, thus encouraging the relationship between industrial
manufacturing and rural development.  In addition, DCCA supports the
research and development of new technologies to reduce the cost of
producing ethanol.<P>

For information call 217/785-3969.<P>
</H4>

<hr>
<h3 align=center>Summary of Developing Ethanol Project in Illinois</h3>
<h4>
<a href="##1">Ethanol Powered State of Illinois Car Fleet</a><br>
<a href="##2">Ethanol Powered Heavy Truck Fleet Program</a><br>
<a href="##3">Peoria Bus Demonstration Project</a><br>
<a href="##4">Ethanol Fuel-Cell Research Project</a><br>
<a href="##5">Advanced Membrane Technology Project</a><br>
<a href="##6">The Hydrated Ethanol Heavy Engine Development Project</a><br>
<a href="##7">The National Ethanol Production Research Facility</a><br>
<a href="##8">Waste Sugar to Ethanol Projects</a><p>
</h4>

<a name="#1"><hr></a>
<h4>1. Ethanol Powered State of Illinois Car Fleet</h4>

The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA), formerly the Illinois Department of Energy and Natural Resources (ENR), is part of an extensive test and demonstration program ethanol-powered, flexible-fuel and variable fuel vehicles incorporated into the state fleet.  The Illinois Department of Central Management Services (CMS) is responsible for operating and maintaining the state fleet.  The state E-85 fleet is being operated and maintained through CMS facilities in Springfield and throughout the state.<p>

In 1992, General Motors produced fifty (50) Chevrolet Luminas optimized for ethanol fuel.  This fuel is composed of 85% denatured ethanol and 15 % light hydrocarbon, to ensure easy starting.  The petroleum denaturant used by the fuel producer (Archer Daniels Midland (ADM) in Peoria, Illinois), commonly called "natural gasoline" (a blend of c4-c6 hydrocarbons), can be used for the light hydrocarbons fraction.  The final blend, then, is 80% anhydrous ethanol and 20% natural gasoline.  This fuel is seasonally blended (down to 70% ethanol/30% natural gasoline in winter) to enhance cold weather starting.<p>

Illinois, Wisconsin and the federal government purchased the original 50 E-85 GM vehicles in late April 1992 at a cost $2000 more each than the standard gasoline versions.  The original 12 E-85 Luminas arrived in Springfield in July 1992.<p>

In the 1993 model year, the state purchased 55 additional E-85 Luminas.  Included in this order were vehicles purchased by Illinois State University, Southern Illinois University and the cities of Bloomington, Champaign, Chicago, Decatur, Normal and Peoria through a joint-purchasing agreement with the state.  Another 14 ethanol Luminas were purchased by the University of Illinois (5 cars) and private fleets such as the Illinois Corn Growers, DeKalb Genetics and Growmark, incorporated, through their Country Companies Leasing division.  The 1993 E-85 Lumina was priced the same as the gasoline version.<p>

In March 1994, the State of Illinois and General Services Administration (GSA) each purchased 25 of first 50 Flexible Fuel 1994 Ford Tauruses manufactured and warranted for use with E-85 fuel.  These "Ethanol-Ready" Tauruses were built by Ford Motor Company at their South Chicago Assembly Plant and are covered by a full factory warranty.  This is significant in that it is the first Illinois-made vehicle operating on Illinois-produced ethanol made from Illinois corn.  The state purchased an additional 71 Flexible Fuel Tauruses in 1995 for use in the state fleet and several state agencies.<p>

Beginning in 1996, the E-85 version of the Flexible Fuel Ford Taurus will be fully optimized for E-85 fuel.  The 1994 and 1995 versions were actually optimized for M-85 fuel, but Ford sold a limited number each year that were fully warranted for the use of E-85.  Illinois has ordered 100 of the 1996 Flexible Fuel Tauruses which will be produced this month at Ford's South Chicago Assembly Plant.<p>

A total of 13 refueling facilities are currently located throughout the state.  They are located at Argonne National Laboratory (southwest suburbs of Chicago), Bloomington/Normal (private), Carbondale, Champaign, Chicago, Collinsville, Decatur, DeKalb (private ), 2 sites in Peoria and 2 sites in Springfield.  The first commercial E-85 station opened in 1995 at the FS - Fuel 24 facility in Dwight, Illinois.  Dwight is situated about half way between Springfield and Chicago at the 220 Exit on Interstate 55.<p>

In mixed city and highway driving, the E-85 Luminas get about 20 miles per gallon on the ethanol fuel, which is slightly better than expected.  The E-85 Ford Taurus cars have been getting about 23 miles per gallon on E-85 fuel (do, in part, to a lower gear ratio), but do not have the acceleration or performance characteristics of the Chevrolet Luminas.  There have no significant mechanical problems with the any of the E-85 vehicles, including the 1992 Luminas, some of which have already been driven over 100,000 miles.  In November 1995, GM inspected, removed and analyzed key engine and fuel system components in four of the highest mileage 1992 Luminas.  Although the final report is not yet available, the initial reaction from GM was that they were extremely pleased with the results and that several of the key components showed significantly less wear in the ethanol vehicles that in conventional gasoline vehicles.<p>

Including the federal fleet, over 340 E-85 vehicles are currently in operation in the state.  GSA purchased 250 E-85 vehicles in the 1995 model year and has located 125 of these vehicles in the Chicago area.  Between state and federal purchase of E-85 vehicles in 1996, the number of E-85 vehicles opening in Illinois is expected to increase dramatically.<p>

In May 1995, General Motors announced that, beginning in the 1997 model year, all Chevrolet S-10 and GMC Sonoma light-duty pick-up trucks equipped with the 2.2 liter 4 cylinder engine will be flexible fuel vehicles optimized for E-85 fuel.  Recently, however, a "glitch" was discovered in the  2.2 liter engine (both in the gasoline and E-85 versions) that has delayed the introduction of the flexible fuel pick-up trucks until the 1998 model year.  The state of Illinois is currently testing three of these pre-production vehicles for GM in the CMS messenger mail vehicle fleet.  Similar vehicles are also being tested in Minnesota, Texas, Florida, and Colorado.<p>

<a name="#2"><hr></a>
<h4><a href="truck.htm"> 2. Ethanol-Powered Heavy Truck Fleet Program</a></h4>

Illinois, through DCCA, is working with the U.S. Department of Energy (USDOE) on a three year test and demonstration program for ethanol fuel in heavy duty, over-the-road trucks.<p>

The ethanol truck fleet is owned and operated by Archer Daniels Midland (ADM) of Decatur.  ADM purchased four (4) new White-GMC tractors powered by the DDC 6V-92TA dedicated ethanol engines and one (1) new White-GMC tractor using the conventional DDC 6V-92 diesel engine.<p>

The National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL) is providing about $368,000 in funding for the program.  DCCA is providing additional funding and personnel time towards the project.<p>

The four ethanol trucks are being used to carry liquefied carbon dioxide on routes that allow the trucks to return to the plant every night.  The engines are accumulating high number of usage hours and high mileage since they will be driven on interstate highways.  Over 1,000,000 miles have been accumulated on the four ethanol trucks to date.<p>

Overall, the operation of the four ethanol trucks has been comparable, or slightly better than, a comparable diesel equipped truck.  However, a few major mechanical problems have  occurred with the ADM ethanol trucks, especially with increasing mileage.  Three of the engines have been partially rebuilt with cylinder kits, two cylinder heads have been replaced, and fuel injector life is still considered a problem.  On a positive note, through, this program has led to the development of several new parts, such as titanium plunger injectors, that are now standard on all of their engines.<p>

The ethanol engine from ADM unit #92002 was removed and was shipped to Southwest Research Institute in San Antonio, Texas for transient emissions tests.  Emissions testing, and an engine tear-down and wear analysis, has just been completed.  This information will provide us with an idea as to the effects of engine degradation on emissions in ethanol fueled engines.  Preliminary results indicate that the ethanol engine showed minimal signs of wear and its' emissions, even after 300,000 miles of actual use were very low.<p>

DCCA has received support from Pekin Energy Company, Detroit Diesel Corporation, the Iowa Energy Office, the National Corn Growers, the Illinois Corn Growers and the Illinois Corn Marketing Board for this program.<p>


<a name="#3"><hr></a>
<h4><a href="bus.htm"> 3. Peoria Bus Demonstration Project</a></h4>

The Greater Peoria Mass Transit District (GPMTD) is conducting a comprehensive study on the sue of dedicated ethanol-powered bus engines.  Detroit Diesel Corporation (DDC) has developed a heavy-duty engine (Model 6V-92TA) which can run on 200 proof denatured ethanol.  This six cylinder, vee-configuration engine that produces 253 horsepower.  The engine was developed based on the design of the methanol engine which has been tested and demonstrated extensively in California and New York.  The changes of the engines include modifying the electronic control system, fuel injectors and glow plugs.<p>

Fourteen (14) buses are being operated on ethanol in Peoria where they have accumulated well over 1,000,000 miles total.  The emissions from these engines are being extensively monitored.  The USDOE/University of West Virginia Transportable Emissions Testing Center started testing the ethanol and several of Peoria's diesel buses in August 1992 for emission levels.  Emissions testing continues with the lab being in Peoria at least once a year.<p>

The performance of the engines is being continuously monitored and oil testing and wear evaluations are being performed.  Surveys of driver, riders and non-riders have been taken to determine driveability of the buses and public opinion of the project.  This is the largest ethanol bus demonstration project in the country and currently the only one using these new, dedicated ethanol engines.  DCCA has a contract with DDC to provide an additional on-site service and maintenance for the buses.<p>

DCCA worked with GPMTD, Detroit Diesel Corporation (DDC), Pekin Energy Company, and Growmark to develop a new ethanol fuel formulation for the ethanol buses that has reduced the cost of operation.  The new fuel is composed of 93% anhydrous ethanol, 5% anhydrous methanol (a qualified special fuel) and 2% kerosene (denaturant).  This formulation enables Growmark, the company delivering the fuel, to take advantage of the Ethanol Blender's Tax Credit and pass most of the Savings on to GPMTD.  The first shipment of E-93 fuel was delivered in march 1994.  Operational cost have been reduced from $0.58 per mile to about $0.35 per mile as a result of this.  The DDC engineers working on this projected approved the use of this fuel in the 6V-92TA ethanol engines being used in Peoria.<p>

DCCA has been working with, and providing information to, the Los Angeles mass transit districts on converting their methanol buses to ethanol fuel.  The methanol buses get about 1.1 miles per gallon opposed to the 2.1 miles per gallon for the ethanol buses.  Additionally, application of the Tax Credit has brought the price of ethanol down to the point where it can readily compete with methanol.  L.A. has converted 70 buses to ethanol and is considering converting the entire 333 bus methanol fleet to ethanol.  Both buses use the DDC 6V-92TA engine, so the engines can be converted to ethanol by simply reprogramming the DDEC II unit.<p>

The total project costs for Peoria are over $4 million with the Urban mass Transit Administration providing over $2 million.  Other contributing participants include the Illinois Department of Transportation, the Illinois Department of Commerce and community Affairs (formerly ENR), Pekin Energy Company, Detroit Diesel Corporation, the Illinois Corn Marketing Board, the Iowa corn Promotion Board, Illinois Central College and the Greater Peoria Mass Transit District.<p>

<a name="#4"><hr></a>
<h4>4. Ethanol Fuel-Cell Research Project</h4>

This is a research project aimed at the development, testing and demonstration of an ethanol fuel cell/battery bus in the Chicago area.  A fuel cell is a device with no moving parts that electrochemically generates electricity from hydrogen gas (derived from a base fuel through a chemical reformer) and oxygen gas.  A fuel cell bus powered by  methanol has already been developed by this project is designed to develop and test a reformer which will convert ethanol to hydrogen gas to be used in the fuel cell to produce electricity.  This new ethanol reformer will be installed and tested in a test-bed bus operated by PACE and located in the Chicago area.  The fuel cell bus is expected to be operating in Chicago by late 1997.<p>

The advantages of this system are obvious.  The primary source of fuel is low-grade ethanol, a readily renewable fuel derived from corn.  low-grade (150-170 proof) ethanol can be used since water is necessary for the reforming process.  Also, the low-grade ethanol is significantly less expensive than using gasoline quality, 200 proof ethanol.  The use of a reformer greatly reduces emissions and the use of electricity to power the bus means a very quiet bus with no additional emissions to the atmosphere.<p>

The USDOE and UMTA have already contributed over $6 million for the development of the methanol fuel cell/battery bus.  The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (former ENR has provided $325,000 to match with USDOE funds) to develop the ethanol reformer and will be a full partner in the project.  Additional funds will be needed after the reformer is fully developed scaled-up to a commercial size.<p>

USDOE has selected the consulting firm of A.D. Little as the subcontractor that will develop the reformer for the program.  A.D. Little successfully completed the feasibility study on the ethanol reformer, the 25kw laboratory scale-reformer, and along with Allied Chemical, has scaling-up the reformer for actual use in the fuel cell bus.<p>

<a name="#5"><hr></a>
<h4>5. Advanced Membrane Technology Project</h4>

Work on the initial University of Illinois continuous Reactor System has been successfully completed.  Testing of the laboratory-scale system proved so successful that a commercial-scale membrane reactor was installed and is being tested at Pekin Energy Company in Pekin, Illinois.<p>

Briefly, the membrane reactor system at Pekin Energy Company is being used in the saccharification stage of ethanol production.  Saccharification normally takes 20 to 21 hours to complete in a batch tank.  The membrane reactor selectively and continuously separates desired products (glucose and water) out of the system more efficiently than by conventional methods, thereby effectively increasing the rate of production.  The remaining starch and enzymes is retained to continue the saccharification process.  Further, the membrane reactor system is modular in design, and can be fitted to any production capacity or flow rate required by adding additional units.<p>

The Continuous Membrane Reactor at Pekin Energy has proven so successful that plans for a Continuous Membrane Fermenter (CMF) are being made.  This new membrane system will use advanced high-efficieny ceramic membranes to continuously remove ethanol from the fermentation process to increase production efficiency and reduce production costs.<p>

The Great Lakes REgional Biomass Energy Program awarded a $50,000 grant to the U of I for this project.  DCCA is contributing $220,000 to this new project with funds form the Illinois Alternative Energy Bond Fund.<p>

<a name="#6"><hr></a>
<h4>6. The Hydrated Ethanol Heavy Engine Development Project</h4>

This study is designed to reduce the cost of operation of ethanol fuel heavy-duty engines used in large trucks and urban transit buses by using less expensive, lower proof (5% water content) hydrated ethanol.<p>

Detroit Diesel Corporation (DDC) and the University of Illinois (U of I) will each perform endurance tests and monitor emissions on the heavy engines.  The engine being used for this study is the ethanol version of the DDC 6V-92TA engine.  DDC has successfully run a 100 hour performance test and monitor emissions using 190 proof ethanol fuel.  The U of I is currently performing a 500 hour endurance test and to optimize the engine emissions using the 190 proof ethanol fuel.<p>

<a name="#7"><hr></a>
<h4>7. The National Ethanol Production Research Facility</h4>

The United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) awarded $500,000 to Southern Illinois University at Edwardsville and the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign for a feasibility study to assess the need for a major ethanol production research facility that would be located in Illinois.<p>

Phase One of the feasibility study includes: Part 1 - A study identifying and outlining all of the recently completed and on-going ethanol research throughout the world completed by Western Reserve Associates, Part 2 - A study performed by Bryan & Bryan, Inc. that identified the top ten (10) research priority areas with the input of the ethanol industry, and Part 3 - A comprehensive evaluation of the ten (10) research priority areas, currently being performed by Stanley Consultants of Iowa.<p>

Phase Two of the project is the physical design and cost analysis for the actual research pilot plant facility.  This phase is currently underway and was awarded to Fluor Daniel of Chicago.<p>

Phase Three of the feasibility study will be the development of a business plan for the facility.<p>

If the facility study is positive and the facility is eventually constructed, the ethanol research facility would have a production capacity of 50,000 gallon per year and would be modular in design so that several different ethanol production technologies can be tested and developed at the same time.  It is anticipated that both university and industry research project would be scheduled to use the facility.<p>

<a name="#8"><hr></a>
<h4>8. Waste Sugar to Ethanol Project</h4>

DCCA staff has been working with the Illinois Department of Corrections and Vienna Correctional Center on a project that will use waste sugar form candy and soft drinks to supplement ethanol production from corn.  Vienna is currently receiving about 26,000 pounds of waste Pepsi from the local Pepsi bottler in Marion, Illinois.  The waste soft drink contains about 10% sugar and is being mixed with corn to produce ethanol.  Vienna wants to expand the research by mixing waste candy with corn to produce ethanol.<p>

This project will generate a regional directory of sugar producers/users, a regional assessment of waste sugar potential, an economic assessment of the project, and the results of actual production runs using waste sugar to produce ethanol.<p>

DCCA is providing $8,480 towards this innovative research project.  Vienna is also receiving $30,000 in funding from the Great Lakes Regional Biomass Energy Program for the project and $5,000 from the Illinois Corn Growers Association.<p>


<HR>
