<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>Energy, Coal & Recycling Programs</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>

<img src="../../graph/enr/enwise.jpg" width=170 height=185 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>
<h3 align=center>
"EnergyWise Homes of Illinois"<br>
A Service to Benefit Homeowners, Home Buyers, Builders and Lenders
</h3>
<HR>
<p>

<ul type=square>
<li>Reduce utility bill expenditures
<li>Enjoy a more comfortable home
<li>Finance energy improvements through savings
<li>Help sell your home
<li>Qualify for first or larger mortgage
</ul>

<h3>What is EnergyWise Homes of Illinois?</h3>

EnergyWise Homes of Illinois is a Home Energy Rating System (HERS) that is a voluntary, market driven program developed by a coalition of housing industry professionals, lenders, utilities and the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs.  The goal is to promote residential energy efficiency thereby making all housing more affordable.  The HERS assigns a numerical rating to existing houses or planned construction.<p>

The rating a house achieves results from a comparison to the Model Energy Code (MEC).  That value is placed on a scale of 0 to 100 with a score of 80 representing the MEC house and 100 being most energy-efficient.  The rating system also categorizes houses according to a star system (five stars being the most efficient, one star the least efficient).  Another important feature of the rating system is to provide an estimate of utility costs and provide recommendations for energy improvements.<p>

<h3>How is Energy Efficiency Determined?</h3>

The level of energy efficiency is determined by on-site inspections and testing of three major components of construction characteristics:<p>

<ul type=square>
<li>Building materials, insulation levels, window types<p>
<li>Efficiency levels of the heating, cooling and water heating equipment<p>
<li>Infiltration levels<p>
</ul>

Proposed construction is rated from plans.<p>

The HERS may be used by:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li>Homeowners or contractors to determine the cost-effectiveness of various energy-efficient measures<p>
<li>Builders or prospective homebuyers to determine annual energy costs for a new home<p>
<li>Lenders to verify energy costs fro EnergyEdge mortgages.<p>
</ul>

<h3>A Standard Mortgage vs. the Energy Edge Mortgage</h3>

If a buyer has:<p>
<pre>
* Monthly income of $2,500
* Down payment of 10%
* Mortgage rate of 8.5% 30 year term
</pre>

Standard Mortgage:<p>
<pre>
* Maximum monthly payment at 28% debt-to-income-ratios:     $700
* Maximum mortgage (90% appraised value):                $82,350
* Maximum house price                                    $91,500
</pre>

EnergyEdge Mortgage<p>
<pre>
* Maximum monthly payment at 30% debt-to-income-ratio:      $700
* Maximum mortgage (90% appraised value):                $88,200
* Maximum house price                                    $98,000
</pre>

<pre>
Added Buying Power with the EnergyEdge                    $6,500
</pre>

<h3>Can an Energy Rating Help Homeowners Obtain a Mortgage?</h3>

Homes that rate as energy efficient are eligible for an EnergyEdge mortgage which is a special loan adjustment that allows a purchaser to stretch their debt-to-income ratio.  The premise is that an efficient home will require less for utilities thereby freeing more money for mortgage payments.  The homeowner wins.  An Energy Improvement Mortgage allows owner of existing homes to include the cost of energy improvements in the mortgage.  The homeowner wins again.  These mortgages allow more people to get larger or more expensive homes while freeing up more cash to pay off the loan.<p>

<h3>How Can This Rating Help the Homeowner?</h3>

The rating a home achieves will allow for comparisons between structures and allow consumers to make informed decisions regarding energy costs associated with construction.  For the first time, a consumer will have access to energy cost savings data that supports the additional costs associated with energy-efficient building construction techniques.<p>

The rating will help consumer understand the overall energy costs associated with their most valuable asset, their home.  Letting people know where their energy dollars are being spent can help them make financial decisions regarding energy conservation products during construction and energy retrofit options in existing homes.<p>

<h3>What Will the Rater Do at my House?</h3>

A rater will make a site visit to obtain the data necessary to do the calculations. (New construction can be evaluated in the plan stage.)  A rater will measure the house, determine types, sizes and orientations of windows and doors, record information on the types and sizes of heating and cooling equipment and assess  infiltration rates by conducting a "blower door" test.<p>

The information gathered at the site is processed and computer generated reports and rating are produced.  The rating can be sued by owners or builders to help sell the property and the reports are used by owners and lenders to determine cost effective ways to improve the house.<p>

<h3>Take Action</h3>

Homes that are energy-efficient are more affordable, safer and more comfortable to live in, making homeowners happier people.<p>

To take advantage of these benefits, contact EnergyWise Homes of Illinois at the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs 217/785-2007; TDD 217/785-0211.<p>



<HR>
<STRONG>| <A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com">DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/energy.htm">Energy</A> |</STRONG>
</BODY>
