<HEAD><TITLE>Illinois Facts: The Illinois Workforce</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>Workforce & Job Training</FONT>
<HR>
<CENTER><H2>The Illinois Workforce</H2></CENTER>
<HR>

<P>
Illinois has an impressive workforce with the skills needed to help 
businesses succeed.   Nearly one-half of the state's workforce of six 
million are professionals, skilled technicians, craftspeople or machine 
operators.  More than 17 percent are employed in manufacturing.  And 
Illinois workers are well-educated -- 46.2 percent have gained education 
beyond high school.<P>

The Chicago metropolitan area is home to nearly four million of the 
state's workers.  Six other metropolitan areas include labor forces in the 
100,000 to 300,000 range.  An additional six metropolitan regions have 
labor forces in the 50,000 range.<P>

Illinois workers are known for their productivity.  While the 
Illinois manufacturing wage rate exceeds the U.S. average by 69 cents per 
hour, productivity in Illinois, measured in terms of value added per worker 
hour, exceeds the U.S. average by $1.86 per hour -- an important 
consideration for companies seeking to improve their bottom line.<P>


<CENTER><H4>Regional Labor Markets in Illinois/1994 Labor Force</H4></CENTER>
<CENTER><PRE>
Labor Market    				1994 Labor Force

Aurora/Elgin						  477.40
Bloomington/Normal					   75.40
Champaign/Urbana/Rantoul				   92.70
Chicago							2,624.70
Decatur							   59.30
East St. Louis						  277.20
Effingham						   60.40
Joliet							  196.20
Kankakee						   50.90
Mt. Vernon/Marion					   61.70
Peoria							  174.40
Quincy							   47.10
Rockford						  184.90
Rock Island/Moline					   98.60
Springfield						  105.10
</PRE></CENTER>

<HR>
<CENTER><H4>Non-Agricultural Employment by Industry in Illinois - 1994 Annual Averages</H4></CENTER>
<PRE><CENTER>
                                            (in thousands)

Mining                                      15
Manufacturing                              953
Wholesale and Retail Trade               1,276
Services                                 1,513
Construction                               213
Transportation and Public Utilities        317
Finance, Insurance and Real Estate         394
Government                                 783

TOTAL                                    5,463
</PRE></CENTER>
<HR>
<H3>Labor-Management Cooperation in Illinois</H3>

Although a few high-profile disputes can grab the headlines, an 
actual study of existing data shows that the level of cooperation between 
Illinois labor and management actually compares quite favorably with the 
nation as a whole.  Approximately 5,700 contract negotiations are conducted 
each year in Illinois, but less than 2 percent of those result in work 
stoppages and the trend is toward shorter work stoppages.  About one-fifth 
of the Illinois workforce is unionized, about the same as in other large 
industrial states.  And Illinois union workers are productive -- their 
median weekly wage is essentially equal to the national median wage while 
the differential wage rates between union and non-union workers appears to 
be substantially smaller in Illinois.<P>

Illinois is taking steps to foster even greater cooperation between 
labor and management.  A 12-member Illinois Labor-Management Cooperation 
Committee, appointed by the Governor, includes six members representing 
executive-level management of businesses that employ labor union members, 
and six members representing labor union leadership.  Six ex-officio non-
voting members representing top levels of state government round out the 
membership.<P>

Committee members see their main goal as fostering a positive labor 
relations image in Illinois to assist the state and its communities in 
attracting new businesses and retaining existing businesses and their jobs.  
To do so, the Committee, with support from the Department of Commerce and 
Community Affairs (DCCA), provides matching grants to help fund area labor-
management committees throughout the state.  Typical services provided by 
the area committees include educational conferences and workshops; annual 
recognition and awards events; newsletters and media coverage; special 
union construction project agreements; and development of videos, slide 
shows and speakers bureaus to raise awareness of the benefits of labor-
management cooperation.  In particular, the Committee has worked with area 
committees to promote the organization of worksite labor-management 
committees aimed at improving worker safety, working conditions, product or 
service quality, and overall labor relations.  These worksite committees 
have developed and delivered customized worker training programs, 
facilitated meetings and seminars, promoted team building, and helped 
workers access needed services, such as literacy and basic skills training, 
alcohol and drug abuse prevention programs and job site safety programs.<P>

The Committee also sponsors an annual awards program, "Labor-
Management Partners:  On the Road to High Performance," to highlight and 
recognize Illinois employer organizations that demonstrate positive labor-
management relations and cooperative work strategies.<P>

With the competition for jobs intensifying and rapid technological 
advances changing the workplace, Illinois has recognized the importance of 
fostering its competitive advantages.  A favorable labor-management 
environment is one of those assets.<P>

<HR>
