<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Illinois Facts: Education in Illinois</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>Workforce & Job Training</FONT>
<HR>
<CENTER><H2>Education in Illinois</H2></CENTER>
<HR>

<P>
Illinois residents are serious about the importance of education.
Education is a major component of the state's budget, with overall state
and local expenditures for elementary and secondary pupils ranking among
the top quartile in the nation. More than 46 percent of Illinois workers
have pursued education beyond the high school level, and the state has some
of the finest colleges and universities in the nation.<P>

<H3>Elementary and Secondary Education</H3>

Illinois has more than 900 public school districts, nearly 4,100
public schools and nearly 1,400 non-public schools. In 1994, there were
more than 2.2 million pupils attending Illinois public schools and more
than 116,000 students graduated from Illinois high schools.<P>

<H3>Community Colleges</H3>

Vocational and technical education is important in Illinois.
Illinois has 49 community colleges and 40 college districts. In fall 1994,
nearly 350,000 students were enrolled in credit courses at these colleges
-- the third-largest community college enrollment in the nation. The
colleges provide instruction and workforce preparation in more than 240
occupational specialties. The Community College Board estimates more than
90 percent of its graduates remain in Illinois to work. Many community
college students are working adults.<P>

During 1994, 37 community college districts provided customized job
training for businesses and industries in their areas. The colleges work
with area businesses to design or broker programs specifically tailored to
the needs of area employers. The businesses determine the type of training
needed, work out a schedule to fit their operations, and decide on the
length of the training. Customized training is offered in company
facilities or on college campuses, and contract training is provided to
upgrade the skills of current employees and train new workers. The colleges
also help businesses acquire training funds through various state and
federal programs.<P>

In 1994, Illinois community colleges provided $3.5 million for
workforce preparation grants. The colleges provided customized training to
1,952 companies, serving 58,516 employees.<P>

More than 30 Illinois community colleges also offer an innovative
new policy -- "educational guarantees." The policy guarantees that
graduates of occupational/technical programs will have the skills needed by
area businesses and industries. If an employer or employee finds the skills
lacking, the employee may repeat the training at no cost.<P>

<H3>Colleges and Universities</H3>

<P>Overall, Illinois ranks fifth in the nation in the number of higher
education institutions, with 184 degree-granting institutions that enrolled
more than 740,000 students and awarded more than 123,000 degrees in 1993.
There are 12 public universities that offer a full range of educational
programs, including nearly 700 baccalaureate degree programs; more than 550
master's degree programs; nearly 200 doctoral programs; and first
professional degrees in medicine, veterinary medicine, dentistry and law.
In the private sector, 105 institutions are not-for-profit colleges and
universities, while the remaining 18 are proprietary.<P>

Many Illinois institutions have world-class reputations. According
to a Business Week magazine ranking of top U.S. business schools, two --
the Kellogg School of Business at Northwestern University and the
University of Chicago -- rank in the top three. Both universities' business
schools also received top ranking in a U.S. News & World Report study. The
University of Illinois in Urbana-Champaign garnered top honors from U.S.
News & World Report for its graduate school of engineering. The National
Association of State Boards of Accountancy reported that Sangamon State
University (now the University of Illinois-Springfield), the University of
Illinois at Urbana-Champaign and Northern Illinois University ranked in the
top 20 of 400 schools for the pass rate of their students taking the
Certified Public Accountant exam.<P>

<HR>
