<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Energy Programs</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>Energy, Coal & Recycling Programs</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>

<CENTER><H3>Energy NET for Grade 7-12</H3></CENTER>
<HR>

ILEED (the Illinois Energy Education Development Project) is pleased to join the TECH 2000, a coalition of education, government and business groups, to sponsor EnergyNet for the 1995-1996 school year.<p>

Students who use classroom technology as part of their daily routine will be better prepared to enter the information age as adults.<p>

<blockquote>
"With the necessary support, every classroom in Illinois can have the technology available to teach academic basics and job skills to our students-helping them to become productive workers and leaders in the 21st century."<p>

<em>Bob Kustra, Illinois Lieutenant Governor</em>
</blockquote>

<hr>
<h3>What is EnergyNet?</h3>

Basically, EnergyNet is an Energy Conservation Telecommunication Project for students in grades 7-12.  But EnergyNet is so much more!  EnergyNet is changing the roles of students and teachers.<p>

Teachers have discovered professional and instructional resources far beyond the classroom  They see themselves shifting away from the role of "information giver" to roles that involve management, coaching and facilitating student activities and teamwork.<p>

As a teacher you can involve your students in the excitement of collaborative research and multi-disciplinary, project-based learning using telecommunications as the tool to discover resources beyond the classroom.<p>

EnergyNet is an innovative project in which students form research teams to:<p>

<ul type=square>
<li>evaluate their school's energy use.<p>
<li>share their data and questions with other students over the Internet network; and<p>
<li>prepare energy conservation recommendations for their school and community<p>
</ul>

<blockquote>
"The kids want to do this project.  It's interesting, it gives us hands-on experience and lets us do things the way we want to do them, not the way a teacher tells us to."<p>

<em>Shane White, Student, East Peoria High School</em>
</blockquote>

EnergyNet gives your students a chance to:<p>

<ul type=square>
<li>collaborate by working in teams of students in their own classroom;<p>
<li>specialized in energy issues;<p>
<li>analyze complex energy data using computerized programs;<p>
<li>interact with peers and with on-line scientists and professionals through telecommunications.<p>
</ul>

<hr>
<h3>How Do I Join EnergyNet?</h3>

Be a part of this exciting program!  Join the increasing number of schools throughout Illinois who participate in the EnergyNet Project.  Training sessions for teacher/student teams are FREE to Illinois schools during the 1995-1996 school year.  For more information contact:<p>

<ul>
Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs<br>
ILEED Program<br>
100 W. Randolph Street, Suite 3-400<br>
Chicago, Illinois 60601<br>
312/814-3467; TDD 312/419-0667<p>
</ul>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com">DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/energy.htm">Energy</A> |</STRONG>
