<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop Business Information Center Search</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/dcca/graph/fs/firststopback.gif" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000000" VLINK="#0000A0" ALINK="#0000A0">

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td colspan=1 valign=top>


<table width=125 >
<td valign=top align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fsdcca.gif"><p>
<p><br><p><br>
<p><br><p><br>
<p><br><p><br>
<a href="fsm1.htm"> <img src="../graph/fs/fshome.gif" alt="First Stop" width=88 height=36 border=0></a>
<p>
<a href="fsasst.htm"> <img src="../graph/fs/whocanhelp.gif" alt="Who Can Help?" width=88 height=45 border=0></a>
<p>
<a href="../home.htm"> <img src="../graph/fs/dcca.gif" alt="DCCA" width=88 height=38 border=0></a>
</td>
</table>


<td colspan=1 align=left>
<table width=475 >

<td valign=top>
<h3 align=center>Illinois Department of Commerce & Community Affairs</h3>
<center>
<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/Fslogo2.GIF" alt="First Stop Logo" width=251 height=120>
<br clear=all>
<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fsbar.gif">
<img src="../Graph/FS/SearchText.GIF" alt="First Stop Search" width=226 height=33>
<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fsbar.gif">
</center>
<br clear=all>
<p>


<p>Use our <strong>Word Search</strong> feature to find information about a specific subject.<p>

Enter a word or words below and press 'Excite Search'.  All First Stop government profile types,  agency, business requirements and assistance, will be scanned for your selected words.  You will be given a list of all documents in the First Stop database that match your selection. You can view each document by selecting it from the list returned. 

<form action="http://www.ilcommerce.com/cgi-bin/AT-First_Stopsearch.exe" method="POST">
Enter:
<input name="mhremove" value="dccaweb\\" type=hidden>
<br><input type="radio" name="mode" value="concept"> words describing a concept <em><b>or</b></em>
<br><input type="radio" name="mode" value="simple" checked> keywords you wish to find information about:
<br><textarea name="search" cols=45 rows=4></textarea>
<p><input type="image" name="SearchButton" border=0 src="/Architext/pictures/AT-search_button.gif">

<input type="hidden" name="sp" value="sp">
</form><p> Documentation about <a href="/Architext/AT-queryhelp.html">making queries</a> is available.<p><p>

<!--
<a name="Tips"><hr></a>

<center><h3>TIPS for using the WORD SEARCH function</h3></center>

Be careful spelling the word(s) you enter!  It will search for exactly what 
you specify.<p>  

The search is not case sensitive.  For example, if you type 'INCOME', the 
system will return a list of documents that have 'INCOME', 'Income' or 
'income'.<p>

The system will return a list of documents that have ALL of the words that 
you enter.  Thus, if you enter INCOME TAX, you will get a list of all 
information profiles that have BOTH 'INCOME' and 'TAX'.  They need not be 
together in a document but only profiles containing BOTH (all) words will 
be selected for you.<p>  

The search function uses the entire word, as entered, in selecting 
'matching' documents.  It does not return documents containing `partial' 
word matches.  For example, if you input 'ENVIRONMENT' for your search, you 
will not get documents that may only contain the word 'ENVIRONMENTAL' or 
vice versa.<p>  

Start by using single words rather than combinations.  You are basically 
'guessing' what words may be used in a document that covers the subject 
matter you need.  After you get a list of documents with one word relating 
to your subject, try limiting the number of matching documents by adding 
another word.  For example, if you start with 'ENVIRONMENTAL', you may get 
a long list of documents.  You can then do another search using 
'ENVIRONMENTAL REGULATIONS' to reduce the list to only those documents more 
closely relating to your desired subject.<p>  

If you don't find what you need on your first selection, try another word 
or words that would logically have the same or similar meaning.  Using 
search functions can be an art.  Don't be discouraged when you don't 
initially find something that you request.<p> 

<em>Note: </em> The quotation marks in the examples above are for clarity only.  
Don't use them when you input your word selections.<p>
-->


