<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>NetWorks, February 1996</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>

<H3>DCCA to provide census data to small businesses</H3>

<H4>By Ed Taft</H4>

The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) is establishing a new Business and Industry Data Center (BIDC) Program to provide census data and other usable information to small businesses. Started in 1988 by the U.S. Census Bureau as an extension of its existing State Data Center Program, the BIDC Program will meet the growing need by decision makers for effective use of economic statistics. The Census Bureau intends to use the BIDC Program as a means to increase the public's awareness of economic and demographic data and to make wider use of this data.<P>

DCCA will help meet this need by providing small businesses, independent contractors and future businesses in Illinois convenient access to statistical data and other sources of practical information. Our goal is to enhance the ability of small businesses to plan, market, manage and expand their businesses in Illinois and throughout the world. The BIDC will create a system of regional and local affiliates capable of providing basic information to the small business community, besides completing complex analysis as needed and performing regional economic analyses.<P>

Five Regional Affiliates (RA) will be responsible for collecting and disseminating information to both the end users of the data and to the local affiliates. The RA also will provide a regional economic analysis on a regular basis, furnish expertise in one or more data bases and provide assistance to local affiliates and data users as needed. <P>

Within each region three to five Local Affiliates will be created. Local Affiliates will be responsible for dealing directly with small businesses and other data users; will provide basic census economic and demographic information and other data prepared by the Regional Affiliates or the state; and will offer technical assistance in basic data interpretation. As of press time, centers have been selected and negotiations are proceeding.<P>

The Regional Affiliate will respond to requests that involve more complex analysis or interpretation. For more information on BIDC or to contact your Regional/Local Affiliate, call 217/785-7545.<P>

Ed Taft is the program coordinator of the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs' Business and Industry Data Center.<P>

<H3>Dividends:  another success story</H3>

<H4>By Boyd Palmer</H4>

When co-owners Terry Havens and Charles Ross Lohr needed an infusion of capital for their fledgling product development company, Phoenix Paper Products Inc. based in Lostant, Illinois, the Illinois Valley Community College Small Business Development Center (IVCC SBDC) came through by facilitating additional avenues for financial opportunity in the form of private and public financing. And that, the partners agree, made all the difference for success.<P>

The SBDC provides an option for small businesses such as Phoenix Paper Products to access resources that will allow for it to adjust to our rapidly changing economy. Through the management and technical assistance of the SBDC a company can find a way to make their business run more efficiently.<P>

The birth of this venture occurred as a result of the merger of engineering skills of both Haven and Lohr who met by chance while serving on the Wenona city council. An engineer who attended the University of Arkansas at Little Rock, Haven was most recently a partner in C&H Construction Co., a millwright and general contracting company specializing in bulk handling of equipment and facilities. Lohr, who formerly worked for an area company, developed and fabricated machinery, along with methods of introducing shredded newspaper into compression chamber systems using no hydrocarbons or any other source of lubricators which might harm the ecosystem. As a result, both individuals have been recognized in their respective fields by obtaining patents on ideas relating to their environmental concerns.<P>

Consequently Phoenix Paper Products has developed and is in the process of marketing a unique line of environmentally friendly products made specifically from post-consumer newsprint. Currently a majority of the company's future output will be directed and marketed as a substitute for sphagnum peat moss which at the moment is a non-renewable resource imported from the Canadian wetlands. It is expected in time to increase in price as a result of environmental overcultivation. Other disadvantages concerning the use of peat moss are that it's cumbersome to handle, may contain harmful microbes and mining is weather dependent.<P>

Designated product markets for the company include mushroom casings, peat moss replacement for horticulture purpose and cat litter which will be used as both commercial and industrial absorbents.<P>

Thanks to collaboration of the SBDC, First Midwest Bank and the Upper Illinois River Valley Community Development Corporation, the Phoenix Paper Products group have shown with promising results that entrepreneurs can and will effectively utilize the many workable resources provided to Illinois business.<P>

"Organizations such as the Small Business Development Center, staffed with knowledgeable personnel, are critical to the survival and growth of small business," Haven said.<P>

Boyd Palmer is the director of the Small Business Development Center at Illinois Valley Community College in Oglesby.<P>

<STRONG><EM>EDITOR'S NOTE:</EM></STRONG> We select our success stories not because we endorse any particular company, center or activities, but because we believe the experiences in the story will be useful and of interest to our readers. We want your success stories! Contact us for editorial deadlines at 312/814-2814; TDD, 800/419-0667; Internet, net.works@accessil.com.


<H3>10 Reasons for Small Business Failures</H3>

<EM>Editor's Note: Portions of this article recently appeared in the Springfield Business Journal.</EM>

<H4>By Freida L. Schreck</H4>

Wanting your own business is part of the American dream that can rapidly turn into an American nightmare when the business fails.<P>

Statistics on business failure are staggering. Some numbers suggest that three out of five businesses fail in the first year. Numbers are important to statisticians. However small business owners aren't as concerned with numbers as they are with reasons. They want to know why business failure rates are so high as well as what can be done to avoid becoming a statistic. I don't have all the answers to the question but I can share with you ten of the most common problems encountered by directors of the Illinois Small Business Development Center Network.<P>

<H4>1. Lack of a business plan</H4>
The primary reason for failure is lack of a business plan. Builders don't start construction without a plan, nor do most people take a vacation without determining a destination, time frame, how much money they are going to need and travel arrangements. A business is going to take a large amount of an owner's time and money, and thus should be given more consideration than a trip to the grocery store.<P>

<H4>2. Lack of market research</H4>
Marketing is a much misunderstood part of a business plan. Conducting market research will assist in determining whether the need for a product or service is perceived or real. Just because family and friends think we have a great idea of a great product does not mean that our potential customer base will too. A marketing survey is the tool that can help an owner understand who the client is and what their needs really are.<P>

<H4>3. Underestimating competition</H4>
Competition is not necessarily bad; it can be healthy for business, some people say that there is "no one out there with anything like mine." Further research usually leads them to the realization that they do not understand what competition means or who the competition is. How can knowing the competition help you be successful? Searching out strengths and weaknesses, pricing, location, product line and customer service policies can provide the information needed to produce your marketing strategy.<P>

<H4>4. Lack of insurance</H4>
It is not uncommon for a business to start on a shoestring. If a line item in the projected budget can be eliminated or postponed it will be. One such line item is insurance. What happens to a business if there is fire, flood or some other disaster? The owner may have the knowledge and skills to continue but how can they replace equipment, furniture, office supplies and computer equipment? Was the cash flow strong enough to allow for a cash reserve? Are there existing loans that would make it difficult to obtain another? If the business is destroyed how much will be lost because of the interruption? A competent insurance agency tailor coverage to meet the needs of a business at a reasonable cost.<P>

<H4>5. Lack of customer service</H4>
We have all heard "the customer is always right." There may be times when we disagree; However customer service is an important key to success. Someone related an incident to me that confirmed my belief that if you can't treat customers with politeness you will lose them. A man came into a small shop to purchase items in excess of $150. When he approached the cash register, he explained that he didn't have the odd pennies necessary and the owner if she would take the even amount. The owner responded, "If you don't have the money, put something back." He did - all of it. I'm sure the story didn't end when the man left the shop. You can be assured that he told all of his friends how rude the owner of the shop was and encouraged them not to shop there. The shop closed within six months of opening.<P>

<H4>6. Lack of experience and knowledge of the industry</H4>
A person may be a great cook and want to start a restaurant but have no idea what it takes to operate one. They don't address some basic concerns such as how much food needs to be prepared each day, what is the cost of food items, how to prepare food items so that the items on an order are ready at the same time, how much to budget for expenses and how much money is needed to start. When giving loans the U.S. Small Business Administration requires three years of experience in the industry. If the owner doesn't meet this requirement, a qualified manager must be hired.<P>

<H4>7. Lack of operating capital</H4>
I can't count the number of times people have told me, "I think I only need $2,000 to start." They try to start on a shoestring and don't realize that lack of capital is the single most common death trap for start-ups. What does adequate operating capital consist of? There are several theories:
Figure start-up costs, then double them.<P>
Start-up costs plus six months protected expenses.<P>
Start-up costs plus one year's projected expenses.<P>

These theories are all adequate but finding out how much capital is needed takes research and planning. Completion of a list of start-up costs is a starting point but must have a projected monthly cash flow statement to accompany it. The monthly cash flow will assist in recognizing what your break even point is and what your monthly expenses may be.<P>

<H4>8. Lack of proper site/location</H4>
"Location - location - location." This statement is often referred to in text books covering business plan development as the most important factor in success or failure of a business. There are many times to consider before selecting the proper site. Consider traffic counts, other business failures in the same location, area demographics and cost of utilities and rental space. Just because it's cheap doesn't make it the ideal spot for a business.<P>

<H4>9. Changes in government regulations</H4>
With today's concerns about the environment and other issues, some businesses are caught in the crossfire because they didn't expect to be mandated to make major modification to meet changing rules and regulations. The modifications can cause severe financial strain.<P>

<H4>10. Lack of fear of failure</H4>
Healthy fear of failure can be a good trait for a small business owner to have. Entrepreneurs are supposed to be "risk takers" but that doesn't mean that they need to think that they are immune to failure. Be cautious and realize that even Fortune 500 companies have failed.<P>

Freida L. Schreck is the director of the Small Business Development Center at Lincoln Land Community College in Springfield.<P>


<H3>BALMER ELECTED ISBDA CHAIR </H3>

<H4>By Mark Petrilli</H4>

Montrey Balmer, director of the Procurement Technical Assistance Center (PTAC) at Moraine Valley Community College in Palos Hills, was recently chosen as chairperson of the Illinois Small Business Development Association (ISBDA) at the organization's annual meeting in Peoria.<P>

ISBDA is a statewide association organized to support and promote the services provided by the programs that make up the Illinois Small Business Development Center Network (ISBDCN) and other not-for-profit organizations which provide small business assistance. Balmer has served on the coordinating council for ISBDA and is also one of the founding members of the association. <P>

"Montrey is one of the most dedicated and committed members we have," said outgoing ISBDA chair, Denise Mikulski, director of the Small Business Development Center at Joliet Junior College. "She is a pleasure to work with and is largely responsible for the success of our meetings," referring to Balmer's work at organizing the agenda and coordinating the training for the ISBDA spring and fall meetings.<P>

Since becoming director of the Moraine Valley PTAC in 1989, Balmer has counseled over 500 businesses seeking government contracts, assisting them is securing over $40 million in contract awards. Assistance provided to these firms has ranged from general procurement counseling and training to detailed one-on-one counseling in such areas as government marketing, bid preparation, contract administration and electronic data interchange (EDI). <P>

In addition to ISBDA, Balmer has actively participated in many other professional organizations including the National Contract Management Association, the American Defense Preparedness Association and the Association of Government Marketing Assistance Specialists (AGMAS). In 1991 she was recognized by AGMAS as a Certified Contracting Assistance Specialist.<P>

Realizing the importance of keeping up with developments in her field, Balmer has extensive continuing training and education in government procurement in areas such as the federal acquisition process, contract management and electronic commerce.<P>

"Montrey is always willing to support and share information with the other centers," said Lois VanMeter, statewide manager of the Illinois Procurement Technical Assistance Center program. "She is one of the most efficient, effective and capable directors in the state if not the country."<P>

Balmer's unselfishness has not gone unrecognized by her peers. She is a recipient of the Outstanding Communications Award and has been honored as Outstanding Director for her work in the PTAC program.<P>

During her term as chairperson of ISBDA Balmer wants to continue to develop the association's spring and fall meetings as excellent opportunities for the members of the ISBDCN to come together and share information and experiences.<P>

"We also need to continue providing high quality training programs which effectively meet the needs of our membership," Balmer said.<P>

Another area which Balmer would like to emphasize during the coming year is increasing the awareness of the services available through ISBDCN. She wants to continue working closely with the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs to increase the access of the Network by the business community and continue developing the ISBDCN as a vital part of the agency's strategy to serve small businesses in Illinois.<P>

Balmer also believes that ISBDA should take a more pro-active role in keeping legislative and community leaders informed about ISBDCN and its benefits to small business.<P>

For more information about ISBDA and the PTAC delivery system, contact Montrey Balmer at 708/974-5469; TDD Relay, 800/526-0844.<P>

Mark Petrilli is the chief of the Office of Network Center Operations of the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs' Illinois Small Business Development Center Network.<P>


<H3>Edgar expands environmental amnesty</H3>

Governor Jim Edgar announced he is expanding a successful initiative to bring businesses into compliance with environmental laws by encouraging them to cooperate with state regulators.<P>

"Through our innovative 'Clean Break' program, we are protecting both the environment and bottom line by stressing cooperation as a very effective alternative to confrontation," Edgar said.<P>

"In less than a year, we have demonstrated through a pilot program in Winnebago and Boone counties that we can achieve positive results by offering amnesty from heavy fines to those small businesses that truly want to be good citizens," Edgar said.<P>

More than 60 businesses have agreed to come into compliance with environmental laws since Edgar launched "Clean Break" in April 1995. By taking advantage of the program, they spared themselves more than $600,000 in potential penalties for violating environmental regulations.<P>

The expansion announced by Edgar will cover about 4,000 printing operations and 15,000 automobile maintenance businesses statewide. Those businesses are faced for the first time with clean-air permitting requirements, and associations representing them have expressed an interest in participating in the "Clean Break" program.<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, Edgar's senior adviser on economic development, said, "Through this initiative, we have brought common sense back into the regulatory process. It's good for the environment and it's good for employers because it saves them from high legal fees and protracted bureaucratic battles."<P>

The amnesty program allows businesses with no more than 200 employees to anonymously learn from the Illinois Environmental Protection Agency (IEPA) what steps must be taken to comply with environmental regulations. After a preliminary assessment, the small businesses may enter into an agreement that establishes a schedule for them to reach compliance and provides them with amnesty from enforcement action. The IEPA also provides the technical assistance needed for the firms to fulfill their commitment. <P>

Dennis Whetstone, director of the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) said, "We were delighted to play a role in a project of such sweeping significance and one that is so important to the business community." <P>

To participate in the Clean Break project, any eligible small business may contact IEPA's Small Business Office at 217/524-2743; TDD, 217/782-9143 or DCCA's Small Business Environmental Assistance Helpline at 800/252-3998; TDD, 800/785-6055.<P>


<H3>EPA limits underground tank liability</H3>

Henry and Gladys Johnson own a small gas station. When the Johnsons decided to upgrade their three underground storage tanks with corrosion protection and spill and overfill prevention to meet U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) requirements, they wanted to get started well in advance of the 1998 deadline. The Johnsons believed that making the upgrades now could prevent leaks later and help them avoid paying possibly higher costs during the 1998 rush. They decided to apply for a loan to begin work on the upgrades right away, and they turned to their local bank.<P>

Armed with their recent tax returns, the Johnsons met with the loan officer of the bank. At the end of their meeting, however, the Johnsons left disappointed. The loan officer "regretted" that the bank could not loan the Johnsons the money they needed. He explained that the Johnsons would need to use the gas station itself as collateral for the loan and, by doing that, the bank could eventually become an "owner" of the station. What if the Johnsons were unable to repay the loan and the tanks should happen to leak? The bank would foreclose on their gas station. The bank would be held responsible for any cleanup costs that might result. Since the bank could not afford that liability -- the so-called "lender liability" -- it would not make the loan.<P>

To help station owners like the Johnsons and to relieve some of the pressure that banks and other lending institutions feel to avoid any risk of liability, EPA has published a new regulation. The new lender liability rule limits the liability of banks and other lenders who hold security interests in property on which petroleum underground storage tanks (USTs) are located. <P>

"We hope that with this rule in place, banks will be more willing to make money available to UST owners and operators who need it to make improvements to their tanks in order to meet environmental regulations," says Lisa Lund, Acting Director of EPA's Office of Underground Storage Tanks. <P>

According to Lund, EPA is particularly concerned about the ability of small UST owners and operators -- the "Mom & Pop" businesses -- to meet the federal UST upgrading and replacement requirements. In the past, lenders have been extremely reluctant to make loans to small businesses such as gas stations for fear of becoming liable for cleanup costs in situations where the business goes bankrupt and the lender takes possession of the property through foreclosure.<P>

Until now, lenders have been very uncertain about the extent of their liability for UST-related problems. Subtitle I of the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act (RCRA) contains a "security interest exemption" that explicitly exempts lenders from liability for clean up of releases from petroleum USTs. However, many lenders don't know about this exemption, and many others don't know exactly what it covers. <P>

More confusion has resulted from court cases regarding Superfund lender liability. In 1994, the D.C. Circuit Court of Appeals vacated (annulled) EPA's Superfund lender liability rule, which attempted to clarify the security interest exemption in the Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability Act (CERCLA). The court's decision and EPA's Superfund rule were limited to actions taken under CERCLA. Because it involves actions taken under RCRA, the UST lender liability rule is not affected. However confusion on the part of the public between the two lender liability rules is understandable.<P>

Under the UST lender liability rule, a bank or other lender that issues a loan on an UST or on a property on which the UST is located where the lender holds the property as collateral does not have to meet the federal UST requirements either before or after foreclosure, if the lender meets the following conditions:<P>
Does not engage in petroleum production, refining and marketing<BR>
Does not manage or operate the UST<BR>
Does not store petroleum in the UST after foreclosure<BR>

The rule lists certain actions, including foreclosure, that lenders can take to manage and protect their collateral and still not be held responsible for meeting the federal UST regulations under RCRA Subtitle I. For example, a lender can perform environmental inspections or audits, arrange for cleanup of leaking tanks or close USTs temporarily or permanently without incurring liability under the federal regulations.<P>

In addition, lenders will be able to regularly monitor or investigate the borrower's collateral, business condition and financial health; require that the property be maintained in an environmentally sound manner; and advise the borrower to clean up the property if it is contaminated.<P>

Under this new rule, a lender can foreclose on and sell its UST collateral without incurring Subtitle I liability if there is a current operator at the site who can be held liable for compliance. Otherwise, the lender must empty the UST(s) within 60 days after foreclosure and either temporarily or permanently close the UST(s).<P>

The rule also describes activities that the lender cannot undertake without becoming responsible for UST cleanup costs. For example, a lender who chooses to operate its USTs is not eligible for the regulatory exemption. The lender could be required to clean up any contamination if the tank leaked and may be responsible for meeting the UST technical standards and financial responsibility requirements of Subtitle I.<P>

For additional information on the UST lender liability rule or for a copy of the Federal Register notice, contact EPA's RCRA/Superfund Hotline at 800/424-9346 or the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs' Small Business Environmental Assistance Program at 800/252-3998; TDD, 800/785-6055.<P>


<H3>Regulations Hurt Small Businesses More Than Others</H3>

Despite progress to reduce regulatory burdens on small businesses, the costs of regulation, paperwork and tax compliance continue to fall disproportionately on small firms with fewer than 500 employees, according to a new study prepared by the U.S. Small Business Administration's (SBA) Office of Advocacy.<P>

The study, "The Changing Burden of Regulation, Paperwork and Tax Compliance on Small Business," reveals among its major findings that the small business regulatory burden is 1.5 times that of large businesses.<P>

"Small businesses bear 63 percent of the total regulatory burden while accounting for approximately 50 percent of employment and sales," according to Jere W. Glover, the SBA's chief counsel for advocacy. "What becomes obvious from analyzing this study is that small businesses -- the very engine powering the American economy today -- are being unfairly burdened by regulations."<P>

Glover said that the heavier regulatory load carried by small business acts as a drag on a powerful economic engine. "If the economy is going to put the pedal to the metal, so to speak, then something more must be done to release the brake that regulation is imposing on small business."<P>

The study also shows that such an inequitable allocation of regulatory costs is not good public policy and that, to help remedy this, public policymakers need to strengthen the Regulatory Flexibility Act to provide for judicial review for small firms.<P>

The Office of Advocacy research analyzes a number of other studies, especially one by Thomas Hopkins of the Rochester Institute of Technology that attempts to determine the total cost of regulation and to allocate those costs to business and industry by size. The Advocacy study takes the total cost of regulation, allocates it by size and industry and compares the cost per employee in large businesses with the cost per employee in small businesses.<P>

Advocacy's chief counsel presented some of the key findings of the study:<P>

In the Hopkins study, the average cost of regulation per employee in firms with fewer than 20 employees is $5,532; in firms with 20-499 employees, $5,298; and $2,979 in firms with more than 500 employees.<P>
According to the Hopkins study, such disparities mean that the regulatory cost per employee for the smallest firms is 1.86 times than for the largest companies.<P>
While small businesses account for approximately 50 percent of employment as well as about 50 percent of gross domestic product, small firm entrepreneurs bear 63 percent of the regulatory burden on all businesses.<P>
Of these regulatory burdens, the most significant to small firms are tax-and payroll-related paperwork. This paperwork burden is especially regressive in that it falls much more heavily on the small business person.<P>

The results of the Advocacy study were released this past fall at a joint hearing of the U.S. Senate and House Small Business Committees.<P>



<H3>New program helps Illinois manufacturers COMPETE</H3>

Coalition for Manufacturing Performance through Technology (COMPETE) is Illinois' effort to build a statewide system of Manufacturing Extension Centers (MEC). The mission of MECs is to assist small and mid-sized manufacturers with manufacturing technology advancement and modernization services to the point of continuous improvement of business practices within the firm.<P>

A network of geographically-based MECs and specialized centers deliver manufacturing and modernization services such as performance benchmarking, modernization assessments, and engineering and technical consulting.<P>

MECs provide access to appropriate technologies, technical information and specialized technology resources in computer information systems, electronic communications, environmental compliance and pollution prevention.<P>

MECs link to other organizations providing workforce training; business marketing, and management and financial packaging.<P>

Companies can benefit from services through increased sales, reduced expenses, and productivity and quality improvements.<P>

The regional MECs are staffed with engineers and professionals who have practical experience in the manufacturing workplace. These specialists work with a company to make confidential recommendations for improvements. They have access to a wide range of industry experts and the resources of universities, community colleges and private consultants to implement the work plans and improvement projects which the company determines are needed.<P>

MECs are partially funded through the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, as part of the Illinois Technology Challenge Grant program and the National Institute of Standards and Technology.<P>

For more information about the Manufacturing Extension Center in your area call the center nearest you or call the COMPETE Office at 312/814-8759; TDD, 800/419-0667 to learn how your company can benefit from technology, business and workforce development services.<P>

Manufacturing Extension Center Locations<BR>
Chicago Manufacturing Center<BR>
Chicago 312/265-2020 <BR>
Serves: Chicago area<P>

Joliet Junior College MEC<BR>
Joliet 815/727-6544<BR>
Serves: Will and Grundy counties<P>

North Central Illinois MEC<BR>
Rockford 815/654-5501<BR>
Serves: Rockford, Elgin and surrounding areas<P>

Central Illinois MEC<BR>
