<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: CCI News, Vol #1, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs</h3>
<center><img src="../../graph/cci.gif" alt="CCI News " width=393 height=107 ></center>
<h3 align=center> Volume #1, 1996</h3>
<hr>

<h3>DON'T MISS IT</h3>

Here's a conference you won't want to miss!  The upcoming COMPETITIVE COMMUNITIES CONFERENCE is designed to five you direct access to people with "hand on" experience.  Hear from business people and developers about what they look for, talk with mayors, chamber executives and other local leaders who have been successful, and gain access to policy developers familiar with the national and global markets.<p>

The Conference will be held at the Renaissance Hotel Springfield, with programs beginning at 9 a.m. on Wednesday April 3 and closing at 3 p.m. on Thursday April 4.  Registration is from 1 to 5 p.m. Tuesday April 2.<p>

A $50 single and $65 double rate have been secured for conference participants.  You may make your room reservation by calling 217/544-8800 (TDD Relay, 800/526-0844).<p>

Conference registration may be made by sending a check for $50 per person, made payable to the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, with the names of the registrants and the community or organization you represent to:<p>
<dl><dd>
Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs<br>
Accounting Office<br>
Attention: Lynda Coker<br>
620 East Adams, Second Floor<br>
Springfield, IL 62701<br>
</dd></dl>

<hr>
<h3>BUSINESS LOOK FOR INFORMATION<br>
<em>by: Rich Funderburk</em></h3>

For the last few issues, we've been talking about things businesses look for when choosing locations.  It is important for you to understand what drives the information needs of businesses looking for new locations or places to expand.<p>

Long before anyone ever makes contact with a community, the business will develop a needs assessment and develop information criteria to help them make a decision on whether to move, expand, or simply expand into a different labor force or market area.  That need will vary greatly depending on what the project is and the company or person using that information.<p>

For example, a business that employs 100 people will want more labor information than one that employs 10.  An insurance company will need a different kind of work force and have different information needs than a company that is going to put in a standing operation.  Each kind of business has its own needs and its own evaluation criteria.<p>

These information needs have increased by a huge percentage in the last 25 years.  Much of that increase is due to the increase in government regulations such as zoning.  EPA and OSHA to name a few.  As community leaders, this means you need to collect more information for your database, and develop rapport with agencies that create databases, regulate or administer the regulations that control these businesses.  In some cases, you might need to hire a consultant to help you.

But before you hire anyone, your community organization should understand the need for and the use of this information.  Let me stress again, the information has to be factual and up-to-date because if it's not, it's not tangible and therefore cannot be evaluated.<p>

There is also evidence that the time cycle for these evaluations is shrinking.  Businesses are making decisions quickly.  This means that the demand for information will increase and the time companies allow you to provide that information will be reduced. Having current accurate information readily available will put you in a better position to compete and not be eliminated.<p>

You will never be able to answer every question asked of you on the spot.  But you need to demonstrate that you have the ability to provide good factual information with quick turnaround.<p>

No matter what kind of business your community wants to attract, information is essential.  Start working today to develop that information base.<p>

<hr>
<h3>PEACE CORPS FELLOWS, COMMUNITIES WORKING WELL TOGETHER<br>
<em>by: Tom Lawton</em></h3>

Under a unique program, seven Peace Corps Fellows from Western Illinois University (WIU) and Illinois State University (ISU) are tackling community development projects in Illinois small towns.  The fellows are Peace Corps volunteers who have returned from earlier assignments and now are serving 11 month assignments in small towns as part of the requirements to earn master's degrees for WIU or ISU.<p>

An example is Scott Johnson.  Johnson is working with the Carthage Industrial Development Corporation (CIDC) in pursuit of six goals, including bringing industry to town, developing housing and building a stronger membership base.<p>

"The Peace Corps Fellows program has been a big spark plug for our community," said Jerry Bartel of CIDC.  "Our economic and social development bases were fragmented and Scott has helped us pull them together."<p>

Another participant is Todd Crabtree.  Crabtree is working in Cumberland County through the Cumberland County Development Corporation (CCDC)/  Some of the county goals that he has been working toward include implementing an educational foundation, an ambassadors group, and a speakers bureau.  Other goals include tourism, business retention, and historic preservation. <p>

"Todd helps us make our plans happen.  He has made a lot of good connection for us and he has fit into our community really well," remarked Carol Jo Fritz form CCDC.<p>

Other 1994 Peace Corps Fellows from WIU and ISU are stationed in Cairo, Murphysboro, Grundy County and Ford County.  Lacon, Washburn and Wenona are jointly hosting a Fellow.  Both Cairo and Murphysboro are involved in the Competitive Communities Initiative.<p>

The next class of Peace Corps Fellows will be available to work in communities beginning in June 1996.  If your community is interested in hosting a Fellow, please contact John Gruidl, Illinois Institute for Rural Affairs, at Western Illinois University, phone 800/526-9943 or 309/298-2984.<p>

<hr>
<h3>FOUNDATION OF THE MONTH<br>
<em>by: Jeff Markland</em></h3>

<h4>THE FOUNDATIONS FOR GROWTH</h4>
<ul type=square>
<li>Pro-competitive policies affecting local business climate
<li>A skilled and adaptive workforce.
<li>Access to capital for business growth and expansion.
<li>Good basic and advanced infrastructure.
<li>Access to technology and business modernization resources.
<li>The social infrastructure necessary for a high quality of life.
</ul>

Years ago it was common knowledge that three factors determined the desirability of property: Location, location and location.  Cheap taxes and land were the main focuses during the site selection process.  But things changed.  Soon, communities and states found themselves in bidding wars, each trying to outdo the other with costly incentives to attract businesses.<p>

Today, to some degree, technology and transportation have changed that.  Companies are looking for more than just low taxes - the overall tax structure, tax burden and expenditure policies share equal importance.<p>

Companies look to get "bang for the buck".  Taxes should not be out of line with the benefits received.  Taxes spent effectively can actually reduce operating costs; for example, good schools reduce the need for remedial training.<p>

Stability and predictability are also of importance.  Uncertainty about taxes can undermine confidence in community leadership.<p>

You want to be sure that your taxes are in line with other communities in your market area.  But you also need to make sure that businesses know how those tax dollars are spent.  A quality business will understand that appropriate expenditures are important to preserving and improving quality of life in a community.<p>

<hr>
