<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: CCI News, Vol. #10, 1995</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs</h3>
<center><img src="../../graph/cci.gif" alt="CCI News " width=393 height=107 ></center>
<h3 align=center> Volume #10, 1995</h3>
<hr>

<h3>
O.N.E. TO WRITE ACTION PLAN<br>
<em>by: Don Falls</em>
</h3>
The Organization of the Northeast (O.N.E.), the neighborhood group that is sponsoring participation in CCI by Chicago's Edgewater and Uptown areas, has completed work on its self-assessment and is now working toward developing a written action plan for the two neighborhoods.<p>

O.N.E. faces some unique challenges.  These neighborhoods are among the most culturally, economically and ethnically diverse communities in our state.  Home to people with Chicago's highest and lowest incomes, the housing stock includes lakefront townhouses and condos, rehabilitated apartments, assisted housing, boarding houses, and many ethnic, religious and racial groups.  The neighborhoods provide a social and cultural mix only found in one of the great cities of the world.<p>

O.N.E. is particularly well-suited for CCI work because it is already very familiar with the issues involved in community competitiveness.  Formed almost 25 years ago with the purpose of identifying areas of mutual concern in the Uptown and Edgewater neighborhoods, each year O.N.E. completes a self-assessment that identifies the needs, issues and concerns of the neighborhoods. This information is then prioritized into an action agenda.<p>

This year, O.N.E. conducted 45 house meetings in the various areas.  Participants included youths, seniors, owners, renters and people of various economic levels.  Because the size and diversity of the area makes communicating very difficult, meetings were conducted in five different languages.<p>

O.N.E. also conducts an annual convention where the members review and discuss information and priorities.<p>

This year's convention identified the following priorities: leadership training and outreach; child care; safety, anti- drug and community policing; opportunities for youths; improved education at all levels; job training; housing; immigration issues, voter registration and citizenship campaigns.<p>

With this phase of the self-assessment complete, CCI staff will assist O.N.E.'s Jobs & Economic Development Team to develop the written action plan for the two neighborhoods.  The plan will detail the actions to be completed, who will be responsible for the projects and what resources will be needed to complete the various goals.<p>

<hr>
<h3>
THE DETAILS OF ORGANIZATION<br>
<em>by: Rich Funderburk</em>
</h3>

In the last issue, I talked with you about O.I.L. - Organization, Information, and Land.  I'd like to revisit two of these subjects - organization and information - in more detail.<p>

As I said before, there are many types of local organizations. They can all work if the right people are involved, if they take the time to learn the economic development process, and if they develop a clear understanding or plan of what they want to accomplish.  Then they need to set some realistic goals and a timeframe in which to achieve these goals.  I don't mean pie-in-the-sky ideas, but things that are within the ability of your organization and your community.<p>

Many community organizations have failed through the years because they were put together by people with visions of grandeur, what I call the "hero syndrome".  They're people with good intention, but who are misdirected and uninformed.<p>

Every organization needs a good leader.  Choose one who can bring all of a community's resources to focus on a common goal and, when successful give credit to all those who made it happen.  Remember, in today's world, and the economic development business in particular, no one person can make it happen.  It takes lots of people, not only from your community, but from outside the community, to make real economic growth happen.<p>

I want to stress again that the longevity of you organization's leaders is very important.  If you look around the state, or any other state as far as that goes, you'll find that in successful organizations people have been involved for as many as 10, 20 and even 30 years in their local economic development program. Don't involve people just because they are popular.  If they're popular, and they're hard worker at helping the community, that's different.<p>

I'm a strong believer that most local organization are underfunded.  A community needs to invest more than just its time if it wants to compete for growth in today's world. <p>

Funding is something that's been done in many different ways (and something we can talk about in a later column).  But no matter what path you choose for your community, be realistic in its goals, be patient, stay dedicated, there's much to learn.  Economic development is a very complex process, with many different interests.  And don't be afraid to ask for help.  No one knows for sure you're not going to re-invent the wheel in this business.  If you need help ask for it, and don't ask us too late.<p>

<hr>
<h3>NEW COMMUNITIES ANNOUNCED</h3>

Gov. Jim Edgar recently announced that 10 new participants have been chosen for the Competitive Communities Initiative (CCI).  "The goal of the CCI is to help participants lay the groundwork for economic success," the Governor said.  "The communities selected to pilot this program during the past year have given it excellent reviews.  I am pleased to see additional communities make commitment to their future."<p>

The communities chosen from this round of applications are Benton, Crystal Lake, East Moline, Grafton, Greenville, Henry, Milford, Warren County, Sparta and Yorkville.<p>

Last year, during the first selection process, CCI only selected communities assessed as being in the initial stages of development for participation in the program.  This new round of communities has demonstrated various degrees of preparedness.  "We learned a lot from working with our first round selections," said Jeff Markland of the CCI staff.  "I fully expect the program to gain strength and value as we and our communities progress."<p>

The Department of Commerce and Community Affairs Office of Local Initiatives (OLI) is responsible for administration of the CCI program.  OLI is presently working with 29 communities throughout Illinois ranging in size from a few hundred to over 150,000 people.<p>

<hr>
<h3>
CCI ON THE MOVE<br>
<em>by: Jane Robert</em>
</h3>

"CCI On the Move" is the name given to the Oregon, Illinois CCI program by its 22-member steering committee.  And there's no question it's true!<p>

With the dynamic leadership of the Steering Committee, directed by Donna Mann of the Cooperative Extension Service, subcommittee members have gone to work in the past year and are making great strides to improve their community.  Through their efforts, the "New Look for Oregon" campaign was held last June which included community clean-up work as well as adding flowers to the downtown area.  For the holidays, twinkling lights are now glowing downtown.<p>

Future plans that have already been approved include funding for period lighting on the Route 64 bridge scheduled to be constructed next  year, and development of a not-for-profit 501(C)3 Finance Committee 3 whose responsibility consists of coordination and fundraising activities for all CCI projects.  City support includes the Oregon City Council's commitment to finance one-half of the holiday lighting program and some of the administrative funds for CCI activities.  Local service organizations and individuals have financed the other half of the holiday lights.<p>

Lynn Kilker, Chairman of CCI, said, "This is only the beginning of our work in Oregon.  We are excited and CCI is working here!"<p>

<hr>
<h3>
FOUNDATION OF THE MONTH<br>
<em>by: Jeff Markland</em>
</h3>In the early years of development waterways, railroads, highways and air service determined market areas.<p>

The new "transportation system" is "ACCESS TO TECHNOLOGY AND BUSINESS MODERNIZATION RESOURCES".  It is as critical to today's competitive community as any other.  Three kinds of resources comprise this foundation.<p>

Current generation (or "off the shelf") product and process technologies including the latest equipment, applications and materials.<p>

Easy access to expertise on business modernization techniques, and third is access to applied research and development of product or process technologies as well as knowledge of innovation at both the local and global level.<p>

Improving this foundation requires close working relationships with the local business community, telephone companies, utilities, technology users and the local communities.  An up-to-date communications system is critical to your communities economic growth.<p>

<hr>
<h3>QUOTATION CORNER</h3>

"Our task now is not to fix the blame for the past, but to fix the course for the future." President John F. Kennedy<p>

<hr>
<h3>BUMPER STICKER WISDOM</h3>

Talk Is Cheap.  Until You Hire an Attorney.<br>
Submitted by Tom Gainer, Springfield<p>

