<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Illinois Economic Bulletin, November 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<h2 align=center>Department of Commmerce & Community Affairs</h2>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/ieb.gif" alt="Illinois Economic Bulletin" width=575 height=75></center>
<H3 align=center>Vol. 9 No. 5, November 1996</H3>

<hr>
<h3>BALANCED ECONOMIC EXPANSION</h3>

The Illinois Department of Employment Security (IDES) reported recently that the state is enjoying a balanced economic expansion with job growth continuing across several major industry groups led by services (36,600), trade (27,700) and manufacturing (6,900).  IDES added that for the first time in more than two years, jobs in finance, insurance and real estate have been steadily increasing, up more than 4,000 or 1.1 percent above September 1995.<p>

New business incorporations in Illinois have risen 2.7 percent through September.  During the first nine months, there were 27,057 filings with the Secretary of State compared to 26,356 incorporations a year ago.  Despite a slowdown the past two months, new domestic filings have increased  by over 700 incorporations this year.<p>

Retail sales continued to rebound from their mid-year sluggishness as receipts in August totaled $9 billion.  This was a $315 million gain over the previous August but down $123 million from the July total.  Overall, retail sales in the state have increased 3.5 percent year-to-date. 
Consumer prices in the Chicago metropolitan area rose at a moderate 2.8 percent rate in September, matching the August rate of change.  The increase was below the comparable 3 percent national level for September.  The Chicago all-urban rate trended upward in May, with the increase in energy costs, but it has remained relatively stable over the past four months.<p>

According to the October report by F. W. Dodge, contracts for future construction in Illinois are down 3.6 percent for the year.  Their nine month total of $9 billion is below last year's pace by $335 million.  This leading economic indicator reports that nonresidential construction is down 23.1 percent for the year, while nonbuilding (infrastructure improvements) contracts are off by 3 percent.  Residential construction has partially offset the other two categories with a 16.9 percent year-to-date increase.<p>
   
The University of Illinois Flash Index of Economic Growth decreased to 102.7 in October from 103.2 the previous month.  Its compilers reported that both personal income and corporate profits were sluggish in October.  They added that the two were offset somewhat by a surge in sales tax receipts. <p>

<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS  AGRICULTURAL  EXPORTS </h3>

With a strong 32.8 percent gain last year, feed grains (which includes corn) surged ahead of soybeans as the state's top agricultural export commodity during the 1995 federal fiscal year.  Large increases of agricultural crop purchases by Korea, Egypt, China, Spain and Germany boosted international shipments last year.  According to the U.S. Department of Agriculture, Illinois exported nearly $3.5 billion in farm products in FFY 1995 for a 13.8 percent yearly increase.<p>

Over $1.5 billion or 44.2 percent of the state's sales to foreign nations were feed grains (primarily corn).  An additional $1.2 billion in crop shipments or 35.7 percent were soybeans and soy-products.  In combination, Illinois' exports of feed grains and soybeans accounted for 80 percent of its agricultural sales and 17.1 percent of the U.S. shipments of these products.  Overall, Illinois exported 6.4 percent of the nation's agricultural goods in FFY 1995, down from the 7 percent reported the previous period. <p>

<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS HIGHLIGHTS</h3>

Illinois ranked second nationally in both feed grains (primarily corn) and soybean exports last year.  The state placed third overall in the international shipments of agricultural products.<p>

The U.S. Department of Commerce's first ranking of metropolitan areas by the value of their export shipments placed Chicago sixth.  Sales from the metro area totaled $17.3 billion in 1994 and primarily were manufactured products.  Non-manufactured commodities represented about 8 percent of the shipments.<p>

The National Foundation for Women Business Owners reported that Illinois ranks fifth out of the 50 states in the number of women-owned firms.  Illinois also placed fifth in employment and a similar rating for sales by women-owned firms.<p>

<hr>
<h3>DRI/MCGRAW HILL -OCTOBER ECONOMIC OUTLOOK-FORECAST OVERVIEW</h3>

The forecasting firm estimates that the U.S. economy is now operating close to capacity.  DRI feels that the strong growth in the first half of the year appears to be moderating in the second half.  They add that with the unemployment rate well below most economist's measures of full employment, above-trend growth is no longer possible for any extended period.<p>

DRI relates that the recent data suggest that, with the clear exception of housing, the economy may be cooling more quickly than expected.  Their forecast of third-quarter growth has been revised downward, primarily in net exports, where the data now suggests weaker exports and stronger imports.<p>

They predict that the economy should slow to near-trend growth in the second half of 1996 and then to below-trend growth in early 1997.  DRI expects that the Federal Reserve will keep trying to fine-tune the economy.  They estimate that the Fed will hike the funds rate by year-end and raise it to 6 percent by spring.<p>

DRI notes that business investment has been the strongest contributor to the economic expansion over the last four years.  They add that except for computers and "other" office equipment, business investment slowed late last year.  DRI expects computer outlays will slow in 1997 as early signs are beginning to appear.<p>

They also note that state and local spending will be constrained by budget problems and declining federal support.  DRI adds that rising educational outlays will limit the possibilities for further tax cuts.<p>


<HR>
