<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Illinois Economic Bulletin, July 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<h2 align=center>Department of Commmerce & Community Affairs</h2>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/ieb.gif" alt="Illinois Economic Bulletin" width=575 height=75></center>
<H3 align=center>Vol. 9 No. 1, July 1996</H3>

<hr>
<h3>NONFARM EMPLOYMENT SETS RECORD IN MAY</h3>

Nonagricultural jobs reached a new level in May, topping 5.7 million for the first time.  The preliminary monthly count was 96,600 above last year's May total with 43 percent of the growth occurring in services.  Business services alone added 14,400 jobs (6,900 in personnel supply) with health services expanding by 6,900.  Employment in retail trade grew by 19,500, of which 8,800 jobs were in eating and drinking places.  Manufacturing also added 11,100 jobs over the year, with government employment increasing by 9,300.<p>
        
Retail sales totaled $8.5 billion in April to set a new high for the month.  Data from the U.S. Department of Commerce indicates that March's receipts topped last year's total by $178 million.  The unusual weather pattern this year has produced a sawtooth type movement in retail sales in the state, but year-to-date receipts are above last year by 3.4 percent after sales averaged 3 percent in 1995.<p>

The U.S. Department of Commerce also recently released metropolitan area economic projections which predict that the Chicago area will have the nation's largest increase in jobs by the year 2005.  Issued by Commerce's Bureau of Economic Analysis, the forecast estimates that the Chicago metropolitan area will add 763,00 jobs between 1993 and 2005.  They also project that the area's population will grow by 716,000 during this period to 8,328,000 residents.<p>    

CB Commercial Real Estate Group reported that their industrial vacancy index for Chicago registered 6.3 percent in the first quarter, up from 6.1 percent the previous quarter, but down from the 8 percent of a year ago.  Their commercial office vacancy index for the Chicago metropolitan area also declined to 14.8 percent from 15.2 percent in the fourth quarter as both indexes moved to within one percent of the national averages.<p>    

According to the Illinois Association of Realtors, the median sale price of an existing single family home rose 6.8 percent in the first quarter over the cost of a year ago.  The statewide average reached $120,300 with the quarterly amount for the Chicago metro area increasing to $146,500.  The association added that there was a 1.3 percent gain in the number of units sold year-to-date.  They also noted that interest rates were edging up, but related that their national office predicts that rates would begin to stabilize, resulting in strong sales in 1996.  <p>

The U.S. Bankruptcy Courts reported that filings by Illinois businesses were up 5.1 percent in the first quarter.  Their three district courts in the state posted 434 quarterly cases compared to 413 last year and 471 two years ago.  While the business filings in Illinois rose at a moderate pace, non-business cases were more pronounced.  With a change in the bankruptcy code last year, non-business filings in the state increased to 12,219 in the first quarter from 9,411 a year ago.<p>

The University of Illinois Flash Index of Economic Growth registered 104.8 in June down from 105.1 the previous month.  Its compilers reported that the state's economy will continue to grow moderately without pushing up inflation.  They also related that both personal income and corporate profits in Illinois were strong in June, but they were offset by anemic sales of retail goods.<p>  

<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS  EXCELS  IN  MANUFACTURING</h3>

From cookies and candy to construction machinery and basic nuts and bolts, the state is the national production leader in 35 industrial categories.  In Illinois, manufacturing accounts for about 19.2 percent of its Gross State Product with an estimated value of $66 billion.  Its historical strength provides an important component to the state's diverse economy.<p>

<hr>
<h3>DRI/MCGRAW-HILL - JUNE  U.S.  ECONOMIC  OUTLOOK - FORECAST  OVERVIEW</h3>

DRI/McGraw-Hill states that the 1995 economic stall has ended.  They estimate that the economy is now in a growth  mode and has already reached full employment.  DRI forecasts that inflation is edging up, and feel that the Fed needs to respond with higher interest rates.<p> 
  
They expect housing starts in the second quarter to be strong.  DRI notes that consumer confidence is high and mortgage rates are still moderate.  They think that this year could match the 1994 peak in housing starts.<p>

The forecasting firm predicts that state and local governments will remain under serious budget constraints because of lower grants in aid and increased growth of the school age population.  They anticipate mild increases in state and local spending but note that the pressure for lower taxes will restrain spending growth.<p>

DRI predicts that foreign trade is likely to improve in 1996, in part because of the recovery in the Mexican and Japanese economies.  They note that the recessions in these two countries were major factors in restraining export growth in 1995.  DRI adds  that the European economies look less robust, but also seem likely to have a better 1996 than 1995.<p>

<HR>
<STRONG>|<A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com"> DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/econbull.htm"> Illinois Economic Bulletins</A> |</STRONG>
</BODY>
