<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Illinois Economic Bulletin, June1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<h2 align=center>Department of Commmerce & Community Affairs</h2>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/ieb.gif" alt="Illinois Economic Bulletin" width=575 height=75></center>
<H3 align=center>Vol. 8 No. 12, June 1996</H3>

<HR>
<h3>NEW BUSINESS INCORPORATIONS SET MONTHLY RECORD</h3>

Entrepreneurial optimism abounded in April with a record setting 3,770 domestic business filings.  The large monthly total topped the previous high set in December, 1992 by 280 incorporations.  April's surge added to March's substantial filings, increasing the year-to-date total to 7.6 percent above a year ago.  In the first four months, new business incorporations have risen by 910 filings over last year's growth.<p>

Following a lackluster March, the U.S. Department of Commerce reported that residential building in the state rebounded in April.  Their numbers indicate that  housing starts rose to a near record 5,418 units authorized for construction during the month.  A relatively drier April  allowed building activity to progress more rapidly with year-to-date permit issuance above last year's level by 12.2 percent.<p> 
  
The Chicago all urban consumer price index rose 2.2 percent in April from last year's level as overall costs moderated.  The major upward push in prices occurred in energy, led by natural gas and followed by motor fuel cost increases.  Offsetting the rise were subdued medical care costs and a decline in apparel and upkeep.  Without energy costs,  the index would have risen only 1.6 percent in April.<p>

The Department of Employment Security reported that after setting a new record in January, total employment in the state remained above 5.8 million for the fourth consecutive month.  IDES added that the unemployment rate at 5.1 percent in April experienced little change since the previous month and has remained below the U.S. level for 30 straight months.<p>

Employment in manufacturing was up by 12,800 in April over the previous year with growth occurring primarily in durable goods.  Approximately 9,500 jobs were added in the production of industrial machinery with the manufacture of electronic equipment expanding by 3,300 workers.  Nationally, there has been a sharp decline in manufacturing employment over the past year.<p>

An economic forecasting firm, Regional Financial Associates, related that the Chicago-metro area trails only the San Jose and Boston areas in the number of high-tech manufacturing jobs with nearly 163,000.  RFA added that the Chicago area is enjoying steadily increasing high-tech employment led by the Motorola and U.S. Robotics (modems) expansions.<p>  

The University of Illinois Flash Index of Economic Growth registered 105.1 in May from 106.1 the previous month.  Its compilers reported that evidence grows the Illinois economy is slowing to a more moderate pace after two years of rapid expansion.<p>   

<hr>
<h3>RECENT INDICATORS</h3>

Unemployment Rate                 5.1%<br>
(April-SA)<p>

Consumer Price Index              2.2%<br>
(April-Chicago All Urban)<p>

Gross State Product-Real         +1.5%<br>
(4th Quarter '95 Change-SA AR)<p>

Total Personal Income            +5.6%<br>
(4th Quarter '95 Change-SA AR)<p>

Labor Force Employed        5,824,973<br>
(April-SA)<p>

Employment Change             +61,697<br>
(Since April '95-SA)<p>

Purchasing Managers' Barometer   53.0<br>
(May-Chicago-SA)<p>

Retail Sales (3 mo. '95-'96)     +4.1%<p>

Exports (3 mo. '95-'96)          +5.7%<p>

SA-Seasonally Adjusted<br>
AR-Annual Rate<p>

<hr>
<h3>ILLINOISANS  INCREASE  PERSONAL INCOME IN 1995</h3>

Per capita personal income rose $1,156 last year reaching an average of $24,763 for each state resident in 1995.  The 4.9 percent increase moved the state to eighth place from ninth the previous year.  Illinois was the only state in the Midwest to appear in the top 10, with eastern states heading the listing.<p>  

Illinois also placed highly in total personal income with its $293 billion overall amount, ranking fifth among the states.  The 5.6 percent growth in 1995 was slightly below the 6 percent national increase, as farm income declined last year.<p>

<hr>
<h4>TOP  STATES  BY  PER  CAPITA  INCOME      </h4>
<pre>
<strong>RANK                    STATE                     DOLLARS</strong>
 1                      CONNECTICUT              $30,303
 2                      NEW JERSEY                28,858
 3                      MASSACHUSETTS             26,994
 4                      NEW YORK                  26,782
 5                      MARYLAND                  25,927
 6                      NEW HAMPSHIRE             25,151
 7                      NEVADA                    25,013
 8                      ILLINOIS                  24,763
 9                      HAWAII                    24,738
10                      ALASKA                    24,182
11                      DELAWARE                  24,124
12                      CALIFORNIA                23,699
13                      WASHINGTON                23,639
14                      VIRGINIA                  23,597
15                      MICHIGAN                  23,551
</pre>

Source: The U.S. Department of Commerce, Bureau of Economic Analysis<p>

<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS HIGHPOINTS</h3>

  At an estimated $350 billion in 1995, Illinois' gross state product ( GSP ) is fourth among the states.  Compared to other nations' gross national products ( GNP ), Illinois' GSP is larger than all but 12 worldwide. <p> 

  Illinois placed fifth with $32.6 billion in exports last year, and its 23.6 percent annual increase was the largest among the top 10 exporting states.<p>

  Researchers at the University of Illinois recently announced that they have developed a new computer chip which runs faster, and last up to 50 times longer.  The chip making process replaces regular hydrogen with deuterium, resulting in a chip which can handle more electricity, while adding only a small amount to the cost.<p>    

<hr>
<h3>WEFA - MAY U.S. ECONOMIC OUTLOOK - FORECAST OVERVIEW</h3>

  WEFA predicts that the economy's surprisingly strong performance will be sustained for an additional quarter.  They forecast that by the second half of the year, growth will slow to the 2 percent range.  WEFA anticipates that the Federal Reserve will respond by the end of the year with an additional reduction in the Fed Funds rate, because inflation will remain under control.<p>
    
  The forecasting firm notes that the pickup in oil and grain prices cannot create inflation without sufficiently tight labor markets. They add that the Bureau of Labor Statistics employment cost index indicates that wage inflation remains moderate.<p>

  WEFA reports that business investment in equipment will decelerate from its very fast pace since capacity is less imperative at this time.  They anticipate that investment in structures will grow modestly, as businesses build industrial plant and commercial structures in response to low vacancy rates.<p>    

  They predict that the impact of 1995's drop in mortgage rates on the housing market is over.  They add that for the rest of 1996, mortgage rates are likely to drift downward, sustaining housing starts at close to 1.4 million units.<p>

  WEFA relates that despite a poor trade performance in the first quarter, U.S. exports remain competitive.  They forecast that the recovery in Mexico and Japan will allow U.S. exports to maintain high expansion rates, even without strong growth in Europe.<p>

<HR>
<STRONG>|<A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com"> DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/econbull.htm"> Illinois Economic Bulletins</A> |</STRONG>
</BODY>
