<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Illinois Economic Bulletin, May 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<h2 align=center>Department of Commmerce & Community Affairs</h2>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/ieb.gif" alt="Illinois Economic Bulletin" width=575 height=75></center>
<H3 align=center>Vol. 8 No. 11, May 1996</H3>

<HR>
<h3>ILLINOIS' ECONOMIC GROWTH OUTPACES THE NATIONAL RATE</h3>

The value of the goods and services produced in the state during 1995 totaled $350 billion for a $16.4 billion gain over the previous year.  In chain-weighted constant dollars the Illinois GSP rose to $325 billion for a 2.4 percent annual increase.  Last year's advance topped the 2.0 percent national GNP rate, marking the third time out of the past four years that the state's economy has exceeded the U.S. growth level.<p>   

The U.S. Department of Commerce reported that total personal income in Illinois rose 5.6 percent in 1995.  On a per capita basis, income reached $24,763 from $23,607 the previous year moving the state to eighth in the nation from ninth in 1994.  By major category, income growth was led by a 8.7 percent increase in services along with a 6.8 percent advance in transportation, communications and public utilities.  The overall growth was partially muted by a noticeable reduction in farm income last year.<p>         

The Illinois Department of Agriculture in its April 1 release estimated that the corn crop acreage will increase 14 percent this year to 11.6 million acres.  They cite the current high prices, low supply and anticipated reduction in the Government Feed Grain Program set-aside acreage to zero.  IDA estimates that soybean planting intentions are 9.75 million acres and equal to last year's record level.  They noted that the supply of all major grain in the state is presently down from the stock of a year earlier.<p>  

Exports in February increased 5.6 percent over last year for a gain of nearly $130 million.  The $2.46 billion monthly total was the sixth largest ever despite record cold weather in early February.  The shipment of nonmanufactured commodities (grain, coal, etc.) aided the growth and accounted for $43 million of the monthly increase.  Last year, overall exports exceeded the previous year by 24.5 percent with manufactured products accounting for 90.7 percent of the state's international shipments.<p> 

According to the March report by F.W. Dodge, contracts for future construction in Illinois are up 8.7 percent for the year.  Their three month total of $2,370 million for the state is comparable to the record pace of two years ago.  Nonbuilding (infrastructure improvements) contracts led the quarterly increase with a 16.8 percent gain, followed by residential with 8.3 percent growth and nonresidential building which rose 1.4 percent.<p>          

After a sluggish start in January, retail sales rebounded in February registering $7.8 billion.  The robust monthly increase was $612 million above the previous February for a 8.6 percent gain.  This boosted the year-to-date total to 5.5 percent above the first two months of a year ago continuing the upward trend of the past two years.<p>   

The University of Illinois Flash Index of Economic Growth registered 106.1 in April from a revised 106.3 the previous month.  Its compilers reported that the personal income and retail sales sectors of the Illinois economy were relatively strong in April while corporate profits were down from their recent high rate of growth.<p>


