<hr>
<h3>AFRICAN AMERICAN-OWNED AND WOMEN-OWNED BUSINESSES IN ILLINOIS</h3>

The U.S. Department of Commerce recently released two summary reports that provided highlights of forthcoming expanded releases titled 1992 Black-Owned Businesses and 1992 Women-Owned Businesses.  The data in both reports were collected  from a large sample of all non-farm businesses filing tax forms that showed receipts of $500 or more in 1992.   Both releases indicated that the Illinois firms were close to or exceeded the national averages as to the percentage growth in the number of firms and their sales and receipts increases.<p>

The 1992 Black-Owned Businesses release indicates that African American firms in Illinois have increased 49.6 percent since 1987 compared to a 46.4 percent rate for the nation.  During this  period, all U.S. businesses grew at a 26 percent rate and increased their revenue by 67 percent.   African American firms in Illinois improved their sales and receipts by 61.2 percent, while nationally the rate was 62.9 percent for black-owned businesses.<p>

Women-owned businesses were described in the report as being substantial and growing contributors to the nation's economy as they represent one-third of all U.S. firms.  In Illinois, their number has risen by 41.5 percent compared to a 43.1 percent gain for the nation's women-owned businesses.  Sales and receipts in particular have grown rapidly with a five year gain of 139.8 percent in Illinois and a 131 percent increase nationally.<p>

<h3>AFRICAN AMERICAN-OWNED FIRMS</h3>
