<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS HIGHPOINTS</h3>

  The Chicago Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange are the world's two largest futures exchanges.  The Chicago Board Options Exchange is the world's largest stock options exchange.  Together, they handle over one-third of the world's futures and options trades.<p>

  As the U.S. government expands its on-line procurement system, which presently purchases standardized items, it is using Illinois' Great Lakes Naval Base as a national test site for the electronic purchase of repair and maintenance services. 
  The number of farms in Illinois stabilized at 77,000 last year while continuing to average 365 acres in size.  This is the second time in 50 years that a decrease in the number of farms has not occurred.<p>

<hr>
<h3>DRI/McGraw-Hill - - FEBRUARY U.S. ECONOMIC OUTLOOK - FORECAST OVERVIEW</h3>

  DRI is projecting that the 1996 U.S. Gross Domestic Product will be near 2 percent based upon the new chain-weighted methodology.  They forecast stronger GDP growth in 1997 and 1998 and add that the Federal Reserve will continue to cut the funds rate at least two more times until the economy accelerates this summer.<p>

  They also report that consumer spending slowed sharply during the Christmas season.  DRI adds that high debt levels may be inducing consumers to pull back on spending, and the bad weather is certainly encouraging them to stay home.  They expect more caution on the part of consumers but no major retrenchment.<p>

  DRI relates that inventories jumped in the fourth quarter because of weak retail sales and high car production.  They anticipate a slow and steady destocking in 1996.<p>

  They add that residential construction has not continued its autumn rebound, despite lower mortgage rates.  DRI notes that even in parts of the country not afflicted by blizzards, home sales have been disappointing.  They expect sales to remain stable, but feel that the hoped-for rebound seems less likely.<p>

   DRI reports that nonresidential construction remains strong.  They mention that office construction has stopped declining, while retail and industrial space has accelerated.  They forecast that this trend will continue through 1996. <p>

  They also mention that federal spending will drop off, even without an overall budget agreement.  DRI expects the government will muddle through fiscal 1996 with no reconciliation bill but no further shutdowns.  They add that departments will operate on continuing resolutions until their individual budgets are passed, which will imply lower discretionary spending.<p>

  DRI relates that inflation remains low.  They note that this past year will be the fifth consecutive year of below 3 percent inflation in the consumer price index.  They add that it's the first time there has been five back-to-back years below 3 percent in 30 years.<p>

  They report that employment dropped sharply in January.  DRI feels that the decline was a fluke caused by the blizzard and the federal shutdown, which may have distorted the employment survey.<p>


<HR>
