<a name="CDAP Funded Contracts"><hr></a>
<h3>CDAP FUNDED CONTRACTS - REQUESTS FOR PAYROLL INFORMATION</h3>

Periodically, CDAP grantees receive a request for the weekly payrolls of CDAP construction projects from outside parties.  The request should be made to the grantee through the Freedom of Information Act.  HUD Handbook 1344.1 (Federal Labor Standards Compliance in Housing and Community Development Programs) states:  "Requests by Outside Parties for Payrolls.  In order to protect the personal privacy interests of employees, copies of weekly payrolls containing the individual's salary, work hours, claimed exemptions and tax status, address and social security number shall not be released to outside parties and may be withheld under Exemption 6 of the Freedom of Information Act unless any identifiers are first deleted.  When payrolls are in the possession of State or local government, then the applicable State law will govern the release of payroll information."  The grantee's legal counsel must determine what information must be disclosed.<p>  

Should you require any additional information in this regard, please contact your CDAP Grants Manager.<p>

<a name="Implementing Section 3 Report Req"><hr></a>
<h3>IMPLEMENTING SECTION 3 REPORTING REQUIREMENTS</h3>

This is the first of several forms of communication to CDAP grantees to notify you of the Section 3 revisions and DCCA's plan for implementation at the beginning of the 1996 program year (April 1, 1996).  This article will give you a brief overview of the revised regulations.  More detailed instructions and reporting forms will be distributed to affected grantees later this year.<p>

Section 3 of the Housing and Urban Development Act of 1968 was created to stimulate jobs and business opportunities in areas receiving HUD assistance.  For several years, the CDAP grant agreements have contained the "Section 3 Clause," placing a number of requirements on grantees and contractors to ensure their compliance with Section 3 regulations.  On June 30, 1994, Section 3 was overhauled, which substantially strengthened it and established clear priorities for targeting opportunities among Section 3 residents and businesses.<p>

Section 3 contains thresholds wherein Section 3 regulations apply.  Grantees receiving a grant in excess of $200,000 are covered by Section 3.  Contractors who receive a contract in excess of $100,000 from grantees who receive a grant in excess of $200,000 are also covered by Section 3.  If the grantee threshold is met but the contractor threshold is not, then the Section 3 regulations apply only to the grantee.<p>

Each grantee will be responsible for:<p>
<ul>
<li>     Notifying Section 3 residents and business concerns about training, employment and contracting opportunities generated by Section 3 covered assistance.
<li>     Notifying potential contractors for covered projects of Section 3 requirements.
<li>     Incorporating the Section 3 clause in all solicitations and contracts.
<li>     Facilitating the training and employment of Section 3 residents.
<li>     Facilitating the award of contracts to Section 3 business concerns.
<li>     Obtaining the compliance of contractors and subcontractors with Section 3 requirements.
<li>     Refraining from entering into any contract with any contractor where the recipient has notice or knowledge that the contractor has been found in violation of the Section 3 regulations.
<li>     Documenting actions taken to comply with Section 3, the results of actions taken and impediments, if any.
<li>     Submitting required reports.
</ul>

One of the key points to keep in mind is the dollar threshold.  Many of the projects funded with CDAP dollars cost considerably more and funding is received from several sources.  For example, if a community is installing water lines to an unserved area and receives funding from CDAP in excess of $200,000, the entire project is covered.  The community may be receiving $200,000 from CDAP, $200,000 from RECDS and $10,000 in local funds, for a total project cost of $410,000.  Any contract let in excess of $100,000 regardless of the funding source is considered covered under Section 3.<p>

A Section 3 resident is described as a public housing resident or an individual who resides in the metropolitan area or nonmetropolitan county in which the Section 3 covered assistance is expended and who is a low-income or very low-income person.  A Section 3 business is described as a business in which 51 percent or more is owned by Section 3 residents, has permanent full-time employees at least 30 percent of whom are currently Section 3 residents or within three years of the date of first employment with the business concern were Section 3 residents, or has a commitment to subcontract in excess of 25 percent of the dollar award of all subcontracts to be awarded to such businesses described above.<p>

DCCA will require grantees to report their Section 3 covered activities.  Grantees with individual grants in excess of $200,000 will be required to report on their efforts undertaken to comply with Section 3.  Each grant is considered a "project."  Therefore, if a grantee has a $300,000 CDAP Public Facilities grant and a $400,000 CDAP Housing Rehabilitation grant, the grantee will be required to submit two reports--one for each grant.<p>

DCCA will implement the Section 3 reporting requirements with the 1996 program year.  Keep in mind, though, that CDAP grants awarded in prior program years contained the Section 3 clause.  Therefore, if the grant threshold is met, then the prior year grants are also covered.  It will not be necessary to retroactively manufacture data.  Grantees will be required to report activities for all grants meeting the Section 3 threshold for activities which occur during the reporting period.<p>

Section 3 is meant to provide economic opportunities for low and very low income persons in the areas where the HUD assistance is being expended.  We believe this to be a worthwhile program and we don't anticipate any major problems in implementing the regulations in the Illinois Community Development Assistance Program.  We also recognize that the guidelines can be confusing at times and with future communication we will attempt to make compliance as painless as possible.<p>

<a name="Questions & Answers"><hr></a>
<h3>QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS</h3>

Often you may feel there are no answers available to questions that develop in administering your grant.  The answer may not be found in the Grants Management Handbook because the question or problem is a "unique" situation that requires more definition or clarification.  This section of The Grant Manager will be devoted to questions from you, the grantees, and answers from the CDAP staff.  We will also include common concerns encountered by Grants Managers during their site visits.  In each newsletter we will answer your questions and share your comments with other grantees who may have experienced similar problems.<p>

<h4>Planning/Design:</h4>
<ul>
Q.  After the environmental review has been met, can the grantee enter into an agreement and spend only leverage funds pending the Release of Funds letter from DCCA?<p>
A.  No.  You cannot enter into an agreement AFTER the environmental review has been met and BEFORE the date of the Release of Funds letter to the grantee.  The contract would commit CDAP dollars as well as leverage funds.  You would be committing funds not yet released.<p>
</ul>

<h4>Public Facilities:</h4>
<ul>
Q.  Can administration costs be incurred while waiting for a grant modification to include administration as a project activity?<p>

A.  No.  You cannot incur administration costs while waiting for a grant modification.  The grant modification must be approved before costs are incurred.<p>

Q.  Is income verification required for all household residents receiving hook-ups if the line item indicates 60% leverage and 40% CDAP funds?<p>

A.  No.  Income verification would be required for the 40% of households utilizing CDAP funds for the household hook-ups.<p>
</ul>

<h4>Housing/Application Process:</h4>
<ul>
Q. Does the housing fact sheet of the application pertain only to those homes that express an interest in the project if funded?<p>

A.  No.  The housing fact sheet requests information on all homes within the targeted project area.<p>

Q.  Does a survey of the entire targeted project area need to be conducted?<p>

A.  Yes.  To demonstrate project need and project benefit, the application should provide information on all homes within the targeted area.  Sample survey forms shall be submitted with the application equal to the number of homes to be rehabilitated.<p>
</ul>

<h4>Housing/Administration Process:</h4>
<ul>
Q.  Does the required 25% leverage need to be incorporated into each individual home to be rehabilitated?<p>

A.  No.  The rehabilitation line item of the grant budget shall be leveraged by 25%.  It is recommended that, if possible, each home rehabilitated have leverage funds expended as part of the project cost.<p>

Q.  Can funds be transferred from one line item to another within the grant budget?<p>

A.  Yes, with the exception of increasing the administrative or inspection line items of the budget which have a limit of 7% and 8% respectively.  Always review the Scope of Work and Budget sections of your grant agreement for accuracy before executing the agreement.<p>
</ul>

<a name="Farm Income Definition Revision"><hr></a>
<h3>FARM INCOME DEFINITION REVISION</h3>

After much consideration, the DCCA staff have determined that there is a need to redefine the method of computing farm income for CDAP program eligibility.  Page 3-5-9 of the CDAP Grants Management Handbook contains the definition of annual income which has been changed to read as follows:  "Annual Income is the gross amount of income anticipated to be received by the family during the twelve months following the effective date of examination, excluding farm income."  Previous year tax returns are acceptable as a basis for computing current income for farm households only as defined in paragraph 3 of the "Income Inclusions" section on page 3-5-9, which reads:  "3)  Farm income defined as net money income (gross receipts minus operating expenses) received from the operation of a farm by a person on their own account, as an owner, renter or sharecropper.  Operating expenses include depreciation, interest on debt as well as other normal operating expenses."<p>

<a name="Activities in a Floodplain"><hr></a>
<h3>ACTIVITIES IN A FLOODPLAIN</h3>

The Great Flood of 1993 resulted in numerous projects in floodplain areas.  If a project involves activities in a floodplain, grantees must conduct a federally mandated eight-step review procedure.<p>

Executive Order 11988--Floodplain Management Guidelines--is applicable to all grantees whose projects occur in the 100 year floodplain.  The order requires grantees to conduct an eight-step review procedure.  This is a decision-making process to consider any practicable alternatives to locating the project in the base floodplain.  Instructions for the eight-step floodplain review procedures can be found in Chapter 2, Section I, pages 2-1-18 and 19 of your CDAP Grants Management Handbook.  The eight-step process is part of the environmental review.<p>

Steps 2 and 7 of the review procedure involve notices to the public and allowing time for meaningful input.  These publications are the "Early Public Review for Construction in a Floodplain" and "Findings and Public Explanation for Construction in a Floodplain."  To satisfy special grant conditions, the grantee will publish the "early public review" notice early in the process.  A total of 15 full days, excluding day of publication, will be allowed for public comment for the early notice.  The "findings and public explanation" publication will be published once the public comment period has elapsed on the early publication.  The public comment period for this, the second publication, will be a full seven days excluding the day of publication.<p>

When the eight-step floodplain review procedure has been completed and the National Environmental Policy Act of 1969 (NEPA) requirements have been satisfied the grantee can publish the Notice to the Public of No Significant Impact on the Environment and Notice to the Public for Request for Release of Funds (combined notice) or the Notice of Intent to Request a Release of Funds, whichever is appropriate.  The eight steps and publications may be forwarded to DCCA once the public comment period has elapsed for the second public notice.<p>

If you have any questions regarding this information, contact Mike Craig for all flood assistance grants, or Amy Zachary for all other CDAP grants proposing an action in a floodplain.<p>

<a name="Projects Funded with 1996 Program Funds"><hr></a>
<h3>PROJECTS FUNDED WITH 1996 PROGRAM YEAR FUNDS WILL REQUIRE HOOK-UPS</h3>

After April 1, 1996, all CDAP-funded public facilities projects funded for new or expanding water or sewer systems will require hook-ups for all qualified owner occupied low-to-moderate income households (hook-ups for rental units are not mandated, but may be done.)<p>

You should also be aware that according to HUD regulations, local governments may not impose a "special assessment" (assessing a fee or charge levied or filed as a lien against a parcel of real estate as a direct result of benefit derived from the installation of a public improvement) against properties which are owned and occupied by persons defined by the most current HUD Section 8 income guidelines for the appropriate county as being low-to-moderate income persons. The term "special assessment" does not relate to periodic water or sewer user fee charges imposed for the use of public improvements.<p>

The most common type of special assessment is a "tap-on" fee which is a one-time charge made as a condition of access to an improvement, normally a sanitary sewage collection or water distribution system.  If an entity determines that a tap-on fee will be charged, the income generated by the collection of such fees will flow into that entity, i.e. water district, community, etc.; and generally be available for project construction costs and may be used as local leverage.  Please keep in mind that tap-on fees are generally required to be paid by all households.  CDAP funds may be used to pay for the tap-on fees for owner-occupied low-to-moderate income households, or the unit of local government may elect to waive those fees.<p>

In some instances, low-to-moderate income households are required to pay a tap-on fee (reimbursable deposit)  prior to CDAP award to satisfy requirements imposed by the Rural Economic and Community Development Service.  In this case, the low-to-moderate income household or the grantee can be reimbursed with CDAP funds provided the proper documentation and income verification is made prior to disbursement of the funds (and the funds were used to assist in financing construction). <p>

In addition to budgeting for the tap-on fee, you must budget CDAP or leverage funds to pay for the hook-ups for all owner occupied low-to-moderate income households.  To prevent confusion, it's very important for the applicant to understand the terms commonly used in conjunction with a CDAP funded project.  A "service lead/connection" is a line extending the main system to the utility's right-of-way line, normally owned and maintained by the utility.  A "hook-up" is a privately owned and maintained line on privately owned property between a service lead/connection and a structure.<p>

The grantee must use CDAP funds or leverage funds to pay for the actual cost of running the private water or sewer lines up to the house for each owner occupied low-to-moderate income household.  If the cost exceeds $500 for water and $750 for sewer, the homeowner must provide the difference.  The final connection to the house is also the responsibility of the homeowner.<p>

Hook-ups are considered a direct benefit activity and, therefore, the grantee must document the income eligibility of each household receiving this assistance.  Please refer to the Direct Benefit Section of the "CDAP Grants Management Handbook"  for additional guidance on verification of income for low-to-moderate income households.<p>


