<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: WorkForce Newsletter, November 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<HR>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/dcca/graph/wforce.gif" WIDTH=272 HEIGHT=109>
<H2>November, 1996</H2>
</CENTER>

<HR><h3>
</h3>PIC/CEO CONFERENCE 

Chris Stevens, Director, The Private Industry Council of Lake County, welcomed private industry council (PIC) members and chief elected officials (CEOs) to the annual PIC/CEO Conference, The Future Is Now which was held July 19-20, 1996, at the Ambassador West Hotel. The conference was sponsored by the Illinois Employment and Training Partnership (IETP) and the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA).  IETP members are directors of local organizations which deliver quality workforce development services through the Job Training Partnership Act program.<p>

Illinois State Senator Steve Rauschenberger, District #33,  provided the opening remarks and discussed the impact and effect of the state's appropriation process and federal block grants on future employment and training programs.  Rochelle Daniels, Attorney at Law with the Broward Employment and Training Administration in Florida, was the guest speaker for the conference.  Ms. Daniels provided insight on the impact of "no new federal legislation" and the Workforce Preparation Action Plan developed by a task force of representatives of the Illinois Board of Higher Education, Illinois Community College Board, Illinois State Board of Education and Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs.  Roundtable discussions on the second day resulted in the identification of local workforce development strategies to be implemented by  PICs and CEOs.<p>

<hr>
<h3>THE ENTERPRISE</h3>

Illinois now has more members of the national Enterprise than any other state. Six agencies receiving membership status this year are The Private Industry Council of Lake County; Private Industry Council of Northern Cook County; Illinois Valley Community College; KDK, Training, Employment & Business Services; City of Peoria; and Management, Training, and Consulting Corporation.<p>    

The Enterprise is a network of workforce development organizations which emphasizes high quality, customer-focused services, using successful process management techniques adapted from the private sector.  Its purpose is to promote and enhance the quality of all workforce development services for dislocated workers and to gain recognition for the quality that exists through the Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA) Program.  The federal JTPA program provides job seekers needed skills through education and training programs as well as assistance in obtaining employment.<p>

By meeting Enterprise standards, 15 Illinois organizations have been certified as delivering a range of services in a manner expected by the organizations' customers; achieving the outcomes expected by their customers and the system's investors; and having implemented the process management principles adopted by successful private sector organizations. In 1996, fewer than 20 percent of the organizations nationwide which are eligible to apply for Enterprise status have achieved membership, as compared to 57.7 percent of Illinois organizations attaining membership status.<p>

<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS EMPLOYMENT AND TRAINING CENTER UPDATE </h3>

Progress on the establishment of Illinois Employment and Training Centers continues!<p>

A total of 44 Illinois Employment and Training Centers (IETCs) have opened across 	the state as of October 1996.
In addition to the agencies that deliver the Job Training Partnership Act program and 	the Illinois Department of Employment Security, at least 143 other organizations are 	located on-site in IETCs throughout the state; they include community colleges, the 	Departments of Public Aid and Rehabilitation Services, Green Thumb, Area Agencies 	on Aging and a wide variety of local governmental, educational, and community-based 	organizations.<p>

IETC home pages were featured at the Illinois State Fair in Springfield and DuQuoin; 
access the home page for your local IETC at  <a href="http://www.ilcommerce.com/ietc">http://www.ilcommerce.com/ietc</a>.<p>

General information cards describing services available to employers and job seekers through IETCs have been developed; copies may be attained by contactingLibby Pillsbury at 217/524-8330; local versions will soon be available.<p>

The University of Illinois at Springfield has identified approximately 100 products 	which will be made available to IETC for use in resource rooms; this activity is part of 	the federal one-stop implementation grant.<p>

<hr>
<h3>MOBILE EMPLOYMENT & TRAINING PROJECT </h3>

The Department of Commerce and Community Affairs awarded grant funds to New Start, Inc. for the purpose of providing a mobile capacity to deliver employment and training services to residents of rural Illinois.  The  demonstration project uses a mobile unit to assist the Illinois Employment and Training Centers in delivering innovative and comprehensive services to the unemployed and the dislocated worker.<p> 

The Employment and Training Services Delivery Model is a satellite-based one-stop mobile that works with employment and training service agencies throughout the state to aid them in assisting individuals develop the skills necessary to find and keep a good job.  The highly flexible vehicle of staff and equipment has the capability of providing advanced re-employment services in rural areas.  Some of the services provided through the computer lab include vocational assessment, UI profiling,  and job search assistance.  <p>

The mobile is successful due to the collaboration and interfacing of several highly technical systems.  Because a two-way satellite service is used, the Employment and Training Services Delivery Model does not require a phone line or advance on-line service to access the Internet.  It also can generate its own electrical hook-up which is very helpful in rural areas.<p>

For additional information contact Jim Torricelli, Director of New Start, Inc., 522 East Monroe Street, Springfield, IL 62701; 217/522-3799.<p>

<hr> 
<h3>MISSED BUT FONDLY REMEMBERED</h3> 

Samuel C. Bernstein, 86, passed away May 7, 1996, at his Pompano Beach, Florida home.  During his lifetime, he was an advisor to three United States presidents, eight Illinois governors and two Chicago mayors.  He was considered the "Father of the Illinois Unemployment Compensation Act" for his role in drafting the 1937 bill that passed and revolutionized support for workers.  Also in 1937 he was appointed by Governor Henry Horner as General Counsel of the Illinois Bureau of Employment Security.  In 1942 he was appointed Commissioner of that office by Governor Dwight Green.<p>

Being active in the Interstate Conference of Employment Security Agencies and Illinois' head Employment Security official, Sam often was asked to advise the nation's Presidents from Roosevelt to Johnson.  He was an advisor to President Truman on the future role of employment service following World War II.<p>

In 1961 Mr. Bernstein was appointed Director of Labor for the State of Illinois, a position he held until 1963 when he became the Illinois Employment Security Administrator.  In 1970 Sam was selected by Chicago Mayor Richard J. Daley to serve as Assistant to the Mayor for Manpower, which he continued to hold under Mayor Michael A. Bilandic until 1980.  <p>

Sam was known throughout his career to be an innovator in programs that train disadvantaged workers the skills needed to gain access to the job market.  The agencies that he directed had strict nondiscrimination policies in hiring, and, as an expert in his field, he continued to impact employment policy even after leaving public office. In 1978 he became an Adjunct Professor at the University of Illinois-Chicago.  He worked as a consultant for Kane, McKenna and Associates and Target Group, Incorporated until the time of his death.<p>

Sam is survived by his wife of 62 years, Dena (Nee) Feldman; his daughters, Bonnie Boyd and Carol Acosta; son, Victor Bernstein; six grandchildren and four great grandchildren.  He will be missed by his many friends in the workforce development field.Earl A. Pate, President and Chief Operating Officer of Management, Training and Consulting Corporation (Man-Tra-Con Corp.), passed away at his home in rural Williamson County on Friday, July 19, 1996.  He was 59 years old.<p>  

Earl's professional life began as an employee of Caterpillar Tractor Company in Aurora, Illinois.  He was the youngest individual at the company at that time to be elected president of the United Auto Workers Union, Local 145.<p>

The late Governor Otto Kerner requested that Earl join a handful of individuals to fight the war on poverty.  The honor eventually lead him to design and implement Operation Main Stream, an older workers program, and the Neighborhood Youth Corp programs.  He was named Southern State Director for the Comprehensive Employment and Training Act programs in Illinois during the 1970's and early 1980's.  With the enactment of the Job Training Partnership Act in 1982, Earl was responsible for overseeing the JTPA program for much of southern Illinois.<p>

In honor of Earl's memory, Man-Tra-Con Corporation's Board of Directors has created a scholarship fund for students pursuing a post secondary education and who are residents of Jefferson, Franklin, Williamson, Perry or Jackson counties.  The Department of Commerce and Community Affairs expresses its sympathy to Earl's wife, Virginia; daughter, Lisa (Pate) Bartlow; son, Earl A. Pate II; and other members of his family. <p>

<hr>
<h3>JTPA TRAINING CALENDARS</h3>  

The July-December 1996 Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA) Training Calendar announces and provides information about 16 sessions being offered during the first six months of the program year.  These sessions are designed to enhance the effectiveness and quality of services delivered through JTPA programs and other federal, state, and local employment and training programs.<p> 

This calendar presents many workshops of interest to a broader audience than individuals involved in workforce development activities.  Therefore, recognizing the benefits of interaction with the private sector, training sessions will now be marketed to private sector companies based upon availability<p>.

If you would like more information on training calendar offerings, contact Libby Pillsbury at the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, 620 East Adams Street, Springfield, IL 62701 or call 217/524-8330; TDD, 800/785-6055.<p>

<hr>
<h3>CALENDAR AND RESOURCES</h3>  

If you are interested in attending training or obtaining copies of identified resources, please direct inquiries to Libby Pillsbury at the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, 620 East Adams Street, Springfield, Illinois  62701; 217/524-8330; TDD, 800/785-6055.<p>   

November 13 and 14, 1996<br>
THE INTERNET<br>
Join the rest of us who have entered the technology age; this training will provide you with a general understanding of how to access the Internet and an appreciation for the kind of information available through the Internet.<p>

November 19, 1996<br>
MOTIVATING CLIENTS TO SUCCEED<br>
Don't miss this one!  This session will provide you with the skills you need to change clients' habits, attitudes, beliefs, and expectations about what they can achieve so they can become self-sufficient and self-reliant.<p>

November 21, 1996<br>
MAKING THE LINK! EXPANDING THE PARTNERSHIP! <br>
Come to this session and discover how to make the logical linkages between the Illinois Employment and Training Centers, Welfare-to-Work and Education-to-Careers systems. <p>


SUMMERWORKS has been prepared by the U. S. Department of Labor Employment and Training Administration in collaboration with the Employment Development Department of the State of California, Region IX.  It is a compendium of the 1995 Private Sector Summer Youth Jobs Initiative and School-to-Work Summer Programs, and is based on a series of interviews with private sector employers and employment and training practitioners active in youth initiatives in Arizona, California, Hawaii, and Nevada.<p>

FINAL REPORT OF THE MASS LAYOFF STATISTICS (MLS) PROGRAM is a report on the MLS Program which was administered by the Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) for the purpose of developing and maintaining statistical data related to permanent layoffs and plant closings.  An interagency agreement between the U. S. Department of Labor Employment and Training Administration and BLS provided for the establishment of a workgroup to determine l) the usefulness of the MLS Program; 2) whether any changes to the program would enhance its usefulness and, if so, to identify what those changes should be and their associated implementation cost.  The final report provides a summary of the workgroup's analysis and resulting recommendations.<p>

LITERACY LEADER FELLOWSHIP PROGRAM REPORTS is Part I in a Series, Framework for Developing Skill Standards for Workplace Literacy, by Eunice N. Askov, Ph.D., and was the research project at the National Institute for Literacy from October 1994 through September 1995.  Based on the changing business environment, the project focused on describing and defining cross-occupation workplace skills necessary for worker and business success, regardless of occupation and job tenure level, in order to work in the high performance work organizations.<p>

All programs may be accessed through the State TDD Relay, 800/526-0844.<p> 


