<head><title>DCCA: Small Business Environmental Assistance Program</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000080" link="#000080" vlink="#8080C0" alink="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+2>Governor's Small Business Environmental Task Force Report</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<p>


Illinois Department of <BR>
Commerce & Community Affairs<BR>
620 East Adams Street<BR>
Springfield, Illinois 62701<P>
<P>
Illinois Environmental <BR>                     
Protection Agency  <BR>                         
2200 Churchill Road  <BR>                       
Springfield, Illinois 62794-9276<P>            

April 1994<P>

Dear Small Businessperson:<P>

As Governor of Illinois, I am convinced that is is important for the State 
to address small business' concerns and problems in an effective manner.  
The economic and environmental well-being of small business is essential to 
the well-being of Illinois.  We must protect the environment and at the
same time facilitate a business climate where small businesses flourish and 
prosper.<P>

I am presenting in this report the recommendations of the Governor's Small 
Business Environmental Task Force.  This document represents a
collaborative effort of numerous small business representatives, local 
chambers of commerce, trade associations, attorneys, the Illinois 
Environmental Protection Agency, and the Illinois Department of Commerce 
and Community Affairs to address the concerns that small businesses have in 
complying with environmental laws and regulations.
<P>
Already, implementation is beginning on key recommendations contained in 
this report.  The Illinois Environmental Protection Agency, in cooperation 
with the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs and key business 
associations, is actively developing informational materials that will 
clearly guide specific business through the maze of environmental laws and 
regulations.  Informational videos that will demonstrate cleanup and other
environmental activities are in the production stage.  And legislation is 
under consideration that would provide tax incentives for small businesses 
that take action to address their environmental problems.
<P>
I would like to thank you, the members of the business community.  We
asked you to be candid with us and to make recommendations to us on how to
help you meet your environmental responsibilities.  You responded 
enthusiastically, giving hours of your time and expertise.<P>
<P>
I am delighted that this task force is taking the next step, working with 
my administration to implement the recommendations that have been set 
forth.  I look forward to the continuation of this cooperative effort as 
through this new found partnership we ensure a healthy environment and a 
Healey economy.
<P>
                                        Sincerely,
<P>
                                        Jim Edgar<BR>
                                        Governor<P>

 <HR>
<P>
                            <CENTER><H3> TABLE OF CONTENTS</H3></CENTER><BR>

<UL type=square>
<LI><a href="#Intro">Introduction</a><br>
<li><a href="#Goals">Goals</a><br>
<li><a href="#Organization">Organization of Task Force</a><br>
<li><a href="#General Findings">General Findings</a><br>
<li><a href="#Educations">Education Recommendations</a><br>
<li><a href="#Compliance">Compliance Recommendations</a><br>
<li><a href="#Permit Recommendations">Permit Recommendations</a><br>
<li><a href="#Technology Recommendations">Technology Recommendations</a><br>
<li><a href="#Financial Recommendations">Financial Recommendations</a><br>
<li><a href="#Master List">Task Force Members</a><br>
</ul>
<P>

<a name="Intro"><hr></a>
<H3>Introduction</H3>
<P>
     In July of 1993 the Governor's Small Business Environmental Task Force 
was launched.  This collaborative effort between the Illinois Environmental 
Protection Agency (Agency) and the Illinois Department of Commerce and 
Community Affairs (DCCA) was established to reach out to one of the most 
critical and one of the most vulnerable links in the economic chain: small 
business.  <P>
     Complementing the efforts of the Task Force were two extensive Agency 
outreach initiatives.  These initiatives were aimed at getting input from 
the broader small business community in Illinois.  To reach this business 
sector, the Agency worked with local chambers of commerce across the state 
and held nearly two dozen meetings.  The meetings gave Agency staff the 

opportunity to hear first hand from many small businesses.  Additionally, 
the Agency is cooperation with DCCA, conducted a survey of nearly 5,000
small businesses in Illinois.  <P>
     Through that survey, small business owners across the state told the 
Agency about the problems they have in understanding and complying with 
Illinois' environmental requirements.  Those expanded outreach efforts 
served to further crystallize the understanding that small business is the 
backbone of the State's economy.  More than 300,000 small businesses in 
Illinois provide jobs to Illinoisans and supply goods and services to 
citizens in this state, across the country, and around the globe.  But 
while these small businesses are a critical link in economic chain, they 
also are critical link in the environmental chain.  Like larger businesses, 
they have an impact on the environment and face many complex environmental 
laws and regulations in operating their businesses.  Understanding those 
laws and regulations is often a daunting challenge, to which many small 
business owners do not have the staff or money to dedicate.<P>
     Just as the economic well-being of the state is dependent on small 
business, the environmental well-being of the state also depends on small 
business.  The issues examined by the Task Force and the recommendations 
they have produced recognize the "real world" concerns of small business 
and propose broad steps to address those concerns.  Implementation of the 
recommendations will open the doors of communication between small business 
and state agencies.  Implementation also will enable strong measures to be 
taken to assist small businesses in their compliance efforts.  The 
recommendations recognize that, to accomplish their joint goals, small 
businesses and state government must work together in partnership wherever 
possible.
<P>

<a name="Goals"><hr></a>
<H3>Goals of the Task Force</H3>
     To respond to small businesses concerns, a number of goals were 
established for the Task Force.  These goals reflect the commitment that 
Governor Jim Edgar, IEPA, and DCCA have made to address the problems of
small businesses, and to ensure both the economic and environmental 
well-being of our state:

<ul type=square>
     <li>Identify and articulate the issues, concerns, and problems that small 
businesses encounter with environmental laws and regulations, so that they 
can be addressed effectively.
<P>
<li>     Develop creative ways of using both the public and private sectors to 
assist small businesses to better address their environmental concerns and 
problems.<p>
<li>     Improve communication and understanding between small businesses and 
state government agencies.<p>
<li>     Develop a variety of plans and methods to enable small business to 
better understand environmental issues and requirements.<p>
<li>     Streamline and coordinate the environmental requirements, so that the 
environment can be well protected in the least burdensome manner to small 
businesses.<p>
</ul>

<a name="Organization"><hr></a>
<H3>Organization of the Task Force</H3>

     The Task Force began its work in July of 1993, with an ambitious 
schedule for studying the issues, reaching out to small businesses, 
developing recommendations, and delivering a report to the directors of the 
IEPA and DCCA by December of 1993.<p>
     At its initial meeting, the Task Force created four workgroups.  The 
workgroups were composed of small businesspeople, associations, and 
attorneys.  They were developed to address specific areas of concern:  
compliance, education, permits and technology.  Subsequently, in response 
to a suggestion made at a local small business meeting, a fifth workgroup, 
the financial workgroup, was formed to address financial concerns faced by 
small businesses in meeting environmental compliance costs.  Each of the 
workgroups had a defined scope of work and was composed principally of 
member so the Task Force.<p>
     These workgroups embarked on an intensive two-month effort to develop 
recommendations for consideration by the full Task Force.  Recommendations 
of the initial workgroups to the Task Force were largely completed by the 
end of September, 1993 and submitted to the Task Force for review.  The 
Task Force then considered the recommendations at a series of meetings, 
reaching a consensus on a set of Task Force recommendations and determining 
the future role of the Task Force in November, 1993.  Thereafter, the Task 
Force developed this final report.<p>
<dl>
     <dt><STRONG>Education Workgroup: </STRONG> <dd>The Education Workgroup focused on educational 
and information efforts that could assist small businesses, looking at what 
documents or methods could be developed to help small businesses better 
understand what is needed to plan and to operate their businesses in 
compliance with the environmental laws and regulations in Illinois.<P>

    <dt> <STRONG>Compliance Workgroup: </STRONG><dd> The Compliance Workgroup focused on the 
concerns that small businesses have in understanding and meeting the
environmental compliance requirements in the state, including problems in 
the compliance process itself.<P>
     <dt><STRONG>Permit Workgroup:  </STRONG><dd>The Permit Workgroup identified and examined the 
various permitting requirements that apply to small businesses and examined 
such issues as how a small business can determine what permits are needed, 
how the application process works, small business/agency interactions 
during the application process, and the problems small businesses have in 
understanding permit requirements.  This included an examination of how the 
permitting process, including the application process, could be streamlined 
to help small businesses.<P>
    <dt><STRONG> Technology Workgroup:  </STRONG><dd>The Technology Workgroup focused on identifying
computer and other "high tech' alternatives that could help small 
businesses in understanding environmental requirements, filing permit
applications, submitting reports, doing recordkeeping, and other 
environmental activities.  The Workgroup also considered the use of videos 
and other technologies to assist small businesses.
<P>
    <dt> <STRONG>Financial Workgroup:  </STRONG><dd>The Financial Workgroup focused on informational 
needs that small businesses have in determining how to obtain financing to
meet the costs of environmental compliance and on whether there is a need
for any additional programs to aid small businesses in meeting those costs.<p></dl>
     Each of the workgrups discussed and developed recommendations.  There 
was a great deal of participation and interest by Task Force members in 
each of these workgroups, as can be seen in the recommendations contained 
in this report.
<P>

<a name="General Findings"><hr></a>
<H3>General Findings of the Task Force</H3>
<P>
     In additional to the specific recommendations that are included in 
this report, the Task Force identified a few general points that must be 
addressed in dealing with small business problems.  These can be grouped 
into a few categories.<P>
     First, the Task Force identified a widespread and pervasive "fear 
factor" among small businesses.  The Task Force heard a common refrain 
again and again:  Many small businesses fear the environmental regulations 
themselves, the implementation of those regulations, or both.<P>
     A number of bases for this fear exist.  The paramount fear is that the 
cost of complying with the regulations will put the company out of 
business.  However, other fears are important as well, including a few by 
small businesses that they cannot determine whether they need a permit or 
multiple permits from the Agency.  They cannot understand the multitude of 
regulations that may apply to them.  There also is a fear that the Agency 
will be rigid and insistent on literal compliance in all instances.  
Related concerns include the costs associated with having to hire an 
environmental consultant or an attorney.<P>
     As a result of the "fear factor", many small businesses try to avoid 
the environmental regulatory system and interaction with the Agency and may 
even avoid making an attempt to identify what regulations might apply or 
whether they need a permit.  Members of the Task Force find this is a 
serious problem that must be addressed.  As a result, many of the 
recommendations focus on those concerns.<P>
     The second key area is understanding what must be done in order to 
comply with the applicable regulations.  This concern is nearly as 
pervasive as the first and many recommendations addressing this issue have 
been developed by each of the workgroups.<P>
     The Task Force also emphasized the need for widespread publicity in 
order to help overcome the "fear factor" and to make small businesses in 
Illinois aware of the many Task Force recommendations that will be useful 
to them.  The Task Force believes it is especially important that small 
businesses are aware of the Agency's willingness to address their concerns.  
This will contribute a necessary step to the communication and openness 
that will be required to make the small business initiative effective.
<P>

<a name="Educations"><hr></a>
<H3>Education Recommendations</H3>
<P>
     The Task Force believes that much of the noncompliance that may be 
found in small businesses today does not result from a desire by those 
businesses to circumvent their obligations, but rather from a lack of 
understanding or information on the part of businesses as to the 
regulations that apply to them.  In essence, this education process may be 
similar to that which occurred with the advent of environmental regulation 
some years ago when larger entities were subject to regulation for the 
first time.  It is believed that an education process is a two-way street 

requiring efforts by both the regulated community and the regulators.
<P>
     The clear consensus of the Task Force is that is is important that the 
Agency, in partnership with private parties and associations, aggressively 
work to provide educational resources to small business owners.  Once these
resources are developed, a catalog of available materials should be
provided to interested parties.  These resources would allow small 
businesses to be educated about what is available for purposes of ensuring
their business is in compliance with applicable Illinois environmental
regulations.<P>
     The Task Force has divided its recommendations into four categories:  
publications, avenues of communication, education, and general principles.  
In this section, a priority level is given to each category.<P>
     The Task Force also determined that a fundamental problem in the
current system with respect to regulation of small businesses is a lock of 
satisfactory means for disseminating information to small businesses.  To 
address the problem, the Task Force agreed that representatives of 
associations and chamber of commerce would, in many cases, provide the best
method for reaching out to small businesses.  Therefore, it was decided by 
the Task Force that the agency should actively seek out partnerships with
these associations to better enable it to reach various business entities.<P>
     The Task Force believes that the educational efforts recommended can 
contribute significantly to overcoming this "fear factor" that is
widespread among small businesses.
<P>

<CENTER> <STRONG> 1. Publications</STRONG></CENTER><dl>
<dt>Recommendation 1<BR>
     <dd>Comprehensive informational documents should be prepared and written 
in lay terms for each major group in the Standard Industrial Code.  These 
would serve as guides to explain the environmental requirements applicable 
to small businesses in each such category.<P>
<dt>Explanation:<BR>
     <dd>Because some small businesses do not have the resources to dedicate 
individuals solely to following environmental regulations, it is critical 
that information be provided to help them understand their obligations.  
     After much discussion, the Task Force determined the use of SIC Codes
would be an effective way to develop appropriate categories.  Such codes 
are somewhat standardized and because of their common usage would be a
readily available means of identifying the various industries to small 
business owners.  The guide should include information on permit
requirements, methods to determine which rules may apply, as well as 
compliance, pollution prevention, and other information that may be 
determined to be relevant.  These documents should be developed with input 
from affected businesses, as well as relevant trade associations.  This is
a high priority.
<P>
<dt>Recommendation 2<BR>
     <dd>General publications should be developed to provide information on 
environmental matters that may affect them.<p>
<dt>Explanation:<BR>
<dd>     In addition to specific documents for a given industry, the Task Force
recognized that similar general information also will be needed to assist 
small businesses, particularly with respect to industries not covered by 
the more specific documents discussed in Recommendation 1.  In addition, 
since many small businesses are dealing with regulations for the first

time, the publications should discuss laws and regulations, as well as 
explanations on how to participate in the regulatory process.  Guides also 
should be developed on how to interact with the Agency, particularly with 
respect to inspections and enforcement.<p>
     Again, these documents should be developed with input from small 
business operators and others in the private sector with relevant 
experience. 
<P>
This recommendations is a high priority.<p></dl>

<CENTER> <STRONG>II.Education</STRONG></CENTER><dl><BR>
<dt>Recommendation 1<BR>
     <dd>The Illinois Environmental Protection Agency and the Illinois 
Department of Commerce and Community Affairs should develop a system 
whereby seminars geared to small businesses are presented throughout the
state.<p>
<dt>Explanation:<BR>
     <dd>Publications of environmental regulations are insufficient in 
presenting the total picture.  Therefore, it would be appropriate to 
provide small businesses with the opportunity to attend seminars on 
relevant topics.  Since resources will limit the Agency's ability to 
implement some recommendations, it is believed that the private sector 
should help fill this role.  Associations and/or chambers of commerce could
sponsor seminars with the cooperation of the Agency, environmental 
attorneys, and consulting firms.  This recommendation is a high priority.
<p>
<dt>Recommendation 2<BR>
     <dd>Mentoring programs or similar techniques should be developed to 

facilitate sharing and assistance by large businesses to aid smaller 
businesses in understanding environmental obligations.<P>
<dt>Explanation:<BR>
     <dd>The Task Force was advised that some large businesses with educational 
capabilities are interested in assisting small businesses.  However, the
Task Force recognize that the different perspectives of small, medium, and 
large businesses may inhibit the success of a mentoring program.  
Therefore, the Task Force recommends that in the event medium or large 
businesses are willing to provide training, a pilot program should be 
developed to determine interest in such opportunities.  A clearinghouse of 
volunteers to answer questions might also be developed.  This recommendation
would be pursued as a pilot program.  This recommendation is a not a high 
priority.
<P>
<dt>Recommendation 3<BR>
  <dd>   Video libraries and computer diskettes containing educational and 
informational materials should be developed.<p>
<dt>Explanation:<BR>
     <dd>Small business operators may be unable to attend a class, and some 
informational brochures may be more technical than can be easily
comprehended.  It is suggested that a library of media other than written 
materials be developed and catalogued.  For example, remediation operations 
or inspections could be videotaped for playback for small businesses 

concerned about those situations.  Seminars could be videotaped for use by 
small businesses at a later date.  Computer programs could be developed to 
assist in completion of permit applications and other forms.  The Task
Force sees this as a long-term, rather than an immediate goal.  The Agency 
should be alert to opportunities to archive its activities for cataloging. 
This recommendation is not a high priority.<p>
</dl>
<CENTER><STRONG>III. Communication Avenue</STRONG></CENTER><dl>
<dt>Recommendation 1<BR>
     <dd>Partnerships should be developed between trade associations, chambers 
of commerce, and state agencies to help communicate useful information to 
businesses affected by environmental regulations.<P>
<DT>Explanation:<BR>
<DD>     Representatives of the chamber and associations on the Task Force
unanimously agreed to act as conduits for the dissemination of information 
from the Agency in newsletters, publications, and meetings.  Since 
association newsletters and trade journals are widely ready by small 
business owners, the Agency should undertake an aggressive campaign to have 
articles and/or information available to these publications for their 
inclusion.  Recognizing that meetings are a regular aspect of associations,
the Agency should develop a speakers bureau of its personnel who would be 
available for presentations to such meetings.<P>
This recommendation is a high priority.<P>

<DT>Recommendation 2<BR>
<DD>     A program should be implemented to seek small businesses' input in the 
development and adoption of environmental regulations.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     Rulemaking may have great impact on a small business.  However, small 
businesses typically do not have a full-time staff to monitor such 
developments.  Therefore, it is imperative that the Agency aggressively 
undertake to include small businesses, either individually or represented 
through associations, in the development of these regulations.  Without 
these efforts, small businesses will continue to be adversely affected
without an adequate opportunity to provide input into the rules that 
ultimately impact them.  Some efforts also must be made in the Agency to 
advise potentially affected businesses of regulations that will be 
developed.  This may include the development of a semi-annual regulatory 
agenda such as that published by the United States Environmental Protection 
Agency, or by early notification of trade groups once it is apparent that a 
regulation will be developed at some time in the future.  This
recommendation is a high priority.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 3<BR>
<DD>     The Agency should develop a strategy to disseminate information to the 
popular press such as business journals and local newspapers regarding 
programs affecting small business.<P>
<DT>Explanation:<BR>
<DD>     The Task Force believes that this would be a low cost, efficient means
of reaching businesses not otherwise involved in associations or trade
groups.  It is important that business journals, particularly in the
Chicago and St. Louis areas, be reached because most businesses read such

publications.  Therefore, information from the Agency on small business 
environmental programs would reach a greater population.  This 
recommendation is a high priority.<P>

<DT>Recommendation 4<BR>
<DD>     An environmental newsletter geared towards small businesses should be 
published by the Agency.<P>
<DT>Explanation:<BR>
<DD>     This newsletter should include information on regulations, deadlines,
technical information such as pollution, and other matters of interest to 

small businesses.  This newsletter would be mailed to chambers of commerce,
business associations,a and other individuals.  If some of the other avenues 
are developed adequately, the importance of this document may be lessened. 
This recommendation is not a high priority.<P></DL>

<CENTER><STRONG> IV. General Principles</STRONG></CENTER>
<DL>
<DT>Recommendation 1<BR>
<DD>     Pollution prevention information should be integrated into all efforts 
produced pursuant to the Education Recommendations.<P>
<DT>Explanation:<BR>
<DD>     The pollution prevention office of the Agency should actively seek to
provide assistance to small businesses in adapting their processes and
materials to prevent pollution, thus eliminating the need to comply with 
various regulations.  If a pollution prevention technique exists to remove
a business from regulation, that may be the most cost efficient method of 
complying.  This recommendation is a high priority.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 2<BR>
<DD>     The Agency should review its programs, policies and practices to 
ensure that they encourage and facilitate compliance by small businesses in 
the most cooperative and expeditious manner possible.
<DT>Explanation:<BR>
<DD>     Prior recommendations recognize that small businesses have an
obligation to learn the requirements applicable to their operations.  
Similarly, the Agency has an obligation to conduct its operation in a 
manner that encourages and maximizes compliance by small businesses in 
order to meet its mission of providing the best possible environment for 
the citizens of the State of Illinois.  This can best be achieved in a 
cooperative, non-adversarial manner whenever possible.  This recommendation 
is a high priority.
<P></DL>
<CENTER><STRONG> Conclusion</STRONG></CENTER>
     Some effective means are already in place to help reach small 
businesses, e.g., through associations and chambers of commerce.  Those 
entities may act as go-betweens to help alleviate the "fear factor", which 
many small businesses may be experiencing.  An improved environment can be 
achieved if businesses are better informed of their environmental 
responsibilities.
<P>

<a name="Compliance"><hr></a>
<H3>Compliance Recommendations</H3>
<P>
     The general consensus among the Task Force is that a large number of 
small businesses are out of compliance in Illinois.  Many small businesses 

are afraid of the Agency because the environmental requirements and the 
regulatory system in general are perceived as a threat to the business'
continued existence.  Further, the Task Force believes that this perception 
of small businesses is to some degree true, and that the current regulatory 
system, particularly as related to enforcement, acts as a disincentive for 
many small businesses to come into compliance.  This stems from a
combination of factors, some of which other recommendations address:
uncertainty over the applicability of permit and control requirements, lack 
of knowledge of the enforcement process, uncertainty over the amount of 
penalties likely for violations, and related factors.<p>
     Consequently, the Task Force structured its compliance recommendations 
to achieve two major objectives.  The first objective is to bring as many
small businesses into environmental regulation as possible, in a 
non-threatening manner where possible, and to bring those businesses into
compliance, thereby reducing future threats to the environment as well as 
to business.  For this reason, the Task Force recommends that the Agency 
develop and implement an amnesty program.  It is believed that such a
program has the potential to bring a substantial number of small business 
that might not otherwise be reached into compliance on a voluntary basis.<P>
     The second major objective is to keep small businesses in regulation 
and in compliance without threatening their existence.  The recommendations
following the amnesty recommendation are designed to achieve the second
objective.  All of the following recommendations in some way are designed 
to make the environmental regulatory system a little more accommodating for 
small businesses.<P>
  <DL>  
<DT>Recommendation 1<BR>
     <DD>In cooperation with small businesses and working with the Office of
the Attorney General and the Pollution Control Board, the Agency and DCCA 
should seek to develop a small business amnesty program that will provide a 
one-time opportunity for small businesses to opt into a no-penalty
compliance program, taking into account the federal and practical
limitations of such a program and nay legal and environmental constraints.<P>
<DT>Explanation:<BR>
<DD>     The Task Force believes there are a substantial number of small 
businesses that are currently operating in noncompliance with one or more
regulatory requirements.  Some of the businesses have some knowledge of 

environmental requirements but are unsure if the requirements are 
applicable to them and are afraid to find out.  Some are unaware of 
environmental requirements in general.  Some know they are operating in
violation, but are afraid if they attempt to come into compliance they will 
subject themselves to large monetary penalties and thereby jeopardize their 
business.  It is believed that the Agency is unaware of the identity of 
many of these businesses.<P>
     A carefully structured and well organized amnesty program would bring
a large number of small businesses into the regulatory program, which
should lead to a substantial increase in compliance both during the amnesty 
period and in the future.  For these reasons, the Task Force recommends
that the Agency implement an amnesty program.<P>
     While agreeing to recommend an amnesty program is relatively easy, 
reaching a consensus on the nature of such a program is much more
difficult.  The Task Force agrees that the ultimate goal of any amnesty
program is increased compliance.  Increased compliance as a goal argues for 

an amnesty program that is as broad as possible.  However, there are other 
factors that must be considered:  the salability of the program; both state 
and federal equity factors, such as should intentional violations be 
treated the same as non-intentional violations be treated the same as 
non-intentional; and whether serious health-threatening violations or 
criminal violations should be treated the same as inconsequential 
violations.<P>
     These issues prompted a sustained, thought-provoking discussion among 
Task Force members.  In the end, the Task Force agreed upon a general 
recommendation for an amnesty program.  This decision was made to allow all 
interested groups to have the opportunity to provide input into the 
development of the program.<P>
     The tax amnesty program implemented some years ago by the Illinois 
Department of Revenue was discussed as a model for the program.  It was 
very successful and was carried out with the acknowledgement that an 
amnesty program is "inequitable" on its face.  The key issue is whether an 
environmental amnesty program would achieve enough positive results to 
outweigh the inequities, which might result from certain applications.  The 
Task Force agreed that models such as the tax amnesty program should be 
reviewed in designing and supporting an environmental amnesty program.<P>
     The Task Force strongly believes that the success of the program would 
be directly related to efforts to publicize the program, with adequate lead 
time needed to enable the business community to respond.  In addition, the 
educational efforts contained in the Education Recommendations may be a 
necessary prerequisite to a successful amnesty program.  This 
recommendation may need to be adopted by a legislative amendment.<P>
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 2
     <DD>The Task Force recommends that the Agency, in cooperation with small 
businesses, develop a simplified enforcement process for small businesses 
and minor infractions.  The Task Force recommends that authority be given, 
through concurrence by the Office of the Attorney General, to the Director 
of the Agency to settle noncompliance matters, (including any penalty or 
other transfer of value) by agreement among the parties, and without the 
use of administrative citations or referral to the Office of the Attorney 
General.  Such authority would not preclude any parties from involving the 
Office of the Attorney General, if it is so desired.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The current enforcement process is very complicated and resource 
intensive, both for the business involved and the State.  The Task Force 
recommends that an enforcement process for small businesses be developed 
that is simpler and less expensive.  In particular, the Task Force 
recommends that the Agency be given authority to informally reach 
compliance agreements, including payment of any penalty or other transfer 
of value, avoiding the current formal enforcement process completely.  Such 
an approach could result in an enforceable contractual agreement, which 
would accomplish the same objectives as the current process at greatly 
reduced cost and with increased efficiency.<P>
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 3
<DD>     The Task Force recommends that the Agency develop a written penalty 
guidance applicable to small businesses.  Such a guidance should recognize 
that frequently financial resources for small businesses are severely 
limited.  The guidance also should provide:<P>
<UL type=square>
<LI>September  6, 1994    An incentive for self-reporting, such as a 50% reduction 
in penalty.
<LI>September  6, 1994    A credit mechanism for money spent for overcompliance.
<LI>September  6, 1994    A credit mechanism for implementation of pollution 
prevention measures.
<LI>September  6, 1994    An escalation factor for those that could have 
participated in an amnesty program but did not do so.
<LI>September  6, 1994    A recognition factor for payment or contributions to 
other government, community, or local public service organizations that contribute to 
local, community or state improvement. [See also Recommendation 6]

     The penalty guidance should be limited to use in negotiated 
settlements.</UL>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The existing enforcement process is keyed to the maximum penalties, as 
provided for in the Illinois Environmental Protection Act, of $50,000 per 
violation and $10,000 each day the violation continues.  As a practical 
matter the maximum penalty is almost never assessed.  However, the maximum 
numbers are a major contributor to the fear factor, which causes many small 
businesses to avoid environmental requirements to the extent possible.  
Many small businesses to avoid environmental requirements to the extent 
possible. Many small businesses would be bankrupted by an assessment of a 
penalty that could be handled by a larger business.  For this reason, the 
Task Force recommends a penalty policy specifically applicable to small 
businesses, which takes into account the limited resources of many small 
businesses.  The Task Force further recommends that the policy contain 
several credit factors that would credit the good faith of a company in 
self-reporting, in spending resources for compliance above and beyond that 
required by the regulations, and for implementing pollution prevention 
measures.  The Task Force also recommends a recognition factor that would 
both recognize payments or contributions to local public service 
organizations, government, community, or state organizations for the 
betterment of the community where the environmental problems occurred.<P>
     On the opposite side of the coin, the Task Force recommends an 
escalation factor for those companies that could have participated in an 
amnesty program but did not do so.  The Task Force believes that the 
penalty should be higher where there is bad faith or clear negligence by a 
business in not addressing violations that could have been resolved within 
the amnesty program at an earlier date.  In addition, the Task Force 
believes the threat of an escalation factor is important to the success of 
an amnesty program.<P>
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 4
<DD>     The Task Force recommends that the Agency and DCCa develop a program 
for identifying consultants who will offer small business consulting 
services.  Such a list should be made available to small businesses to 
assist them in obtaining compliance assistance.  The Task Force further 
recommends that the Agency and DCCA develop a guide that will assist small 
businesses in selecting consultants and in managing projects in which 
consultants are involved.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     Many small businesses find it very difficult to locate qualified and 
competent consultants, to afford, monitor and understand the activities of 
a consultant, and to determine whether their work has been or is 
acceptable.  Thus, to the extent possible, the Task Force recommends that 
the Agency and DCCA assist by providing a list of consultants that will 
provide services to small businesses.  In addition, the Task Force 
recommends that a guide be developed that would assist a small business in 
selecting a consultant and in managing a project, e.g., dividing a project 
into manageable segments.<P>
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 5
<DD>     The Task Force recommends the Illinois Environmental Protection Act be 
amended to allow the 35 day time frame for permit appeals by extended by a 
maximum of 90 days by mutual agreement of the applicant and the Agency to 
provide more time to negotiate solutions to problems that may be posed by a 
permit.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     When a company receives a permit from the Agency, it often contains a 
condition that the company finds unacceptable.  The company then has two 
options: to appeal or to attempt to negotiate with the Agency to remove or 
modify the condition in a manner that is acceptable.  However, if the 
company wishes to protects its right to appeal, it must file a petition 
with the Pollution Control Board within 35 days.<P>
    Frequently, a company will be negotiating with the Agency in an 
effort to find a mutually agreeable solution, and the company is forced to 
file its petition for appeal in order to protect its right to appeal.  This 
is time-consuming and expensive.  The Task Force's recommendation would 
allow the parties - the applicant and the Agency - to mutual agreement to 
extend the deadline for filing an appeal by up to a maximum of 90 days to 
allow more time to negotiate a mutually satisfactory result, and thereby 
avoid the time, effort and expense of an appeal.<P>
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 6
<DD>     The Task Force recommends that a program be developed to provide 
recognition of those businesses doing positive things for the environment, 
especially actions beyond those required by law.  This program should 
provide incentives for businesses to take positive environmental actions.  
At a minimum, it should include recognition either by publicity or a letter 
from the Agency that businesses could use with their customers.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Agency's programs are primarily designed to recognize and penalize 
non-compliance (enforcement) or to assure compliance (permits).  This 
contributes to an anti-business image of the Agency.  A strong program of 
positive reinforcement for those companies that do comply, and particularly 
for those companies that do more than the minimum required by the 
regulations, would provide recognition of those efforts and improve the 
Agency's image.  A letter of commendation or a certificate complemented 
with a news release would be appreciated by businesses.  Such recognition 
could be displayed within the company and might even be of assistance in 
promoting the business.<P></DL>
<P>

<a name="Permit Recommendations"><hr></a>
<H3>Permit Recommendations</h3>
<dl>
<DT>Introduction
     <DD>The Task Force spent considerable time discussing difficulties that 
small businesses have in determining whether they need none or more of the 
permits issued by the Agency.  The Task Force agreed that is is a threshold 
issue that needs to be dealt with in order to assist small businesses with 
the permit process.  The Task Force concluded that a series of publications 
of general use explaining how to deal with the Agency during the permitting 
process.  This publication would address many of the concerns that were 
expressed by small businesses, including:  how to complete an application, 
how to get assistance in the application process when necessary, how to 
deal with the Agency once an application has been submitted, and how to 
resolve any differences that might arise during that process or after the 
issuance of a permit.
<P>
     The Task Force also discussed a number of specific areas it believes 
would provide regulatory relief without compromising the protection of the 
environment.  From this, a number of recommendations were developed such as 
the expansion of the general permit approach, evaluation of permit 
exemptions, and the simplification of permit application forms and 
procedures.  There also was a discussion of how the permit document could 
be changed to help small businesses understand the requirements that apply 
to them.<P>
     The order of the recommendations that follows is not a prioritization 
of the recommendations.  The Workgroup considered eight of the nine 
recommendations to be high priority items.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 1
<DD>     The Agency should investigate the feasibility of developing an 
operating permit renewal system that provides small business applicants 
with an application form that includes the base information already in the 
Agency files.  The form also would request current or new information 
necessary for processing of the application and request verification of the 
base information.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     There is a widespread belief among members of the Task Force that 
simplification of the permit application process is important.  In order to 
address this concern in the permit renewal application area, the Task Force 
recommends that a system be developed similar to that recently used by the 
Agency's Bureau of Air for the annual emission report.  The Task Force 
believes that if the Agency could supply applicants with a printout of 
information already available to the Agency, this also could serve as an 
application and greatly facilitate the process for small businesses.  This 
form should highlight key pieces of information in order to encourage an 
applicant not to simply rubber stamp previous information as correct.  The 
form also would request any new information required since the previous 
application.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 2
<DD>     Where appropriate, interactive computerized permit systems should be 
developed or some other form of electronic communication, where disks would 
be sent by the Agency to permit applicants and returned to the Agency as 
permit applications.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Task Force discussed different methods for facilitating the 
permitting process for small business.  While all small businesses do not 
have computers available to them, the sense of the Task Force is that the 
vast majority of small businesses at least own a personal computer.  
Therefore, the Task Force agreed that the development of an interactive 
computer permit system would assist many small businesses initially, and 
many more small businesses over time.  This recommendation encourages 
development of simple, user-friendly computer disks, which could be mailed 
to small businesses with a notice of renewal, completed by small businesses 

on their personal computers and mailed back to the Agency.  The Task Force 
believes that the issues of how to get a legal, authorized signature to 
accompany the application could be handled simply to cover letter with the 
proper authorization contained in the letter, perhaps on a form prepared by 
the Agency.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 3
<DD>     The Agency should attempt to expand the "general" permit approach, such 
as that used for stormwater permits, into new areas where the permitted 
businesses are similar enough to allow standardized terms and conditions.  
These general permits should allow businesses to voluntarily opt into such 
a permit in order to foster prompt and efficient processing of permit 
applications and consistent treatment of similar businesses.  The scope of 
each general permit should be limited to a particular suitable type of 
permit.  Multi-media general permits should be avoided except for specific 
interrelated permits such as permits for air strippers at LUST sites, as is 
currently done for groundwater remediation permits.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Task Force believes a general permit approach, such as that used 
by the Agency's Bureau of Water for stormwater permits, could be very 
helpful to small businesses in areas where businesses are similar and would 
allow such standardization.  It is recommended that each Bureau within the 
Agency review all areas where a significant number of similar sources might 
exist and try to develop general permits in those areas.  There was a 
special interest in providing such general permits in areas where other 
actions or programs could be delayed by the need for a permit from another 
Bureau.  The Task Force believes that the use of general permits by a 
business should remain a voluntary option wherever possible.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 4
<DD>     A cooperative effort of the public and private sectors a should be 
developed to provide information, education, and assistance to small 
businesses on how to adjust or modify their business activities in order to 
reduce permit requirements applicable to their businesses.  This effort 
should include information on pollution prevention and other related 
methods.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Task Force agreed that efforts to simplify permitting requirements 
for small businesses should include a concerted effort to assist small 
businesses in modifying their activities, or voluntarily limiting their 
activities in a manner that would eliminate the need for certain types of 
permits where they are not essential.  The effort of the Agency's Bureau of 
Air to provide federally enforceable state operating permits in lieu of the 
Clean Air Act permit is the type of option that could greatly assist small 
businesses if similar efforts could be made in other permit areas.  This 
may require the cooperation of the Agency and various associations in order 
to disseminate information about the availability of such programs and 
methods to determine whether a specific small business could make use of 
such a program.  The Task Force agrees that inclusion of such methods as 
pollution prevention and process modification could be very helpful in 
those areas as long as the Agency ensures that small businesses receive the 
information.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 5
<DD>     The Agency should develop a steamlined and efficient system that would 
allow applicants to obtain information via telephone inquiry on the status 
of a pending permit application.  An attempt should be made to computerize 
such a system and allow electronic access by applicants to the application 
status information.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Task Force believes that easy access by a small business to 
information on the status of its permit application is very important.  
This stems from the fact that knowing when an operating permit will be 
acted upon can be critical to a small business.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 6
<DD>     A cooperative effort should be undertaken, where appropriate, to 
simplify permit application forms and procedures required of small 
businesses.  A through simplification of permit application forms should be 
undertaken for sources in different industrial categories and coordinated 
with the development of informational guides for industrial categories.  
This should be undertaken with awareness that some similar terms used in 
one permit program may have different meanings pursuant to federal and 
state law when used in another permit program.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Task Force agrees that the permit application process is at times 
difficult and expensive for small businesses.  Therefore, a very high 
priority has been placed on simplification of the permit application forms 
with a particular goal of providing forms that a small business could 
complete without great expense.  The Task Force recognizes that this is a 
large undertaking.  Therefore, the Task Force believes that this review 
should be coordinated with the Education Recommendations to develop 
information guides for various industrial categories to assist small 
businesses in understanding both permitting and compliance requirements.  
The Task Force believes that caution must be taken in this simplification 
process to avoid confusion, which might result between different permit 
systems, many of which are predetermined by federal law.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 7
<DD>     In cooperation with small businesses, the Agency should prepare a 
publication, or series of publications, on how to deal with the Agency 
during the permit process.  The publications should cover a range of 
issues, from how to determine whether a permit is needed to implementation 
of the requirements within an issued permit.  A separate publication on how 
to determine whether a business needs an air, land, or water permit should 
be developed.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     This recommendation grew from the sense of the Task Force that many 
small businesses know very little about the permit requirements or the 
permit processes of the Agency.  Since these are critical requirements for 
small businesses and essential to helping small businesses achieve 
environmental compliance, an effort to produce the appropriate 
informational publications is critical.<P>
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 8
<DD>     In cooperation with small businesses, the expansion of permit 
exemptions for small businesses should be carefully evaluated by the 
Agency, in order to eliminate permit requirements where there is no clear 
existing need.  For air pollution permits, this evaluation should be 
coordinated with the federal development of air toxic rules for sources 
that may be affected by those rules.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     This recommendation reflects the view of the Task Force that permit 
requirements for small businesses should be eliminated unless clearly 
necessary.  This is based on the assumption that some of the permit 
requirements applicable to small business may no longer be necessary.  
Expansion of the permit exemptions would provide considerable regulatory 
relief for small business.  The Task Force is aware that certain developing 
federal and state requirements, particularly the development of the air 
toxic program under the Clean Air Act, might prevent some exemptions.  
Therefore, the Task Force believes that any review of permit exemptions 
should take federal requirements into account in their development.<P>
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 9
<DD>     In cooperation with small businesses, the Agency should evaluate the 
format and structure of permits to determine whether changes can be made to 
make the permit document itself more understandable and useful to small 
businesses.  Changes to make permits into compliance information documents 
(similar to the federal air and water operating permit programs) should be 
created without making the documents too cumbersome.  Time lines for 
reporting and compliance activities should be included.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Task Force endorsed the general idea of developing permit 
documents that, when issued, would provide small businesses with a single 
source of information reflecting all the requirements that small businesses 
must meet in order to be in compliance with environmental regulations in a 
particular area.  It is believed that this would greatly enhance the 
ability of small businesses to know whether they are in compliance and 
allay fear that there are other requirements unknown to a small business, 
which they also must meet.  The Task Force believes this effort should be 
undertaken with sensitivity to make the documents as clear as possible.  In 
particular, the Task Force believes that creating permit documents that 
organize reporting and record keeping requirements and provide compliance 
time lines would be very helpful to small businesses.<P>
</DL>

<a name="Technology Recommendations"><hr></a>
<H3>Technology Recommendations</H3>
<dl>
<DT>Introduction
<P>
<DD>     The Task Force evaluated a number of technological systems to 
determine if they could help small businesses understand and meet 
environmental requirements.  In particular, the Task Force focused on 
computer systems that would be helpful to small businesses.  In doing so, 
the Task Force evaluated computer bulletin board technology, interactive 
permits, electronic filing, and computerized record keeping and reporting.<P>
     In general, the Task Force believes the technologies under 
consideration are supportive of the recommendations and should, therefore, 
generally be developed in concert with the implementation of the other 
recommendations, particularly the Education and Permit Recommendations.<P>
     The Task Force agreed that use of these technologies should begin as 
pilot projects.  This would ensure that ensure that resources would not be 
<P>
wasted developing an extensive system that would not be useful small 
businesses.  For example, the Task Force recommends a pilot project be 
initiated to develop an interactive computer system for permit applications 
in an appropriate area.  The Task Force also believes that a video library 
could prove helpful to small businesses, but should be used to increase the 
availability of the information being developed pursuant to the Education 
Recommendations.<P>
     The Task Force believes the use of the many computer technologies 
available should begin with a bulletin board system.  The system should be 
set up so that it can be expanded to accommodate a variety of other uses 
such as computerized record keeping, computerized reporting, interactive 
permits, and further down the road, electronic filing of permit 
applications and reports.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 1
<DD>     In cooperation with small businesses, a computer bulletin board should 
be developed and made accessible to small businesses by modem for the 
purpose of providing informational assistance to small business on 
environmental matters.  The bulletin board should originally be set up on 

small scale, but in a manner that will later expansion into a variety 
of other uses, including more sophisticated uses.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Task Force believes that a computer bulletin board would be useful 
and flexible source of information to small businesses, especially if it 
were set up so that any small business that has a personal computer with a 
modem could access the bulletin board.  The Task Force believes strongly 
that this would be an important initial step in the development of 
computerized methods to assist small businesses.  Time also should be taken 
to develop a good system that could be expanded to accommodate other 
recommendations.  It also is believed that the interrelationship with the 
U.S. EPA bulletin board system should be explored and that the system 
should be set up in a user-friendly, simplified manner, so that a small 
business person without computer experience could use this system.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 2
<DD>     In cooperation with small businesses, the Agency should develop 
interactive computer permit systems aimed at simplifying the permit 
application and review process.  It is essential that such systems be 
designed to cut down the review time for permit applications.  A pilot 
project in an appropriate permit area should be selected and implemented 
first to ensure that broader systems are developed and implemented 
effectively.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     As mentioned, the Task Force believes that an interactive computer 
permit system would be helpful to small businesses, but it should be 
developed through a pilot project.  Thereafter, it could be expanded to 
other areas based on that experience and responses to the pilot project.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 3
<DD>     In cooperation with small businesses, the development of computerized 
record keeping systems should be evaluated and developed where useful to 
assist small businesses in meeting environmental record keeping 
requirements.  This effort should be coordinated with the efforts to 
simplify permits, to develop permits as compliance documents, and to 
develop industry-specific information for small businesses.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Task Force spent considerable time discussing how software might 
be developed that could provide a computerized recordkeeping system for 
simplifying the recordkeeping requirements of small businesses.  Some 
commercial software already in existence combines such a record keeping 
system with a computerized reporting system.  There was concern about 
whether such commercial systems would be affordable to small business and 
whether the Agency should instead develop systems that would interact 
efficiently with the Agency information bases.  The Task Force believes 
that such systems might be valuable, if they can be developed in an 
effective and affordable manner.  And development of any such system should 
be coordinated with development of permits as compliance documents.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 4
<DD>     In cooperation with small businesses, the development of computerized 
reporting systems should be evaluated and developed to assist small 
businesses in meeting environmental reporting requirements, particularly 
permit and reporting requirements.  This effort should be coordinated with 
efforts to simplify permits and reporting requirements, to develop permits 

as compliance documents, and to develop industry-specific information for 
small businesses.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Task Force believes that a computerized reporting system that 
includes the reporting requirements contained in permits would be very 
helpful to small businesses.  Generally, the same issues and concerns 
existed for computerized reporting systems as described for computerized 
record keeping.<P>

<DT>Recommendation 5
<DD>     The development of electronic filing systems should be pursued as a 
long-term effort following the creation of other simplified computer 
systems, which could be converted to electronic filing systems.  The issues 
of security from competitor access and legal signature should be resolved 
to make electronic filing effective.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     Generally the Task Force believes electronic filing is worth exploring 
but it should be undertaken after implementation of the other computerized 
systems recommended.  In particular, the Task Force believes that 
interactive permits would be more valuable than electronic filing, without 
raising some of the same difficult issues involved in electronic filing.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 6
<DD>     The development of a video library of environmental information should 
be pursued as a long-term effort following the development of 
recommendations made elsewhere in this report.  In general, seminars on 
environmental topics are considered to be more useful and higher priority.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
     <DD>Generally, the Task Force believes that development of a video library 
would be helpful to small businesses but that it is less important than 
development of the information recommended elsewhere in this report.  The 
Task Force discussed how such videos could be made available to small 
businesses and suggested they be disseminated through associations, local 
chambers of commerce, or DCCA's small business assistance centers.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 7
<DD>     The development of effective delivery systems to get information to 
small businesses is essential to the success of the Small Business 
Initiative.  The cooperation of trade associations, local chambers of 
commerce, and similar groups in this effort is particularly important.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Task Force discussed the use of various technologies to assist 
small businesses as part of the broader need to develop and enhance the 
delivery of useful information to small businesses.  The Task Force agreed 
that the cooperation of groups representing small businesses is essential 
to these goals, including the use of the recommended technologies.<P></DL>


<a name="Financial Recommendations"><hr></a>
<H3>Financial Recommendations</H3>
<CENTER><STRONG> Introduction</STRONG></CENTER>
     The Financial Recommendations have been developed in response to a 
suggestion that it is necessary to look at the financial issues of small 
businesses facing environmental costs in order for the task force to look 
at the complete set of concerns facing small businesses.<P>
     The Task Force looked at two specific financial areas regarding small 

businesses and environmental regulation.  First, it looked at informational 
needs and problems encountered by small businesses in being aware of, or in 
dealing with, financing to meet the costs of environmental compliance.  The 
Task Force also examined whether any additional public programs are needed 
to aid small businesses in meeting the costs of complying with 
environmental programs.<P>
<DL>
<DT>Recommendation 1
<DD>     Information should be developed to communicate and explain existing 
financing programs that are available to assist small businesses in meeting 
environmental compliance costs.  This should include programs to address 
pollution control costs available through federal, state, and local sources 
including the Small Business Administration's pollution control loans, FMHA 
loans, community development block grants, community development assistance 
programs, and other public sources available.  This information should be 
provided to small businesses and lending institutions serving small 
businesses.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     One of the principal issues discussed by the Task Force was whether 
small businesses have difficulty obtaining information about financing 
alternatives available to them to meet the costs of complying with 
environmental regulations.  Generally, the Task Force agreed that most 
small businesses had established relationships with lending institutions 
and did not typically have difficulty obtaining financing due to lack of 
access to information about the practices or procedures of lending 
institutions.<P>
     However, general descriptive information about the range of private 
and public financing options would be helpful to many businesses.  In 
particular, the pollution control loans available from the federal Small 
Business Administration (SBA) do not appear to be very well known or 
utilized.  A particular effort to make useful and understandable 
information about these SBA loans available to small businesses, their 
representatives, and lending institutions might greatly assist small 
businesses in obtaining additional help in meeting the costs of complying 
with environmental regulations.
<P>
<DT>Recommendation 2
<DD>     In providing information to assist small businesses, the state should 
encourage small businesses to consult their lender prior to contracting 
with a consultant to avoid potentially duplicative costs.  It is important 
that small businesses be informed that many lending institutions will only 
accept information from consultants they know are satisfactory.<P>
     Small businesses should be advised that, in selecting environmental 
consultant, it is important to lending institutions that the consultant 
have liability insurance, usually to the amount of one million dollars, and 
that the insurance should not have a pollution exemption.<P>
     In addition, the Agency should provide information regarding a 
consultant's responsibilities to report environmental problems it 
identifies in its work.  Small businesses believe that the consultants are 
required by law to report the business to the Agency.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Workgroup agreed that a significant problem for small businesses 
arises if the selection of an environmental consultant is not undertaken 
cooperatively with lending institutions.  The recommendation reflects the 

specific concerns that the small businesses person should be aware of prior 
to choosing an environmental consultant and emphasizes the role lending 
institutions play regarding consultants.<P>

<DT>Recommendation 3
<DD>     In preparing the guides for industry categories as recommended in the 
Education Section, information should be included discussing the typical 
potential environmental risks and problems that a business in a specific 
category should consider, address, or evaluate.  Included in this should be 
any guidelines for addressing the typical risks for certain types of 
industries.  It is believed that such information will be valuable both for 
the small business and for any lending institution financing an 
environmental compliance project.  It should take the form of a discussion 
of known or likely problems that arise in a given industry, including such 
things as remedial actions or leaking underground tanks.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Task Force discussed and considered the value of the informational 
guides by industry category contained in the Education Recommendations.  
The Task Force agreed that these would be of value not only to small 
businesses but also to lending institutions making loans to small 
businesses for environmental compliance activities.  The Task Force 
concluded that the information guides should include industry-specific 
discussions of environmental risks that might exist at a small business and 
that should be examined by a small business and lending institutions.  
Where possible, the discussion of environmental risk should include 
guidelines for dealing with such risks.<P>

<DT>Recommendation 4
<DD>     Information should be developed that will aid businesses and lending 
institutions in evaluating site compliance and clean-up activities.  This 
information should be provided to small businesses and lending institutions 
serving small businesses.  It should include an explanation of the new 
legislation affecting leaking underground storage tanks.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Task Force discussed the need for greater knowlede and certainty 
regarding the nature and extend of environmental problems at a small 
business.  This would aid small businesses in understanding and dealing 
with environmental problems and would aid lending institutions serving 
small businesses in making loan decisions.<P>
     This problem most often occurs where a clean-up or remediation problem 
exists at a small business.  There was discussion of how the new 
legislative amendments contained in House Bill 300, which affects leaking 
underground storage tanks, would provide improved certainty in these areas 
and address the concern of the Task Force.  The Task Force concluded it is 
very important that information on these changes be distributed to both 
small businesses and lending institutions.<P>

<DT>Recommendation 5
<DD>     Governmental financing assistance programs should be investigated to 
determine whether any additional programs could assist small businesses in 
meeting the compliance costs for environmental requirements in tow major 
areas, i.e., remediation costs and compliance costs for high risk 
businesses that will have difficulty in obtaining financing for 
environemntal costs.  It is recognized that considerable thought and effort 

would need to go into the development of criteria for identifying 
financially high risk businesses and making them the beneficiary of 
financial assistance.  This is a high priority item to help avoid 
situations where a category of sources would have difficulty complying with 
environmental laws, due to their inability to obtain the financing needed 

to meet the costs of the compliance.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Task Force had lengthy discussions on how lending institutions 
make decisions about loans to small businesses for environmental compliance 
costs, including both remediation costs and funding for pollution control 
equipment.  The Task Force concluded that many environmental projects can 
be adequately handled within the normal loan framework used by lending 
institutions.  However, lending institutions do tend to categorize types of 
businesses according to possible environmental risks, and larger lending 
institutions identify environmental high risk industry groups.  As with 
other high risks areas, these businesses then have a more difficult time 
obtaining a loan, including a loanf or measures or activities to address 
those risks.  Many sites where remediation or clean-up may be necessary 
fall into this high risk category for loan purposes, as do many businesses 
with unassessed environmental risks.  The reasons for the high risk 
classification are th uncertainty that exists as to the extend of 
remediation that may be necessary, the costs associated with the 
remediation,and the inability to use land that may be polluted as security 
on a loan.<P>
     The Task Force expressed concern about whether public funding would be 
available to support any new programs in these areas.  For that reason, the 
Recommendation states that new programs be investigated to determine 
whether they could be developed.<P>
     The Task Force concluded that a significant policy concern exists 
where a small business has high risk rnvironmental problems but cannot 
obtain financing needed to address those environmental problems due to the 
very fact they are high risk problems.  Should lending institutions assume 
these risks?  Can small businesses address them without access to loans?  
And can these risks simply be left without any responsible person to 
address them?  The Task Force concluded that these might be approrpriate 
areas for additional public financing programs to address these issues.<P>

<DT>Recommendation 6
<DD>     Incentives should be developed in federal and state tax laws to 
encourage small businesses to install pollution control equipment and to 
undertake other activies in achieving environmental compliance.  Incentives 
that should be considered include accelerated depreciation of pollution 
control equipment and a pollution control tax credit.<P>
<DT>Explanation:
<DD>     The Task Force concluded that incentives should be developed within 
federal and state tax laws to support the purpose reflected in federal and 
state environmental laws.  Since the state tax incentive would only provide 
a portion of the relief that small business needs, the Task Force believes 
federal tax incentives also should be sought.  The prospect of future 
environmental regulations requiring additional controls or equipment 
increases the importance of accelerated depreciation.  The Task Force 
believes that this is a recommendation that could help small businesses.<P>
</DL>
<P>                       


