<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Office of Minority Business Development -- Hispanic Business Facts</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>Office of Minority Business Development</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>

<h3 align=center>
Fact Sheet<br>
Hispanic-Owned Business in Illinois
</h3>

ILLINOIS IS THE HOME OF 24 OF THE 500 LARGEST HISPANIC-OWNED BUSINESSES IN THE COUNTRY WITH ANNUAL SALES OF $258.53 MILLION.<p>

In the Chicago area Hispanic-owned businesses have continued to show steady growth. The number of Hispanic businesses has grown by over 300 percent from 1972 to 1995. Most are located in the Chicago neighborhoods of Logan Square, Little Village, Pilsen, West Town, South Chicago, Uptown, Humboldt Park and Avondale. There are also areas of concentration of Hispanic-owned businesses in other Illinois cities such as Aurora, Waukegan, Joliet, Elgin, Peoria, Rock Island and Rockford.<p>

The top three industries of Hispanic-owned businesses are services, retail trade and construction. Growth was most brisk in transportation, construction, finance and services with a spectacular growth of small diversified businesses. Growth receipts also quintupled from $51 million to $268 million over the same period. This tremendous increase makes the Chicago market the fourth largest in the U.S. after Los Angeles, New York and Miami. During 1994 these 24 companies created 3,230 jobs and generated $258.53 million to the Illinois economy.<p>

As of 1987 census, there are approximately 12,000 + Hispanic firms registered in the state and their steady growth is anticipated in the coming years. As a newcomer to the economic mainstream, Hispanic firms face many problems and obstacles that require special business assistance. Recognizing the special problems associated with this emerging group, the Hispanic Business Advocate was established in the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs' (DCCA) Office of Minority Business Development to serve as a liaison between minority business owners, organizations and the state to assist minority entrepreneurs who are starting or expanding their businesses in Illinois.<p>

The Illinois Hispanic Business Advocate, works closely with other components of DCCA's business service network including Small Business Development Centers, Procurement Technical Assistance Centers, International Trade Centers, NAFTA Opportunity Centers, the Office of Women's Business Development, Small Business Environmental Assistance and the First Stop Business Information Center to develop materials, approaches, policies and contacts which explain existing minority owned business assistance programs and direct these to targeted business groups and entrepreneurs.<p>

<em>Source:</em> Hispanic Business Magazine<p>

<strong>Contact:</strong>
<ul>
Manuel Suarez, Hispanic Business Advocate<br>
DCCA-Office of Minority Business Development<br>
James R. Thompson Center<br>
100 West Randolph Street, Suite 3-400<br>
Chicago, Illinois 60601<br>
312/814-2331  Fax: 312/814-5247<br>
TDD (for persons with hearing impairments): 800/419-0667<br>
World Wide Web: http://www.ilcommerce.com/<p>
</ul>

Developed through a partnership between the U.S. Small business Administration and the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs under cooperative agreement # SB-2M-00097-13.<p>


