<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Labor Management General Information</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>Labor Management General Information</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>

<img src="/dcca/graph/lm5.gif" width=235 height=341 align=right vspace=10 hspace=10>


<img src="/dcca/graph/lm3.gif" alt="Illinois Labor-Management Committees" width=131 height=78 align=left vspace=10 hspace=10>

The basic goal of all labor-management committees is to improve communication between labor and management, resulting in improved labor-management relations.  Although the structure, goals and objectives of the individual committees may vary depending on the economic conditions of their particular geographic area, all provide a forum in which labor and management can increase communication and work cooperatively toward the betterment of the area.<p>

<ul type=square>
<li>A local Area Labor-Management Committee (ALMC)  serves a municipal, county or regional population and consists of a core advisory body composed of representatives from business, labor, government and/or the public.  The ALMC generally has a permanent office, paid professional staff and full or part-time clerical staff.<p>

<li>An Industry Labor-Management Committee generally consists of associations or coalitions of employers and labor organizations which are involved in the same industry.  Industry committees have been formed in the building and construction, retail food, coal, masonry, men's clothing and rail-road industries.
</ul>

With the growth of the area committee, many industry committees have been incorporated as special subcommittees of an area committee.<p>

<hr>
<img src="/dcca/graph/lm4.gif" alt="Typical Local Labor-Management Programs & Services" width=131 height=78 vspace=10 hspace=10 align=right>

Typical services offered by an area committee include:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li>Conduct committee effectiveness training<p>
<li>Conduct job retention and site visits<p>
<li>Promote job retention and skill training<p>
<li>Sponsor programs for displaced workers<p>
<li>Provide general labor-force statistics<p>
<li>Host educational training programs<p>
</ul>

More specific programs and services include:<p>

<h4>Educational Conferences and Workshops</h4>

ALMC sponsored conferences and workshops provide important educational opportunities to keep members and others attending informed on major issues such as, Workplace Safety Programs, Americans with Disabilities Act, Sexual Harassment, Substance Abuse in the Workplace and Win/Win Bargaining.<p>

<h4>Annual Recognition and Awards Event</h4>

Annual recognition and awards events provide opportunities for ALMCs to: promote cooperative labor-management relations; increase community awareness of joint company/union efforts; and promote ALMC programs and services.<p>

<h4>Newsletters, Brochures and Media Coverage</h4>

Marketing efforts are an important and ongoing activity of the ALMCs which increase awareness of programs and services provided to local companies and unions.<p>

<h4>Special Union Construction Projects Agreements</h4>

Under these agreements unions and contractors work in harmony with the objective of demonstrating to contract awarding agencies and private construction users that organized labor and their employers strive to produce the best quality installation, on time and within budget.<p>

<h4>Video/Slide Show Presentations and Speaking Engagements</h4>

Additional efforts to raise awareness of benefits derived from cooperative labor-management programs and to promote a cooperative labor-management environment include developing video and slide show presentations.<p>

<hr>
<img src="/dcca/graph/lm2.gif" alt="Organizing an Area Labor-Management Committee" width=130 height=76 align=right>

<h4>Getting Started</h4>
<ul type=square>
<li>Determine committee size and membership
<li>Select co-chairs
<li>Conduct a preliminary meeting
<li>Develop an operating plan
<li>Develop a mission statement
<li>Develop a budget
<li>Determine committee goals and community needs
</ul>

<hr>
<img src="/dcca/graph/lm1.gif" width=131 height=76 align=left hspace=10 vspace=5>

There are a number of Illinois Area Labor-Management Committees and professionals available to provide the necessary training and technical assistance to organizations interested in starting an area/industry labor-management committee.<p>

For more information on assistance, available resources and the location of the ALMC nearest you, contact the Labor-Management Cooperation Unit at the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs by phoning 217/785-6215; TDD, 217/785-6055.<p>



<HR>
<STRONG>| <A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com">DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/files/wforce/labor.htm">Labor Management Grant Program</A> |</STRONG>
</BODY>
</HTML>
