<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA - Workplace Safety Programs</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>Workforce and Job Training</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>

<CENTER><H3>
On-Site Safety & Health Consultation Program<br>
A No-Cost Program for Illinois Employers
</H3></CENTER>
<HR>

<p>
The Illinois On-Site Consultation Program assists employers in providing their employees a safe and healthy workplace.  The goal of the program is to help Illinois employers identify and correct potential safety and health hazards before they become expensive and dangerous problems.<p>

The program is a no-cost service of the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs for Illinois employers.<p>

<h3>The Total Service Can Include:</h3>
<ul type=square>
<li>A walk through Safety and Health Survey
<li>Safety and Health Program assessment
<li>Employer/employee training
<li>Hazard communication
<li>Evaluation of electrical systems/equipment
<li>Review of machine guarding
<li>Noise measurements
<li>Air sampling and analysis
<li>Assistance with personnel protective equipment
<li>Comprehensive written reports
<li>Technical assistance
<li>Exemption from routine OSHA inspections
</ul>


<h3>Recommended By:</h3>
<ul type=square>
<li>Illinois Manufacturers Association
<li>Printing Industries of Illinois Association
<li>Illinois New Car and Truck Dealers Association
<li>Automotive Service Association, Inc.
</ul>

<hr>
<h3 align=center>How It Works</h3>

<h3>No-Charge to Illinois Businesses</h3>

The Occupational Health and Safety Consultation Program is available to any business with one or more employees.  We are unable to provide services to municipal, county, state or federal organizations.<p>

Services are provided through the Occupational Safety And Health Administration and administered through DCCA.  There is no charge to any business requesting service.<p>

<h3>Providing Knowledgeable Helpful Assistance</h3>

Program staff are experienced professional safety and industrial hygiene consultants trained to identify safety and health hazards in you business or industry, supply recommendations to reduce or eliminate these hazards, and assess your safety and health programs.  Our purpose is to help your business meet current OSHA job safety and health regulations and to develop an ongoing, effective safety and health program.  We will provide you with confidential, comprehensive written reports containing our findings and recommendations.  Additionally, we will provide follow-up services when requested which can include safety or health training at your place of business.<p>

<h3>Voluntary Employer Participation</h3>

Program staff provide consultation services only at your request.  We will meet you at your place of business, go through your facility with you and point out and explain potential health and safety hazards.  The consultation may include all or any part of the facility or work site, as requested by the employer.  You can also opt to pursue an exemption, with our assistance, from routine OSHA inspections.<p>

<h3>Offering A Non-Penalty Approach</h3>

Our consultants do not issue citations or penalties for violation of OSHA regulations.  Our function is to identify hazards and violations of the regulations and provide recommendations for correction.<p>

<h3>With Employer Commitment to Safety and Health</h3>

Employers must be committed to the elimination of serious hazards.  Our consultants will help you in this process.  Our objective is to assist Illinois employers in providing a safe and healthful working environment, and we ask that all employers actively join us in achieving this goal.<p>

<hr>
<h3 align=center>Major Steps in the Consultation Process</h3>
 
<h4>STEP 1 - Request</h4>

You must advise us of your interest.  You start the process.<p>

<h4>STEP 2 - On-Site Visit</h4>

A date and time is set for an on-site visit at your business or plant.  During the visit there is an opening conference, a walk-through survey, a safety and health program assessment, and a closing conference to discuss the hazards found.<p>

<h4>STEP 3 - Evaluation and Report</h4>

Following the visit, all collected information is evaluated and relevant research conducted.  This may include laboratory analysis if air samples are taken.  A report detailing all findings and recommendations, including ways to improve your safety and health program, is prepared and forwarded to you.<p>

<h4>STEP 4 - Correction of Serious Hazards</h4>

The report you receive will discuss potential hazards, a number of which may be considered to be of a serious nature.  Corrective action by the employer on these or imminent hazards is a required part of this program.  The employer and consultant agree to a set timeframe for correction of the serious hazards.<p>

<h4>STEP 5 - Follow-up</h4>

Once serious hazards have been corrected, you will be asked to confirm your corrective actions.  In a few instances a return visit may be necessary, for example in cases of assuring healthful air quality.  We will follow up with employers seeking an exemption from routine OSHA inspections.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Employer's Obligation</h3>
<ul type=square>
<li>Appoint a designated representative to attend opening and closing conferences.
<li>Take action to correct serious and imminent hazards.
</ul>


<h3>It's Easy to Overlook the Costs of:</h3>
<ul type=square>
<li>Medical costs of job related injuries and illnesses
<li>Lost supervision time
<li>Repair or replacement of damaged equipment
<li>Administrative costs: claims, reports and other red tape
<li>Production schedule disruption, temporary personnel transfers to unfamiliar job, line     rebalancing
<li>Training of replacement employees.
<li>Increase in Workers' Compensation Insurance
</ul>


The intangible costs of industrial accidents and disease, although difficult to measure, are just as real as insurance premium costs.<p>

<h4 align=center>DON'T LET AVOIDABLE SAFETY AND HEALTH HAZARDS CUT INTO YOUR PROFITS!</h4>

<hr>
<h3>Summary</h3>

The Consultation Program provides several benefits for you as an employer.<p>

<h3>On-Site Consultants WILL:</h3>
<ul type=square>
<li>Help you to recognize hazards in your workplace.
<li>Suggest approaches or options for solving a safety or health problem.
<li>Identify kinds of help available to you if you need further assistance.
<li>Provide you with a written report that summarizes these findings.
<li>Assist you in developing or maintaining an effective safety and health program.
<li>Offer training ad education for you and your employees at your workplace, and in some cases, away from the site.
<li>Under specific circumstances, recommend you for recognition by OSHA and a one-year exclusion from general schedule enforcement inspections.
</ul>


<h3>Consultants Will NOT:</h3>
<ul type=square>
<li>Issue citations or propose penalties for violations of OSHA standards.
<li>Routinely report possible violations to OSHA enforcement staff.
<li>Guarantee that any workplace will pass an OSHA inspection.
<li>Prescribe specific engineering designs or identify specific firms to solve problems.
</ul>


<hr>
<h3 align=center>How to Get Help</h3>

A consultation may be requested in person, by phone, mail or by fax.  If you would like to request a consultation, or want more information on the program, write or call a consultant at the office below.<p>

Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs<br>
Industrial Services Division<br>
100 West Randolph Street, Suite 3-400<br>
Chicago, Illinois 60601<br>
312/814-2337<br>
800/972-4216<br>
fax: 800/814-7238<br>
TDD: 800/419-0667<p>

This material, and the safety and health consultations, are free of charge to owners, proprietors, and managers of small businesses.  They are provided by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs under a program largely funded by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA), an agency of the U.S. Department of Labor.<p> 








<HR>
<STRONG>| <A HREF="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/osha.htm"> On-Site Safety & Health Consultation</A> |</STRONG>
</BODY>
