<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA - Workplace Safety Programs</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>Workforce and Job Training</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>

<h3 align=center>Resolving Your Indoor Air Quality Problems</h3>
<hr>
<p>
<h3>Preface</h3>

This information can be used as a guide to recognizing indoor air quality problems and will provide helpful insight for resolving problems.  It can also serve as a resource identifying where additional information and assistance can be found.<p>


<h3>Introduction</h3>

In the 1970s, the encouragement of energy conservation programs led to the design and operation of buildings to conserve fuel and operating costs.  Buildings were sealed to prevent the infiltration of outside air.<p>

What followed were indoor air quality complaints from building occupants.  The sources and causes are as varied as the symptoms and health complaints.  Oftentimes, these symptoms are severe enough to result in missed work days and decreased productivity.<p>

Indoor air quality is a function of many parameters including outdoor air quality in the vicinity of the building, the configuration of enclosed space, the design of the ventilation system, the way the system is operated and maintained, and the presence of sources of contaminants and the concentrations of those contaminants.<p>

At the present time, a federal standard for indoor air quality does not exist.  The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) provides research and technical assistance to the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) as required under the Occupational Safety and Health Act of 1970.  They have evaluated indoor air quality problems as they relate to health effects on workers in non-residential and non-industrial workplaces.  Between 1971 and 1988, NIOSH conducted approximately 529 Health Hazard Evaluations in a variety of office building environments in response to reported health complaints from employees.  The investigations attempted to identify sources of contaminants, assess the performance of the ventilation system and evaluate other comfort parameters (temperature and humidity).  The following table describes, by class, the types and frequency of problems found:<p>

<pre>
<strong><em>PROBLEM TYPE                       NO. OF INVESTIGATIONS       % OF TOTAL</em></strong>

Ventilation inadequate                     280                     53%
Inside contamination source                 80                     15%
Unknown                                     68                     13%
Outside contamination source                53                     10%
Microbiological contamination               27                      5%
Building materials contamination            21                      4%
</pre>

*Note that inadequate ventilation accounted for the problems in over 50 percent of the investigations.

<h3>Typical Symptoms</h3>

The following are symptoms and complaints commonly attributed to indoor air quality problems.  They are usually not clearly defined and not specific enough to associate with a particular illness.  They include:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li>headache
<li>fatigue
<li>eye, nose and throat irritation
<li>sinus congestion
<li>skin irritation
<li>coughing
<li>sneezing
<li>nausea
<li>shortness of breath
<li>dizziness
</ul>


It is often helpful to the person conducting an indoor air quality investigation to obtain as much information as possible from those employees experiencing problems.  Such information might include symptoms employees are experiencing; specific days of the week when symptoms have occurred; worsening of symptoms on any particular days; times of the day when the symptoms are experienced; start-up of symptoms; determination if symptoms clear up after leaving work; identifying any pre-existing health problems or allergies; operation of video display terminals (VDTs), copy machines or any other special machines; smoking areas and users of those areas; location of work area; job tasks; and employee observations which may be associated with the symptoms.<p>


<h3>Reasons for Complaints and Potential Solutions</h3>

Aspects to consider when evaluating indoor air quality problems are listed below:<p>
<ul type=square>

<li>carbon dioxide levels and adequate quantities of fresh air 
<li>construction/remodeling
<li>smoking
<li>microbiological contamination
<li>location of the air handling unit in relation to potential air contaminant sources
<li>preventive maintenance
</ul>


<h3>Carbon Dioxide Levels & Adequate Quantities of Outdoor (Fresh) Air</h3>

Carbon dioxide (CO2) is a normal constituent of exhaled breath and , if monitored can be used as a tracer gas and screening technique to evaluate whether adequate quantities of outdoor (fresh) air are being introduced into a building or work area.  The outdoor, ambient concentration of CO2 is usually 250 to 350 part per million (ppm).  Generally, concentrations are higher inside.  However, if indoor CO2 concentrations are more than 1000 ppm, it is an indicator of inadequate ventilation.  Inadequate ventilation typically results in complaints such as headaches, fatigue and eye and throat irritation.  Please note that the CO2 concentration is not actually responsible for the complaints.<p>

With adequate ventilation maintaining CO2 concentrations below 600 ppm, and with comfortable temperature and humidity levels, complaints about air quality should be minimal.  The American Society of Heating, Refrigeration and Air Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE) considers temperatures in the range of 68.5-74.5 degrees Fahrenheit in the winter and 73.0-79.0 in the summer (at 50% relative humidity) comfortable and healthful.  These ranges apply to persons in typical summer and winter clothing doing primarily light work.  A general range of 30-70% relative humidity is usually accepted as comfortable.<p>

Sometimes problems arise because the ventilation system is shutdown while the building is unoccupied.  If this is the case, carbon dioxide concentrations may be as high as 1000 ppm early in the morning.  This is higher than would be expected and it indicates that it may be necessary to have the system left on for several hours after the occupants leave the offices at the end of the workday to purge the work area of air contaminants.  This helps to maintain the air quality in the morning at or near that of outdoor (fresh) air.<p>

Carbon dioxide concentration of 1000 ppm or greater in the afternoon indicate that provisions may need to be made to introduce significantly more outdoor (fresh) air into the occupied space.  The total quantity of make-up air may need to be increased in addition to increasing the proportion of outside air to total air.  Outdoor air should be adequately distributed to all occupied areas during the entire time they are occupied, at minimum rate of at least 20n cubic feet per minute (cfm) of outside air per person assuming there are 7 people for every 1000 square feet (ASHRAE 62-1989).<p>

In common areas where smoking is permitted, the rate should be at least 60 cfm per person.  All air vents (diffusers) should be checked to ensure they are open and unobstructed,  providing for adequate air mixing in each supplied area.<p>

Keep in mind that carbon dioxide sampling does not necessarily have to be conducted.  If quantities of outdoor air are adequate (as specified by ASHRAE) and distributed properly, complaints about air quality should be minimal.  If a particular source of contamination is present in the space, ventilation requirements may need to be increased.  ASHRAE defines acceptable indoor air quality as "air in which there are no known contaminants at harmful concentrations as determined by cognizant authorities and with which a substantial majority (80% or more) of the people exposed do not express dissatisfaction."<p>

<h3>Smoking</h3>

Studies have shown that environmental tobacco smoke is one of the most harmful and widespread indoor air pollutants.  It contains over 4000 chemicals 43 of which are known animal and human carcinogens.  The preferable method to protect non-smokers is the elimination of smoking indoors.  The alternative method is to require that smoking be permitted only in separately ventilated smoking areas.  Ideally, air from a smoking area should be exhausted directly outside and not recirculated in the building ventilation system.  The smoking areas should also be under negative pressure in relation to the adjoining areas to prevent smoke contaminated air from leaking out of the smoking area and into adjoining areas.<p>

<h3>Construction/Remodeling</h3>

Oftentimes, renovation of an office area can generate complaints about air quality.  During construction activities, return registers in the construction areas  into adjoining areas.  The installation of temporary barriers may help to confine dust, noise and other air contaminants.  After construction activities are completed,  supplying a maximum amount of ventilation initially on a 24 hour basis can assist in rapid dispersion of contaminant levels.<p>

Formaldehyde and other organic vapors can off-gas from insulation, particle board, plywood and glues used in the manufacture of new furnishings and carpeting.  If possible, once new furnishing s have been installed, the ventilation should be left on high when there are no occupants.  This will help in the dissipation of these vapors.<p>

<h3>Microbiological Contamination</h3>

Heating, ventilation and air conditioning (HVAC)  mechanical components can function as reservoirs for microorganisms.  This can be a significant problem in HVAC systems where maintenance is inadequate or lacking.  The presence of adequate nutrients (dust and debris) and moisture provide an ideal site for fungal amplification.  A variety of health disorders can result from microbiological exposure.  Hypersensitivity pneumonitis (HP) and other respiratory diseases have symptoms which include chest tightness, coughing, muscle aches, chills, fever, headache and fatigue.<p>

Microbiological contamination can also result from water damage to carpet and furnishings.  It is recommended that any sources of microbial contamination be eliminated by discarding rather than cleaning and/or dehumidifying the furnishings and carpeting.  Also, eliminate any standing water in the ventilation system components.<p>


<h3>Location of the Air Handling Unit</h3>

The location of the intake vents on the air handling unit may result in contaminated outside air being brought into the occupied space.  Sometimes the air handling unit is located close to a receive dock and vehicle exhaust is pulled into the building' ventilation system.  Other possibilities amy be that the air intake is down wind of a nearby construction project involving asphalt or solvents or may be downwind from a nearby manufacturing facility's exhaust ventilation for processes being conducted in the plant.  In some cases, a building air intake may be too close to its own exhaust vents and consequently, the exhausted air is pulled back into the building.<p>

If there are specific times of the day when the air intake brings in excessive exhaust fumes or vapors,  it may be possible to turn the air handling unit off until the fumes dissipate in the area.  This should only be done if the situation is infrequent.  (If the problem is more general and cannot be solved by simply temporarily turning off the air handling unit,  it may require moving the air intake to a more appropriate location.  Otherwise, investigation of the use and availability of a filter to collect the contaminants before they are distributed by the air handling unit may be helpful.<p>

A negative pressure situation arises when there is an insufficient supply of make-up air to a building.  This can cause untreated air (with air contaminants) to enter from outside (perhaps, through an elevator shaft or open dock doors).  The solution is to properly balance the air supply and exhaust systems.  This is especially important after additions to a building have been made and construction of new walls and/or rooms has taken place.<p>

<h3>Preventive Maintenance</h3>

An HVAC system requires adequate preventive maintenance in order to operate correctly and provide good indoor air quality.  The following components of the system require maintenance in order to maintain comfort and deliver adequate ventilation air:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li>outdoor intake opening
<li>damper controls
<li>air filters
<li>drip pans
<li>cooling and heating coils
<li>fan belts
<li>humidification equipment
<li>distribution systems and exhaust fans
</ul>


The equipment should be inspected regularly to ensure that it is in good condition and is operating as designed.<p>

<h3>References</h3>
<em>
Guidance for Indoor Air Quality Investigations, National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH), January 1987<p>

Building Air Quality - A Guidance for Building Owners and Facility Managers, Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), December 1991<p>

American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers, Inc. (ASHRAE 62-1989), Ventiltion for Acceptable Indoor Air Quality<p>
</em>


<HR>
<STRONG>| <A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com">DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/osha.htm"> On-Site Safety & Health Consultation</A> |</STRONG>
