<hr>
<h3>
Summer EnergyNet Institute<br> 
To Be Held At Two Sites
</h3>

Because of the growing interest in the EnergyNet Program, there will be two summer EnergyNet Institutes; one at Illinois State University at Bloomington/ Normal, week of July 8-12, 1996; and the other at the University of Illinois-Urbana/Champaign, July 15-19. Some 500 students, teachers and administrative personnel will spend 4-1/2 days learning how to perform an energy audit on their school building and to prepare energy conservation measures to recommend to their School Boards. The second component of the program is one of technology. Students and teachers learn how to use computer programs to enter their school's  energy profile into a data base and share information with other schools via E-mail. They also learn how to locate energy resources via the Internet. Those ILEED teachers who have previously requested EnergyNet information will be invited to attend one of these summer Institutes. <p>

For more information, call Marie Lauricella at 312/814-3467; TDD 312/419-0667.<p>

<hr>
<h3>ILEED Soon to Have a Home Page on the Internet</h3>

At our last Teachers' Advisory Board Meeting, students from Palatine School District #15 demonstrated to teachers how to surf the net for energy and environmental resources and also showed them several Home Pages. It was suggested that ILEED should have its own Home Page. Bill Conrad, Curriculum Coordinator of Palatine District 15, has taken the lead and will be assisted by Carl Sandburg Junior High students in designing an ILEED Home Page and also agreed to be the Web Master. Marie Lauricella and Peggy Chamness are working with Bill Conrad and his students. We will keep you informed.<p>

<hr>
<h3>
Amundsen High School <br>
Hosts Secretary of Energy Hazel O'Leary
</h3>

On a recent visit to Chicago, Secretary Hazel O'Leary, Secretary of the U.S. Department of Energy, visited Amundsen High School, one of the EnergyNet schools. About 20 students demonstrated through visual aids how they conducted their energy audit and discussed the energy conservation measures they recommended. They also demonstrated how they use computer software in conjunction with this program. While on-line, Secretary O'Leary received questions via E-mail from students at East Peoria High School, another EnergyNet School.<p>

In a recent letter to the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, Secretary O'Leary said: "I commend your leadership in teaching energy conservation and environmental stewardship to our young people. As demonstrated at Amundsen High School, our combined efforts reap tremendous results."  ILEED is pleased to be in partnership with the TECH 2000 group in the EnergyNet Program.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Workshops  Will Take Place In Fall.... Schedule  To Be Announced In August</h3>

ILEED plans to host 12 workshops for the 1996-97 school year at sites throughout Illinois for students grades 4-8 and their teachers. These one-day workshops are designed to introduce teachers and students to our free activities and program. While these workshops took place in January and February of this school year, teachers and students have requested that they take place in the fall. We are presently working on our schedule and also will be redesigning the workshops with input from our Teachers Advisory Board. <p>

We'd love to have you join us at one of our "new" workshops!  Watch for the ILEED  workshop brochure which will be mailed to you in late August.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Rookie of the Year</h3>

Alan B. Shepard School<br>
Bourbonnais<br>
is recognized for their first year achievement in energy/environmental education.<p>

Keep Up The Good Work!<p>

