<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: ILEED News, Winter 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<HR>
<CENTER>
<center><img src="../../graph/ileed.gif" alt="ILEED News" width=373 height=152></center>
<H2>Winter 1996</H2>
</CENTER>
<hr>

<h3>March Features the Renewable Energy Source - Wind!!</h3>


Did you know that wind is considered an indirect form of solar energy?  This is because the wind is driven mainly by temperature differences on the surface of the earth that are caused by sunshine.<p>

For centuries, the wind has been used to sail ships, grind grain, and pump water.  Now, people use the wind to generate electricity.  The windmills built long ago had many blades, but today's wind turbines usually have just two or three blades that turn when the wind blows, but the blades on the wind turbine are much longer than those you might see on a windmill.  In fact, wind turbine blades can be up to 82 feet (25 meters) long!<p>

The blades drive a generator that produces electricity, much like steam turbines.  The longer the blades and the faster the wind speed, the more electricity the turbine generates.  Wind turbines are placed on towers because the wind blows harder and more steadily above the ground.  To produce the most electricity, wind turbines need to be located in areas where the wind blows at a constant speed, which it does not do in all parts of the world.  Wind speed is described by seven "classes".  For example, Class 7 winds are extremely strong, while Class 2 winds are mild breezes.  Generally, Class 4 winds and above are considered adequate for a wind turbine to produce electricity.<p>

Large groups of wind turbines, called wind farms or wind plants, are connected to electric utility power lines and provide electricity to  many people.  New turbine designs now take advantage of less windy areas by using better blades,  more electronic controls, and other improvements.  Some new turbines can also operate efficiently over a wide range of wind speeds.<p>

An advantage of wind turbines over some forms of renewable energy is that they can produce electricity whenever the wind blows (at night and also during the day).  In theory, wind systems can produce electricity 24 hours every day, unlike PV systems that can't make power at night.  However, even in the windiest places, the wind does not blow all the time.  So, while wind farms don't need batteries for backup storage of electricity, small wind systems do need back-up batteries.  And, we're still learning about local wind patterns and how they affect wind turbines and blades.<p>

<hr>
<h3>ILEED Program Update</h3>
<h4>
Workshops<br>
Grades 4-8
</h4>
With the 95-96 school year well underway, the Illinois Energy Education Development (ILEED) staff has met several students and teachers at the workshops and various conventions.  Despite the hazardous winter weather, the January workshops' average attendance was 78.  Students left the workshops excited and enthused and ready to start and /or complete energy/environmental workshop presenter, entertained and motivated 4-8th grade students throughout the state with his G.O.A.P.E. leadership skills presentation and the Energy Olympics project, while teachers were allowed some networking time.<p>

<h4>
Youth Awards Ceremony<br>
Grades K-12
</h4>
On May 1, 1996, in Springfield, the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs is hosting a luncheon to honor students and educators who have active energy/environmental education programs in place in their school or community.  The ILEED staff would love to see you in Springfield!  The top projects in three categories are chosen to represent Illinois in the national awards competition on June 21-24 in Washington, D.C.  The ILEED committee urges schools to document their projects form the beginning with pictures and text.<p>

<h4>
Summer Intern Program
</h4>
Internships for participating high school junior and seniors will be announced by march 28.  These students will spend the summer of 1996 working for organizations in their communities on a variety of projects involving energy auditing, recycling, utility issues, environmental issues, etc.  If you know of a high school student or business that would like to participate in the 1997 program please contact the ILEED staff.  It's not too early to plan for summer 1997.<p>

<h4>
Camp Keep, JULY 14-19<br>
Grades 5-8
</h4>
Applications are being taken until May 15 for Camp KEEP (Kids for Energy and Environmental Protection).  Camp registration fees are $175 which includes all camp expenses, except transportation.  High school and college student counselors teach campers about energy and the world around them by playing games, hiking, participating in arts and crafts, working on group projects and other fun activities.  Illinois teachers serve as adult mentors.  Camp is held in Cantrall, Illinois, just outside of Springfield.<p>

<h4>
Teacher Advisory Board
</h4>
The annual meeting of the teacher advisory board was held in Chicago, December 4-5.  Various teachers and administrators representing grades K-12 met to discuss and generate ideas for upcoming ILEED programs.  Access to Internet and various telecommunication projects were high on their list of priorities.  A student group from District 15 in Palatine with educator Bill Conrad, gave a demonstration on how to make a home page and explained ways their classroom used the latest telecommunication technology to promote energy/environmental education and conservation.<p>

<h4>
EnergyNet<br>
Grades 7-12
</h4>
In an effort to incorporate "telecommunications" projects in Illinois schools, the Illinois State Board of Education has joined forces with the EnergyNet Project to accomplish this goal.  Approximately 240 students and teachers representing 60 schools (grades 7-12) attended the EnergyNet Institute in Springfield, November 29-December 1.  Working in teams, students and teachers learned about energy auditing, energy conservation measures, and reading and interpreting utility bills.  They also attended hands-on computer classes which featured software that analyzed energy data; and also learned how to surf the Internet for useful energy resources.  Team building activities were stressed throughout the Institute.<p>

Those ILEED schools which have previously expressed interest in EnergyNet have been placed on the list of schools to be invited to this summer's EnergyNet Institute.  This is a week-long program which is scheduled to take place August 1996.  If you'd like to learn more about the EnergyNet Project, please call Marie Lauricella at 312/814-3467; TDD 800/419-0667.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Recycling Grants Available</h3>

The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs' (DCCA) Bureau of Energy an recycling is announcing the availability of school recycling education grants for all Illinois schools (K-12), public and private, for school year 1996-1997.  The grant money can be used to implement or expand recycling and waste reduction programs i schools.  Purchasing collection and storage containers, implementing school-wide source reduction activities, promoting classroom education on recycling and waste reduction are allowable expenditures.  All Regional Offices of Education, larger school districts and the six regions of the Chicago Public School District (#299) are eligible to apply for the grant.  Depending on the number of participating students, grants may be awarded ranging from $5,000 to $35,000. <p>

The proposals are due by March 15, 1996, and awards will be announced by April 24, 1996.  The Department will conduct several workshops to answer questions on the grant application process and proposed projects.<p>

The Request For Proposals may be requested form the Information and Distribution Center of DCCA at 620 East Adams, Springfield, IL 62701 or call 800/252-8955; TDD 800/785-6055.  For workshop locations and dates and other additional information call Bina Fleck at 217/785-2800; TDD 217/785-0211.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Partners in Environmental Education Directory</h3>

The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs and the Illinois Chamber are pleased to present the Partners in Environmental Education program (PIE)-a partnership between Illinois businesses and schools to promote environmental education.  The new PIE directory, an up-to-date listing of resources and services available to Illinois schools provided by Illinois businesses, government agencies and not-for-profit organizations, is available from the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs.  For your free directory contact Jan Halford at 217/785-3412; TDD 217/78/5-0211.<p>

<HR>
