<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<HR>
<CENTER>
<center><img src="../../graph/ileed.gif" alt="ILEED News" width=373 height=152></center>
<H2>Fall 1995</H2>
</CENTER>
<hr>

<h3>Free Energy/Environmental Education Programs Available</h3>

Welcome to the Illinois Energy Education Development (ILEED) Program!  ILEED (pronounced "I Lead"), offers FREE enrgy/environmental materials and services to Illinois K-12 schools.<p>

ILEED sponsors teacher/student workshops, a summer camp for 5th-8th grade students, state and national award recognition programs, telecommunications/weatherization audit training institute for students and teachers, paid professional summer internships for high school students, essay contests, and an opportunity to network with other energy/environmental educators.  Details of ILEED program components can be found in this newsletter.<p>

Formerly a program with the Illinois Department of Energy and Natural Resources, ILEED now is a part of the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs.  The ILEED staff is pleased to be a part of this agency and looks forward to promoting energy conservation education programs in the schools, businesses and local communities.<p>

To find out more about the ILEED program, please call or write:<p>
<ul>
Peggy Chamness<br>
325 West Adams, Room 300<br>
Springfield, IL 62704<br>
217/785-3411<br>
217/785-0211 TDD<br>
217/785-2618 Fax<p>
</ul>

<hr>
<h3>ILEED Components</h3>

<h4>
Workshops<br>
Grades 4-8<p>
</h4>
Teachers are invited to bring up to five students to an all day workshop to learn about energy and the environment.  At the workshops, presenter Rich Ammentrop, 1994 Energy/Environmental Education Professional of the Year, encourages students working together from various schools to participate in several hand on energy activities.  While having fun, students are taught leadership skills necessary to organize energy and environmental education projects in their school.  Workshops are free and lunch is provided for participants.  Call the Information and Distribution Center at 217/785-6194 or 800/252-8955 (Illinois residents only); TDD users call 800/785-6055.<p> 

<h4>
Awards Program<br>
Grades K-12<p>
</h4>
Recognition is an integral part of learning.  Students are encouraged to send a report to the ILEED committee summarizing their energy/environmental activities during the school year.  School groups that have organized energy/environmental projects are invited to attend the ILEED Statewide Youth Awards Banquet in Springfield in the spring.  The top projects in three categories are chosen to represent Illinois in the national awards competition in June in Washington, D.C.  The ILEED committee urges schools to document their projects from the beginning with pictures and text.<p>

<h4>
Summer Internships<br>
High School Jr. and Sr.<p>
</h4>
For the past six years, ILEED has provided ten high school students throughout the state the opportunity to work as paid energy/environmental professionals.  These interns work for organizations in their communities on a variety of projects involving energy auditing, recycling, utility issues, environmental issues, etc.  Application information, brochures and posters are sent to all Illinois high school guidance counselors in late fall.  Any student wishing to participate as an intern or any business wishing to host an intern may contact ILEED.<p>

<h4>
Camp Keep<br>
Grades 5-8<p>
</h4>
Students participate in a week of energy and environmental discovery at this summer camp led by experienced ILEED students.  Several Illinois teachers attend camp as adult mentors.  High school and college student counselors teach the campers about the energy and the world around them by playing games, hiking, participating in arts and crafts, working on group projects and other fun activities.  The camp is held in Cantrall, IL, just outside of Springfield.  Applications for camp will be sent in the winter ILEED newsletter.  <p>

<h4>
EnergyNet<br>
Grades 7-12<p>
</h4>
EnergyNet has been initiated by a statewide coalition of education, government and business groups to introduce students and teachers to the resources available through telecommunications.  Through EnergyNet, students employ math, science, social studies, computer applications and language arts skills as they investigate solutions to complex energy problems.  A four day energy/auditing and telecommunications institute is provided free of charge for student and teacher teams interested in learning additional technical and leadership skills necessary to audit their school and present their energy findings and recommendations to the school boards.  These schools may be eligible to apply for grant money to fund recommended energy conservation measures.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Advisory Committee</h3>

The success of the ILEED program is attributed to input from teachers and students.  A constant dialogue is maintained with Illinois teaching professionals to determine their priorities, needs and interests.  Illinois teachers have helped develop all major components of the ILEED program and continue to meet annually to improve and update the program.<p>

<hr>
<h3>ILEED Resources</h3>

A fall, winter and spring newsletter is published for K-12 teachers containing updated program information and current events in the energy and environmental field, as well as news about other free energy and environmental education materials available to educators.<p>

<hr>
<h3>'95 EnergyNet Institute</h3>

Over 125 students and teachers from 32 Illinois junior high and high schools participated  in the EnergyNet Institute at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, July 31-August 3, 1995.  EnergyNet began with the question - Is your school wasting energy? - then encouraged students to gather, analyze and share their information electronically with other students.<p>

Divided into eight teams of 20, students and teachers spent the week taking basic energy courses and using EnergyNet databases to compare and contrast their school's energy use with that of other schools in the "mock" Cyber7 School District.  At the end of the Institute, each team recommended cost saving, energy conservation measures to the Cyber7 School Board.  The results were amazing.<p>

Recognition for their work culminates at the EnergyNet Conference in Springfield on March 1, 1996.  Students will display their projects at the Illinois State Capitol.<p>

<hr>
<h3>'95 Camp Keep News</h3>

Campers and staff shared a lot of good times while learning about energy and land management at Camp KEEP '95.  Here's some thoughts from the campers:<p>

<strong>On the Camp Field Trip:</strong> On Wednesday Camp KEEP went on a field trip.  First we went to a farm where a farmer told us how he uses his and other people's yard waste to fertilize his field.  He showed us a machine that mixes it all up.  After he finished talking,  he gave us all sodas.  Next we went to another farm where we hauled wood chip mulch and put it around trees.  Third, we went to a park.  Everyone acted weird and had fun.  After everyone worked up an appetite, we ate lunch.  Last of all we went to the zoo.  We split up into different groups and walked around.  Campers learned how land management effects animals.  The best part of the trip was that we got to fide in a bus that was painted like an ear of corn.  It was a special city bus that ran on ethanol instead of gasoline.<p>

by: Kirk Wilson  Kell, IL<p>

<strong>On some of the activities:</strong> There were four different activities that we got to do in the New Horizons group.  They were Making Paper, Friendship Bracelets, Word Sort and Problem Solving!  Making paper was cool!  There is a white paper pulp like forest paper pulp.  All of the paper turned out good, even some people think they are so good they are going to write home with them.  Friendship bracelets were awesome!  We learned to tie or braid string into great bracelets.  Everybody spent their free time working on these as gifts.  A lot were given to "secret campers".<p>

by: Mandy Voigts  Bloomington, IL<p>

<HR>
