<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs</h3>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/tl.gif" alt="Trade Leader" width=572 height=100></center>

<center><font size=+3>Winter 1996</font></center>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>

<HR>
<h3><center>The International Business Newsletter for the State of Illinois</center></h3>
<hr>
<h3>SEPTEMBER 1995 MEDICAL EQUIPMENT ASIA MISSION SUMMARY</h3>

The Department of Commerce and Community Affairs International Business Division represented 12 companies in New Zealand, Australia, Malaysia, Thailand, Korea and Japan in September 1995. A variety of small and mid-size manufacturers participated which provided a range of products and technologies to promote on site at each country stop. Laboratory optics, x-ray equipment, biohazard waste, emergency care, surgical tools, and products for the handicapped exemplify the diversity of the exhibition. The mission, referred to as Medical Equipment Asia, generated 546 sales leads for the group of Illinois firms and was a success for all involved.<p>

Prior to departing on the Mission, invitations were sent to major hospital groups and pre-screened companies in the medical/scientific fields from the active database files of the International Business Division's Hong Kong and North Asia/Tokyo offices. This promotional campaign initiated enormous interest among the medical communities at each stop. Some companies have already identified serious distributors for their products and several companies are following up on immediate sales opportunities. All of the Illinois companies realize that there is a market in Asia for their products. The mission provided the directive and contacts necessary to begin entry into Asia's most dynamic markets. In addition, mission participants were educated on the process of doing business in the Pacific Rim and collected valuable data for long term market strategies. With a little patience, perseverance and preparation all of them will be able to determine a road to success.<p>

Why Asia? Asia is the fastest growing region in the world for medical equipment and supplies. By the year 2000, the economies of East Asia, from Japan to Malaysia, will almost equal that of the United States. As purchasing power is boosted by swift economic growth, Asians are demanding more and better medical care. The quantity of simple and sophisticated medical goods required to meet this demand provides a serious opportunity for Illinois medical device companies. Sales of quality medical devices are expected to increase to keep pace with more affluent lifestyles and aging populations.<p>

Entering the markets of the Far East can be intimidating at first, but it is impossible to ignore the vast amount of opportunity and the demands for high end medical care. Moving into the future, the companies that develop a long term commitment to the Asian marketplace will reap significant benefits. If conservative assumptions about GNP growth hold true, the East Asian economy will surpass $6 trillion by the year 2000. By the year 2000, less than five percent of the population of East Asia will be classified below the poverty line. One billion Asians will live in households with consumer spending power, and over 400 million of them will be as rich as their western counterparts. Asia is simply too vast a market to ignore.<p>

<em>Margaret MacLean, Managing Director, International Business Division</em>

<hr>

<center><h4>January 8, 1996 - Press Release from the Office of the Governor-Springfield, Illinois </h4></center>

<h3>DCCA RECEIVES GRANT FOR EXPORT DEVELOPMENT</h3>

Governor Edgar announced that the state has been awarded a $450,000 grant by the U.S. Department of Commerce for export development. "Exporting is one of Illinois' greatest economic strengths," the Governor said. "We manufacture products that are in demand in the global marketplace, and one in eight Illinois jobs is dependant on exporting. It is crucial that Illinois continues to expand and explore markets which have untapped potential. This grant will help Illinois businesses identify those markets and sell their products in foreign markets that are emerging as significant trading partners with our state." <p>

The grant awarded to the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs is one of only eight Market Development Cooperator Program competitive grants awarded this year by the U.S. Department of Commerce for export development. Lt. Governor Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development, said the program DCCA will implement with the grant stresses the importance of cooperation. "This program is an intergovernmental private/public partnership," Kustra said. "The Illinois Manufacturers Association, the Illinois State Chamber of Commerce and The Chicagoland Chamber of Commerce supported our proposal and will promote the services to be offered to their members and other interested companies. Small and medium size businesses, in particular, will benefit from the extensive assistance we will be able to provide with this grant."<p>

The program will assist Illinois firms in the targeted industries of environmental, health and information technologies. The markets to be targeted are China, Mexico, Poland, South Africa, South Korea and Turkey.<p> 

Marketing Assistance will be offered at three levels:<p>

<ul>
<li><em>State Level</em> - Trade and Catalog shows for export ready companies will be organized by DCCA's International Buisness Division. The IBD is also responsible for the overall administration of the program.<p>
<li><em>Regional Level</em> - Seminars on market opportunities and exporting training for new-to-export and new-to-market companies will be provided by Illinois' four regional International Trade Centers, which are located in Glen Ellyn, Peoria, Champaign-Urbana and Edwardsville.<p>
<li><em>Local Level</em> - Electronic database development for trade show recruitment and follow-up matching for new-to-export and export ready companies in Chicago will be provided by the City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development Office of International Affairs.<p>
</ul>

<em>For more information contact:</em>  Tom Hagle, DCCA-IBD, 312/814-4959; TDD, 800/419-0667.<p>



<hr>
<h3>1996 GOVERNOR'S EXPORT AWARDS</h3>

Acknowledging exports as a vital component of the Illinois economy is an important factor for continued economic growth. The Governor's Export Awards were created to recognize and encourage small and medium sized Illinois exporters as well as organizations which work to promote export awareness for Illinois products. Signed into law (Senate Bill 269) by Governor Jim Edgar in 1993, the Governor's Export Award program is designed to highlight the significance of Illinois in the world marketplace. <p>

Currently in its third year, DCCA is administering the awards program as part of the agency's overall strategy to promote business expansion into global markets. Small and mid-size enterprises were responsible for more than one-third of total merchandise exports in 1994 and play a crucial role in driving the next generation of U.S. jobs. Companies that are competing to overcome the "export gap" should apply for this prestigous award. Deadline for application is March 29, 1996; and presentation of the Awards will take place on May 16, 1996, at the Crossing International Borders Annual Conference. The conference is jointly sponsored by DCCA's International Business Division and Arthur Andersen and will be held at the Chicago Hilton and Towers.<p>

Awards will be given for outstanding achievement in global competition in the following three categories:<p>

1)  New to Export (honoring companies that have successfully exported Illinois products for one to five years); <p> 

2) Continuing Exporting Excellence (honoring companies that have successfully exported for more than five years); and<p> 

3)  Export Awareness and Development (honoring not-for-profit organizations involved in the promotion of Illinois exporting and raising export awareness).<p>

Winners are selected each year by the Governor's Export Award Review committee comprised of a representative for the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, the Illinois Department of Agriculture, and Illinois based trade organizations and firms experienced in international business. Applications will be judged on export sales as a percentage of total company sales, growth of export sales, number of employees involved in export sales, and distinct factors indicating progressive international marketing strategies.<p>

For information on obtaining a Governor's Export Award application or for information regarding the Crossing International Borders Conference to be held on May 16, 1996, at the Chicago Hilton and Towers, please contact Patty Makropoulos of the International Business Division at 312/814-5713; TDD, 800/419-0667.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Mexican Manufacturing Week Great Lake States Pavilion, June 11-14, 1996</h3>

The Great Lake States and Provinces have joined to form a pavilion at this premier exhibition for manufacturing and automation, control design, design engineering, and plant engineering and maintenance. In its third consecutive year, Mexican Manufacturing Week is established on the same format as the highly successful national Manufacturing Week held in Chicago annually. The Great Lake States Pavilion at Mexican Manufacturing Week will provide Illinois manufacturers of industrial machinery and machine tools, as well as engineering firms, an outstanding avenue to gain exposure to potential clients in these important Mexican markets.<p>

<em>Contact:</em>  Mary Anne Brown-Rogerio<br>
<em>Telephone:</em>  312/814-2089<br>
<em>TDD:</em>  800/419-0667<br>
<em>Fax:</em>  312/814-6581<br>


