<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Community Development Programs</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>Programs and Services</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>

<CENTER><H2>Community Development Programs</H2></CENTER>
<HR>

<H3><a href="../commasst/afffin.htm"> Affordable Financing of Public Infrastructure Program</a></H3>
<DL><DD>
     Provides financial assistance to local governments, public entities,
     medical facilities and public health clinics to help make affordable
     the financing of public infrastructure improvements needed to ensure
     health, safety and economic development in a community.<P>

     For information call 217/785-6142.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3><a href="../../menus/cdasst.htm"> Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP)</a></H3>
<DL><DD>
     A federally-funded program that assists smaller Illinois local
     governments in financing public facilities, housing rehabilitation
     projects or economic development needs.  Grants are made to units of
     local government and may be used for improvements to public
     infrastructure that directly support economic development.  Grant
     funds may also be awarded to communities that utilize the funds to
     make loans to businesses for projects that will create or retain
     jobs in the community.  Under the public facilities component, grants
     are provided to assist communities with planning, engineering and
     construction costs associated with public works improvements.  Under
     the housing component, grants are provided to communities to assist
     with rehabilitating substandard housing.  CDAP grants may also be
     provided to assist with emergency public facilities needs and to help
     communities meet accessibility standards.  The program is limited to
     communities with populations under 50,000 that are not located within
     one of the seven large urban counties that receive funds directly from
     the federal government.  Funds are targeted toward projects that
     primarily benefit low- and moderate-income people.<P>

     For information call 217/785-6142.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3><a href="../commasst/hometown.htm"> Governor's Home Town Awards Program</a></H3>
<DL><DD>
     Annually recognizes the outstanding contributions volunteers make to
     the betterment of their communities.<P>

     For information call 217/785-6142.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>Competitive Communities Initiative (CCI)</H3>
<DL><DD>
     Based on the belief that development occurs at the local level, CCI
     helps participating communities move through five "stages" toward
     competitiveness. Communities are assigned DCCA staffers who work with
     local leaders to help them assess community strengths and weaknesses
     and assist them in identifying private and governmental agencies that
     can provide technical skills, funding mechanisms and other assistance.<P>

     For information call 217/785-6142.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>Training and Technical Assistance for Local Governments</H3>
<DL><DD>
     DCCA provides direct and indirect training workshops to local
     government officials to help them more effectively utilize local
     resources in achieving short-term and long-range objectives.  Training
     and technical assistance services consist of identification of revenue
     and property tax resources, procedures to develop and manage
     government budgets, identification of means to finance public
     infrastructure projects, procedures to revise utility rates and other
     general financial management topics.<P>

     For information call 217/785-3263 (central Illinois), 312/814-6696
     (Chicago  metropolitan area) or 618/993-7234 (Southern Illinois).<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3><a href="../commasst/eprise.htm"> Enterprise Zone Program</a></H3>
<DL><DD>
     Offers a number of state and local tax incentives to businesses that
     make investments to create or retain jobs in any of the 91 certified
     zones located in communities throughout the state.  Eligibility varies
     according to specific incentive requirements.<P>

     For information call 217/785-6142.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>Tax Increment Financing Program</H3>
<DL><DD>
     A municipal financing technique that may be used to renovate declining
     areas or redevelop blighted areas while improving the tax base of such
     areas.  The program allows a municipality to acquire and prepare
     property for redevelopment and make needed public (and some private)
     improvements.<P>

     For information call 217/785-6142.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>Illinois Commission on Community Service</H3>
<DL><DD>
     Serves as state Office of Volunteerism.  Federally funded, the
     Commission is guided by a 25-member commission of representatives from
     education, government, non-profit organizations and businesses.
     Promotes and supports community service and volunteerism, stimulates
     new community service initiatives, serves as a resource and advocate
     for community service agencies, volunteers and programs.  Administers
     the National Service AmeriCorps programs in Illinois, funds Community
     -Based Learn and Serve programs, manages a resource center, provides
     technical assistance for start-up of volunteer programs, encourages
     volunteerism in schools, hosts workshops.<P>

     For information call 312/814-5225 or 800/592-9896.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com">DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/programs.htm">Programs & Services</A> |</STRONG>
</BODY>
</HTML>
