<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Proposed Rules - November 1, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>Proposed Rules</font>
<hr>

<CENTER>
The proposed rules marked with an * are of particular interest to small
business and the department specifically requests comments on those issues.
Comments on any rule are encouraged.<P>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<h3 align=center>
Illinois Register<BR>
November 1, 1996
</h3>
<hr>

<h4>DEPARTMENT OF CORRECTIONS</h4>

<strong><em>County Jail Standards</em></strong> - Based on input from county sheriffs, standards have been updated; flexibility provided, juvenile issues addressed.<p>

<hr>
<h4>STATE BOARD OF ELECTIONS</h4>

<strong><em>Registration of Voters</em></strong> - Rules to implement the National Voter Registration Act of 1993.  (Federal) (New) (Emergency)  Hearings:  November 25, 1040 S. Spring, Springfield (Board meeting starts at 11:00; hearing likely held after lunch); December 17, Thompson Center - call 312-814-6477 for location and time.<p>

<hr>
<strong>POLLUTION CONTROL BOARD</strong><p>

<strong><em>Definitions and General Provisions</em></strong> - Updates federal amendments to add perchloroethylene (tetrachloroethylene) to the list of exempt compounds under the definition of volatile organic compound.  (Federal pass-through) (R96-16)  Hearing:  November 20, Thompson Center, Suite 11-500, 1:30pm.<p>

<hr>
<strong>DEPARTMENT OF REVENUE</strong><p>

<strong><em>Charitable Games Act*</em></strong> - Amends definitions, licenses, supplier's licenses, provider's licenses, operations, restrictions and limitations.<p>

<strong><em>Retailers' Occupation Tax*</em></strong> - Businesses making infrastructure repairs that are a result of a state or federally-declared disaster are exempt from tangible personal property tax as long as the property continues to be used for repairs and in a non-exempt manner.<p>

<strong><em>Service Occupation Tax*</em></strong> -  Same premise as above.<p>



