<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Horse Meat License</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I. Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Horse Meat License
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Agriculture<BR>
Bureau of Animal Welfare<BR>
P.O. Box 19281<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9281<BR>
(217) 782-6657<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 635/1-18.  (Illinois Horse Meat Act)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A license is required manufacture pet foods that use equine meat, operate a zoo, and to produce fur bearing animals.  The license authorizes businesses to slaughter equine animals and use the meat in combination with other food products to produce animal foods. Anyone in violation of this Act shall be guilty of a Class A misdemeanor.  The license is valid for one year.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V. Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Interested persons must complete and file with the Department a "Horse Meat License" application. If applicant is a corporation, the application must list all holders of more than 5% of the stock.  The Department will inspect the proposed facility before a license may be issued.<P>  

If the facility doesn't pass inspection, the applicant may enter into a Work Progress Agreement with the Department.  (A Work Progress Agreement describes the specific things that must be done to satisfy Department inspection requirements.)  Usually, the licensing process takes about 30 days.  Denied applications may be appealed under the terms of the Administrative Review Law.<P>  
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The business shall be run in a sanitary manner.   Every package of horse meat ready for distribution must be plainly labeled as such.<P> 

The Secretary of a licensed corporation must notify the Bureau of Animal Welfare of any changes in the listing of the stockholders holding more than 5% of the stock of the corporation.)<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The fee for a license is $50 for each location if the horse meat is for resale.  The fee for a license is $10 if it is for a breeder and raiser for their own use.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
