<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Inspection of Weights & Measures Devices</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>


<H3>I.   Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Inspection of Weights & Measures Devices
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Agriculture<BR>
Bureau of Weights & Measures<BR>
State Fairgrounds, P.O.Box 19281<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9281<BR>
(217) 785-8252<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
470 Illinois Compiled Statues Section 10  (Weights & Measures Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Title 8 Illinois Administrative Code, Chapter I, Subpart D, Section 600.350-380.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. 	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
All weighing and measuring devices used for commercial purposes must be inspected by the Department once each year.  Devices that meet the prescribed requirements are certified with a state decal.<P>

The purpose of inspections is to assure that the weight and measuring devices are correct.<P>

Use of an uninspected or unapproved weight or measuring device is a business offense and subject a fine of $500 for the first offense, up to $1,500 for the second, and at least $2,500 	for the third. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The Department must be notified whenever a new device is installed.  The Department then establishes dates for original or subsequent inspections the site location. If a device does not pass the inspection, a rejection or condemnation tag is affixed to the device and it must be repaired within ten days or removed from service.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. 	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Businesses must allow Department inspectors access to any place where a device is used. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. 	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The following fees are due and payable at the time of such inspection:<P>

A.  Scales (by capacity, except for animal (designed for weighing single head), livestock, and railroad track):<P>
<DL><DD>
1.)  0-300 pounds	$2.			<BR>
2.)  301-2,000 pounds	$7.50<BR>	
3.)  2,001-10,000 pounds	$25.<BR>
4.)  10,001 pounds and over	$50.<P>
</DD></DL>
B.  Railroad Track Scales (per hour):	$10.<P>

C.  Use of State Scale Trucks (Charges to the repairman for use of state scale trucks and weights per hour only during working hours): $50.<P>

D.  Livestock Scales:	$50.<P>

E.  Motor Fuel:<P>
<DL><DD>
1.) Motor Fuel Pumps:  $4<BR>
2.) Blender Pumps:	$7.50<BR>
3.) Adjustment Insp. (Additional):  $6.<P>
</DD></DL>
F.  Motor Fuel Meters (includes vehicle tank and stationary meters):<P>
<DL><DD>
1.)  Meters to and including 2 3/4 in:   $20.<BR>
2.)  Meters greater than 2 3/4 in.: $50.<P>
</DD></DL>
G.  Calibration:  <BR>
<DL><DD>
	1.)  Calibrating for capacity a vehicle tank for each 1,000 gallons or fraction thereof:  $10.<BR>
	2.)  Calibrating Commercial Providing Devices per hour or portion thereof, min charge:  $25.<P>
</DD></DL>
H.  LPG Meters (Liquid Petroleum Gas-Liquid):  $50.<P>

I.  Grain Moisture Measuring Devices:  $15.<P>

J.  Laboratory Fee: <P>
<DL><DD>
	1.)  Lab Charge $25 / hour or portion thereof, minimum charge: $25.<BR>
	2.)  Precision work per hour: $40.<BR>
</DD></DL>
</DD></DL>
<HR>
